{"title_page": "Georgia State Route 141", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n| state = GA\n| type = SR\n| route = 141\n| map = Georgia state route 141 map.png\n| length_mi = 28.0\n| length_ref = <ref name=\"Google\">{{Google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=Peachtree+Rd+NW&daddr=33.9157415,-84.2846256+to:33.948452,-84.2353712+to:GA-141+N%2FPeachtree+Pkwy&hl=en&ll=34.011689,-84.230804&spn=0.605602,0.883026&sll=33.91758,-84.277582&sspn=0.037892,0.055189&geocode=FY9ZBAIdjnf4-g%3BFV2DBQIdL-v5-ilnDJ3A7gn1iDH82w3QFE6EPw%3BFSQDBgIdlav6-inbdcdQ3KD1iDG6YmMyBuKqew%3BFdo_CQId4Jz7-g&oq=Cumm&dirflg=h&mra=dpe&mrsp=1&sz=14&via=1,2&t=m&z=10|title=Route of SR&nbsp;141|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n| length_round = 1\n| established = \n| direction_a = South\n| direction_b = North\n| terminus_a = {{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|9}} in [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]\n| junction = {{jct|state=GA|SR|237}} in [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]<br>{{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Atlanta}} in [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|13|dab1=Doraville}} in [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|I|285}} in [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|SR|140}} in [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]<br>\nPeachtree Industrial Boulevard in [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|SR|120}} in [[Johns Creek, Georgia|Johns Creek]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|400}} southwest of [[Cumming, Georgia|Cumming]]\n| terminus_b = {{jct|state=GA|SR|9}} southwest of Cumming\n| counties = [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb]], [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett]], [[Forsyth County, Georgia|Forsyth]]\n| previous_type = SR\n| previous_route = 140\n| next_type = SR\n| next_route = 142\n}}\n'''State Route 141''' ('''SR&nbsp;141''') is a {{convert|28.0|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[State highway (US)|state highway]] that runs southwest-to-northeast in the [[Northwest Georgia|northwest part]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. It connects the [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]] area of [[Atlanta]] with [[Cumming, Georgia|Cumming]]. Its routing exists within portions of [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb]], [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett]], [[Forsyth County, Georgia|Forsyth]] [[County (United States)|counties]].\n\n==Route description==\n[[File:GA State Route 141 in Peachtree Corners.jpg|thumb|State Route 141 in [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]]]\nSR&nbsp;141 begins at an [[Intersection (road)|intersection]] with [[U.S. Route 19 in Georgia|US&nbsp;19]]/[[Georgia State Route 9|SR&nbsp;9]] (Roswell Road NE) in the [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead neighborhood]] of [[Atlanta]], in [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]. It travels to the northeast to an intersection with [[Georgia State Route 237|SR&nbsp;237]] (Piedmont Road NE). Just after that intersection, it goes over, but does not have an [[Interchange (road)|interchange]] with [[Georgia State Route 400|SR&nbsp;400]] (T. Harvey Mathis Parkway). Immediately after is the southern terminus of [[Georgia State Route 141 Connector (Atlanta)|SR&nbsp;141 Connector]] (Lenox Road NE). The highway passes just northwest of the Buckhead Heights neighborhood, crosses into [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]], and passes through [[Brookhaven, Georgia|Brookhaven]]. SR&nbsp;141 passes [[Oglethorpe University]] and the Peachtree Golf Club, just before passing through [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]]. In [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]], it has an intersection with [[Georgia State Route 13 Connector (Doraville)|SR&nbsp;13 Connector]] and an interchange with [[Interstate 285 (Georgia)|Interstate 285]] (I-285). The road becomes a freeway on the northeast of the interchange, served by a pair of [[one-way traffic|one-way]] [[frontage road]]s with \"[[Texas U-turn]]s\"; it has a few exits along its length. It enters [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett County]] near the middle of the freeway; near the end of the freeway is [[Georgia State Route 140|SR&nbsp;140]]. It passes through [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]. Then, it crosses over the [[Chattahoochee River]] back into Fulton County. It travels through [[Johns Creek, Georgia|Johns Creek]] and meets [[Georgia State Route 120|SR&nbsp;120]] (Abbotts Bridge Road). Northeast of there, it enters [[Forsyth County, Georgia|Forsyth County]]. The roadway curves to the northwest and then to the north. It has an interchange with US&nbsp;19/SR&nbsp;400 (Hospitality Highway), southwest of [[Cumming, Georgia|Cumming]]. Just after this interchange, it meets its northern terminus, an intersection with SR&nbsp;9 (Atlanta Highway).<ref name=\"Google\"/>\n\nAll of SR&nbsp;141 from its southern terminus in Buckhead to a point southwest of [[Duluth, Georgia|Duluth]] is part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], a system of roadways important to the nation's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=\"NHS Georgia\">{{cite web|title=National Highway System: Georgia|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/nhs_maps/georgia/ga_georgia.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=United States Department of Transportation|date=October 1, 2012|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=GA|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Fulton\n|cspan=3\n|location=Atlanta\n|lspan=3\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|9|name2=Roswell Road NE|city2=Sandy Springs|road=Paces Ferry Road}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.6\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|237|name1=Piedmont Road NE}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=1.3\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Atlanta|dir1=north|name1=Lenox Road NE|to2=to|GA|400|road=Monarch Drive / Ritz Drive / Phipps Drive}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of SR&nbsp;141 Conn.\n}}{{GAint|county=Dekalb|location=Doraville|lspan=3|mile=7.4|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|13|dab1=Doraville|name1=Motors Industrial Way}}|cspan=3}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=7.6\n|road={{jct|state=GA|I|285|name1=Atlanta Bypass / [[Georgia State Route 407|SR&nbsp;407]]|location1=[[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]|city2=Marietta|location3=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]]}}\n|notes=I-285, exit 31; southern end of freeway\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=8.4\n|road=Tilly Mill Road -  [[Georgia State University]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county1=DeKalb\n|county2=Gwinnett\n|location1=Doraville\n|location2=Peachtree Corners\n|location_group=city\n|mile=9.5\n|road=Winters Chapel Road / Amwiler Road\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Gwinnett\n|cspan=5\n|location=Peachtree Corners\n|lspan=5\n|mile=10.6\n|road=Jones Mill Road - Peachtree Corners Circle\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=11.2\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|140|name1=Jimmy Carter Boulevard|city1=Roswell|city2=Tucker}}\n|notes=No northern entrance|type=incomplete}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=11.6\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Gwinnett County|dir1=north|to1=yes|road=Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|city1=Duluth}}\n|notes=Northern end of freeway; northbound exit, southbound entrance\n}}{{GAint|road=Holcomb Bridge Road|mile=11.9|notes=Northern terminus of SR 141 Conn.}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=13.5\n|road=[[Spalding Drive]]}}\n{{GAint|mile=17.1|location=Johns Creek|lspan=3|county=Fulton|cspan=2|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=State Bridge Road|location1=[[Gwinnett Medical Center-Duluth]]}}}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=19.5\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|120|name1=Abbotts Bridge Road|city1=Alpharetta|city2=Duluth}}\n}}{{GAint|county1=Fulton|county2=Forsyth|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=McGinnis Ferry Road|location1=[[Emory Healthcare]] Johns Creek Hospital}}|mile=21.0}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Forsyth\n|cspan=2\n|location=none\n|mile=27.7\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|400|name2=Hospitality Highway|location1=[[Atlanta]]|city2=Dahlonega}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|location=none\n|mile=28.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|9|name1=Atlanta Highway|city1=Milton|city2=Cumming}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete}}\n\n==Related routes==\n===Atlanta connector route===\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=GA\n|type=SR\n|subtype=Connector\n|route=141\n|location=[[Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]\n|length_mi=0.9\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google Atlanta Conn\">{{Google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=Unknown+road&daddr=Lenox+Rd+NE&hl=en&ll=33.850833,-84.368026&spn=0.00948,0.013797&sll=33.850711,-84.361979&sspn=0.001194,0.001725&geocode=FVGFBAIdDb34-g%3BFe58BAIdNY34-g&oq=Bro&dirflg=h&mra=dme&mrsp=0&sz=19&t=m&z=16 |title=Overview map of SR&nbsp;141 Conn. (Atlanta) |access-date=June 28, 2013 }}</ref>\n|established=\n}}\n\n'''State Route&nbsp;141 Connector''' ('''SR&nbsp;141 Conn.''') is a {{convert|0.9|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Connector (road)|connecting route]] of SR&nbsp;141 that exists entirely within the [[Buckhead]] section of [[Atlanta]], in eastern [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]. It is known as '''Lenox Road NE''', as well as [[Paul Coverdell]] Memorial Parkway, for its entire length. It was built in the early 1990s in conjunction with [[Georgia State Route 400|SR&nbsp;400]] to serve area businesses and offices.\n\nIt begins at an [[Intersection (road)|intersection]] with the SR&nbsp;141 mainline (Peachtree Road NE) just northwest of the Buckhead Heights neighborhood of Atlanta. The highway heads northwest, curves to the west-southwest underneath, where it crosses SR&nbsp;400 (T. Harvey Mathis Parkway) with a [[single-point urban interchange]]. It curves to the southwest to meet its northern terminus, an intersection with [[Georgia State Route 237|SR&nbsp;237]] (Piedmont Road NE), at the [[Buckhead Forest]] neighborhood of Atlanta.<ref name=\"Google Atlanta Conn\"/>\n\nSR&nbsp;141 Conn. is not part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], a system of roadways important to the nation's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=\"NHS Georgia\"/>\n\n{{jcttop|state=GA|county=Fulton|location=Atlanta|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|name1=Peachtree Road NE|city1=Chamblee|nolink1=y}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|dir1=north|to1=yes|road=Monarch Drive / Ritz Drive / Phipps Drive}}|notes=Interchange with left exit and entrance in each direction|mile=.1}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|400|city1=Atlanta|city2=Dahlonega}}|notes=[[Single-point urban interchange]]|mile=.5}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.9\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|237|name1=Piedmont Road NE}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n\n===Gwinnett County connector route===\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=GA\n|type=SR\n|subtype=Connector\n|route=141\n|location=West of [[Norcross, Georgia|Norcross]]\n|length_mi=0.8\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google GwinnettCounty Conn\">{{Google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/33.9436958,-84.2403193/33.9502545,-84.2351817/@33.9475041,-84.241007,16z/am=t/data=!3m1!4b1!4m3!4m2!3e0!5i1 |title=Overview map of SR&nbsp;141 Conn. (Gwinnett County) |access-date=March 5, 2017 }}</ref>\n|established=\n}}'''State Route 141 Connector (SR 141 Conn.)''' is a .8 mile long (1.3 km) connecting route of SR 141 that exists entirely within [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett County]]. It is just west of [[Norcross, Georgia|Norcross]]. The route at [[Georgia State Route 140|SR 140]] (Jimmy Carter Boulevard) and goes north along a [[frontage road]] parallel to SR 141/Peachtree Industrial Boulevard. After the split of SR 141 and Peachtree Industrial Boulevard, SR 141 Conn. merges with Peachtree Industrial Boulevard. The route then turns left onto Holcomb Bridge Road and ends at the intersection of Holcomb Bridge Road and SR 141. The route connects traffic from SR 140 to SR 141 north, since there is no direct entrance ramp between these two roads. SR 141 Conn. south does not exist because traffic can exit from SR 141 south directly to SR 140. \n\n{{jcttop|state=GA|county=Gwinnett|location=Peachtree Corners|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|140|name1=Jimmy Carter Boulevard}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}{{GAint|road=Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|notes=|mile=.3}}{{GAint|road=Holcomb Bridge Road / Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|notes=|mile=.6}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.8\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|name1=Peachtree Parkway}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}{{-}}\n\n===Peachtree Industrial Boulevard===\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=GA\n|type=\n|name=Peachtree Industrial Boulevard\n|location=[[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]]\u2013[[Buford, Georgia|Buford]]\n|length_mi=25.4\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google PIB\">{{https://www.google.com/maps/@34.0308926,-84.1783876,13z}}</ref>\n|established=\n}}\n\n'''Peachtree Industrial Boulevard''' is a road in the U.S. state of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] that begins in [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]] and ends in [[Buford, Georgia|Buford]]. Between [[Interstate 285 (Georgia)|Interstate 285]] and [[Georgia State Route 140|SR&nbsp;140]] (Jimmy Carter Boulevard), the road is concurrent with SR 141. North of SR 140, in Peachtree Corners, Peachtree Industrial Boulevard splits from SR 141 and continues to the northeast as a highway with at least four lanes and center median, traveling through the cities of [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]], [[Duluth, Georgia|Duluth]], [[Suwanee, Georgia|Suwanee]], [[Sugar Hill, Georgia|Sugar Hill]], and Buford. The portion of the road concurrent with SR 141 is maintained by the state; the rest is maintained by Gwinnett County.<ref name=\"City of Duluth\">{{cite web |title=Street Maintenance |url=http://www.duluthga.net/departments/public_works/street_maintenance.php |publisher=City of Duluth |access-date=December 29, 2013 }}</ref> \n\nPeachtree Industrial Boulevard was originally built in the 1960s. The portion of the road concurrent to SR 141 was upgraded to a [[Limited-access road|limited-access highway]] in the 1980s and 1990s. \n\nIn 2008, the section within the city limits of [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]] was renamed to Peachtree Boulevard, to reflect the changing nature of the city. <ref>https://atlanta.curbed.com/2015/1/30/9997144/peachtree-industrial-boulevard-and-the-new-chamblee</ref> Prior to this change, the \"industrial\" name extended until Peachtree Road merges in near the city line with present-day [[Brookhaven, Georgia|Brookhaven]]. In November 2018, the [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]] City Council passed a resolution to authorize the city manager to rename Peachtree Industrial Boulevard within the city limits to Peachtree Boulevard, following the changes made by Chamblee. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/major-dekalb-road-could-see-name-change-the-future/t6SFStrC6mUbI7MJ8VpQFI/|title=Major DeKalb road could see name change in the future|last=Habersham|first=Raisa|date=November 8, 2018|website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> However, these changes have not yet taken place.\n\nIn 2013, Gwinnett County decreased the speed limit the road to 45 mph between SR 141 (Peachtree Parkway) and [[Georgia State Route 20|SR 20]] (Nelson Brogdon Boulevard) and 50 mph between SR 20 and the [[Hall County, Georgia|Hall County]] line. The goal of the change was to reduce speeding and accidents. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwinnettcounty.com/web/gwinnett/Home/Stories/ViewStory?story=New%20speed%20limits%20along%20Peachtree%20Industrial%20Boulevard|title=New speed limits along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|last=|first=|date=September 11, 2013|website=www.gwinnettcounty.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, the Atlanta Regional Commission Board approved funding to equip intersections along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard with connected vehicle technology. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantaregional.org/news/press-releases/arc-board-approves-69-million-in-transportation-projects-across-gwinnett-county/|title=ARC Board Approves $69 Million in Transportation Projects across Gwinnett County|date=2018-06-27|website=ARC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nGwinnett County has looked at adding and improving sidewalks along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard. <ref>https://www.gwinnettcounty.com/static/departments/boc/pdf/2017%20SPLOST%20Transportation%20Projects.pdf</ref>\n\nThe [[Western Gwinnett Bikeway]] is a multi-use trail under construction along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard.{{jcttop|state=GA|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}{{GAint|county=Dekalb|location=Doraville|lspan=3|mile=0.0|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|13|dab1=Doraville|SR|141|name1=Motors Industrial Way|name2=Peachtree Boulevard|city1=Chamblee}}|cspan=3|type=concur|notes=Southern terminus; southern end of concurrency with SR 141; road continues as SR 141/Peachtree Boulevard}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.2\n|road={{jct|state=GA|I|285|name1=Atlanta Bypass / [[Georgia State Route 407|SR&nbsp;407]]|location1=[[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]|city2=Marietta|location3=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]]}}\n|notes=I-285, exit 31; southern end of freeway\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=1.0\n|road=Tilly Mill Road -  [[Georgia State University]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county1=DeKalb\n|county2=Gwinnett\n|location1=Doraville\n|location2=Peachtree Corners\n|location_group=city\n|mile=2.1\n|road=Winters Chapel Road / Amwiler Road\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Gwinnett\n|cspan=11\n|location=Peachtree Corners\n|lspan=4\n|mile=3.2\n|road=Jones Mill Road - Peachtree Corners Circle\n|notes=No southbound exit; SR 141 southbound exit via SR 140 exit\n|type=incomplete}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=3.8\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|140|name1=Jimmy Carter Boulevard|city1=Roswell|city2=Tucker}}\n|notes=No southbound exit|type=incomplete}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=4.2\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|dir1=north|to2=to|GA|400|road=Peachtree Parkway|city1=Cumming|city2=Dahlonega}}\n|notes=Northern end of freeway; northern end of concurrency with SR 141; northbound exit, southbound entrance\n}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Gwinnett County|dir1=north|name1=Holcomb Bridge Road}}|mile=4.5|notes=}}{{GAint|mile=10.3|location=Duluth|lspan=4|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=Pleasant Hill Road|location1=[[Gwinnett Medical Center-Duluth]]}}}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=11.6\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|120|name1=Abbotts Bridge Road / Duluth Highway|city1=Alpharetta|city2=Duluth}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=12.9\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|23|GA|13|name2=Buford Highway|to1=yes|road=Rogers Bridge Road|location1=[[Rogers Bridge Park]]}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=14.0\n|road=Sugarloaf Parkway\n|notes=\n}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=McGinnis Ferry Road|location1=[[Emory Healthcare]] Johns Creek Hospital}}|mile=16.4|location=Suwanee|lspan=2}}{{GAint|road=Suwanee Buford Dam Road &ndash; [[Suwanee, Georgia|Suwanee]]|mile=17.9}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|20|name1=Nelson Brogden Boulevard|city1=Cumming|city2=Lawrenceville}}|mile=21.8|location=Sugar Hill}}{{GAint|road=Cemetery Road / McEver Road|notes=Northern terminus; road continues as McEver Road|mile=25.4|location=Buford|county1=Gwinnett|county2=Hall}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete,concur}}\n\n== Orphaned segments ==\nThere are six road segments that previously carried State Route 141 or a derivative designation that no longer do.\n\n#  What is now Georgia SR 371 once was SR 141 between Georgia SR 9 and SR 20. It was changed to its present number in the early 1970s.\n#  The State Route 141 designation was previously used in DeKalb County between Tucker and US 78 in what is now Stone Mountain Park on what is now Hugh Howell Highway (SR 236) which was at the time named Rosser Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/CountyMapsArchive/DeKalb_1900s.zip|title=Georgia DOT Map Archive, DeKalb County 1900's, 1948 Map|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref>\n# Prior to construction of Peachtree Parkway and the extension and re-routing of SR 141 to Buckhead, SR 141 followed what is present day Medlock Bridge Road from its current intersection with Peachtree Parkway, into downtown Norcross and became North Peachtree Road, crossed the railroad tracks at Park Street, and then traveled on South Peachtree until its terminus at Buford Highway (SR 13). When plans were drawn to re-route SR 141 to its present alignment, GDOT changed the designation of this roadway to SR 141 Connector.  This designation stayed in effect until 1981, when this segment was turned over to the county and converted to local roads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/CountyMapsArchive/Gwinnett_1900s.zip|title=Georgia DOT Map Archive - Gwinnett County 1900's|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> What is now SR 141 between the Buckhead junction with Roswell Road (SR 9) and Motors Industrial Way (present day SR 13 Connector) was designated along with Motors Industrial Way as SR 13W before it was made part of the newly aligned SR 141.\n# With the construction of Interstate 85, Norcross Tucker road, which at the time was a contiguous road, was designated SR 141 Connector, and the small segment of South Peachtree Road between Buford Highway and Norcross Tucker Road was redesigned SR 141 Spur. The South Peachtree Road (SR 141 Spur) was converted to a local road in 1981 along with truncation of SR 141 Connector to Norcross Tucker Road between South Peachtree Rd in Norcross and Interstate 85.\n# As Jimmy Carter Boulevard was constructed in the 1970s, Norcross Tucker Road was split into North Norcross Tucker Road and South Norcross Tucker Road, and a portion of the road was incorporated into Jimmy Carter Boulevard. In 1981, Jimmy Carter Boulevard was designated as SR 141 Connector between Peachtree Industrial Boulevard and Interstate 85.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/CountyMapsArchive/Gwinnett_1900s.zip|title=Georgia DOT Map Archive - Gwinnett County 1900's|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> It was converted to State Route 140 in 1984-1985 timeframe<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/HwyAndTransportationMaps/1984_1985.pdf|title=GDOT State Highway Map 1984-1985|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> and the SR 141 Connector designation was used for what is present day SR 141 Connector at the 141/Peachtree Industrial Boulevard interchange when the Jimmy Carter Boulevard/SR 141 intersection was upgraded to a grade separated intersection.\n#  The 17.5 mile segment of State Route 369 East of '''SR 9''' from North of Cumming to Gainesville was designated as SR 141 until 1970, when it was extended West to SR 20, and redesigned to its present-day number.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/HwyAndTransportationMaps/1970.pdf|title=1970 State Highway Map GDOT|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/HwyAndTransportationMaps/1971.pdf|title=1971 State Highway Map GDOT|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{portal-inline|Georgia (U.S. state)}} \n* {{portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n* [[Peachtree Street|Peachtree Road]]\n* [[Transportation in Atlanta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://georgiaroads.tripod.com/gahwy8.htm Georgia Roads (Routes 141 - 160)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100717222433/http://www.state-ends.com/georgia/014100/ Georgia State Route 141 on State-Ends.com]\n\n[[Category:State highways in Georgia (U.S. state)|141]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Fulton County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in DeKalb County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Gwinnett County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Forsyth County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Brookhaven, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Chamblee, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Doraville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Roads in Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n| state = GA\n| type = SR\n| route = 141\n| map = Georgia state route 141 map.png\n| length_mi = 28.0\n| length_ref = <ref name=\"Google\">{{Google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=Peachtree+Rd+NW&daddr=33.9157415,-84.2846256+to:33.948452,-84.2353712+to:GA-141+N%2FPeachtree+Pkwy&hl=en&ll=34.011689,-84.230804&spn=0.605602,0.883026&sll=33.91758,-84.277582&sspn=0.037892,0.055189&geocode=FY9ZBAIdjnf4-g%3BFV2DBQIdL-v5-ilnDJ3A7gn1iDH82w3QFE6EPw%3BFSQDBgIdlav6-inbdcdQ3KD1iDG6YmMyBuKqew%3BFdo_CQId4Jz7-g&oq=Cumm&dirflg=h&mra=dpe&mrsp=1&sz=14&via=1,2&t=m&z=10|title=Route of SR&nbsp;141|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n| length_round = 1\n| established = \n| direction_a = South\n| direction_b = North\n| terminus_a = {{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|9}} in [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]\n| junction = {{jct|state=GA|SR|237}} in [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]<br>{{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Atlanta}} in [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|13|dab1=Doraville}} in [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|I|285}} in [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|SR|140}} in [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]<br>\nPeachtree Industrial Boulevard in [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|SR|120}} in [[Johns Creek, Georgia|Johns Creek]]<br>\n{{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|400}} southwest of [[Cumming, Georgia|Cumming]]\n| terminus_b = {{jct|state=GA|SR|9}} southwest of Cumming\n| counties = [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb]], [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett]], [[Forsyth County, Georgia|Forsyth]]\n| previous_type = SR\n| previous_route = 140\n| next_type = SR\n| next_route = 142\n}}\n'''State Route 141''' ('''SR&nbsp;141''') is a {{convert|28.0|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[State highway (US)|state highway]] that runs southwest-to-northeast in the [[Northwest Georgia|northwest part]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. It connects the [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]] area of [[Atlanta]] with [[Cumming, Georgia|Cumming]]. Its routing exists within portions of [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]], [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb]], [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett]], [[Forsyth County, Georgia|Forsyth]] [[County (United States)|counties]].\n\n==Route description==\n[[File:GA State Route 141 in Peachtree Corners.jpg|thumb|State Route 141 in [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]]]\nSR&nbsp;141 begins at an [[Intersection (road)|intersection]] with [[U.S. Route 19 in Georgia|US&nbsp;19]]/[[Georgia State Route 9|SR&nbsp;9]] (Roswell Road NE) in the [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead neighborhood]] of [[Atlanta]], in [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]. It travels to the northeast to an intersection with [[Georgia State Route 237|SR&nbsp;237]] (Piedmont Road NE). Just after that intersection, it goes over, but does not have an [[Interchange (road)|interchange]] with [[Georgia State Route 400|SR&nbsp;400]] (T. Harvey Mathis Parkway). Immediately after is the southern terminus of [[Georgia State Route 141 Connector (Atlanta)|SR&nbsp;141 Connector]] (Lenox Road NE). The highway passes just northwest of the Buckhead Heights neighborhood, crosses into [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]], and passes through [[Brookhaven, Georgia|Brookhaven]]. SR&nbsp;141 passes [[Oglethorpe University]] and the Peachtree Golf Club, just before passing through [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]]. In [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]], it has an intersection with [[Georgia State Route 13 Connector (Doraville)|SR&nbsp;13 Connector]] and an interchange with [[Interstate 285 (Georgia)|Interstate 285]] (I-285). The road becomes a freeway on the northeast of the interchange, served by a pair of [[one-way traffic|one-way]] [[frontage road]]s with \"[[Texas U-turn]]s\"; it has a few exits along its length. It enters [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett County]] near the middle of the freeway; near the end of the freeway is [[Georgia State Route 140|SR&nbsp;140]]. It passes through [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]]. Then, it crosses over the [[Chattahoochee River]] back into Fulton County. It travels through [[Johns Creek, Georgia|Johns Creek]] and meets [[Georgia State Route 120|SR&nbsp;120]] (Abbotts Bridge Road). Northeast of there, it enters [[Forsyth County, Georgia|Forsyth County]]. The roadway curves to the northwest and then to the north. It has an interchange with US&nbsp;19/SR&nbsp;400 (Hospitality Highway), southwest of [[Cumming, Georgia|Cumming]]. Just after this interchange, it meets its northern terminus, an intersection with SR&nbsp;9 (Atlanta Highway).<ref name=\"Google\"/>\n\nAll of SR&nbsp;141 from its southern terminus in Buckhead to a point southwest of [[Duluth, Georgia|Duluth]] is part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], a system of roadways important to the nation's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=\"NHS Georgia\">{{cite web|title=National Highway System: Georgia|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/nhs_maps/georgia/ga_georgia.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=United States Department of Transportation|date=October 1, 2012|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=GA|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Fulton\n|cspan=3\n|location=Atlanta\n|lspan=3\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|9|name2=Roswell Road NE|city2=Sandy Springs|road=Paces Ferry Road}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.6\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|237|name1=Piedmont Road NE}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=1.3\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Atlanta|dir1=north|name1=Lenox Road NE|to2=to|GA|400|road=Monarch Drive / Ritz Drive / Phipps Drive}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of SR&nbsp;141 Conn.\n}}{{GAint|county=Dekalb|location=Doraville|lspan=3|mile=7.4|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|13|dab1=Doraville|name1=Motors Industrial Way}}|cspan=3}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=7.6\n|road={{jct|state=GA|I|285|name1=Atlanta Bypass / [[Georgia State Route 407|SR&nbsp;407]]|location1=[[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]|city2=Marietta|location3=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]]}}\n|notes=I-285, exit 31; southern end of freeway\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=8.4\n|road=Tilly Mill Road -  [[Georgia State University]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county1=DeKalb\n|county2=Gwinnett\n|location1=Doraville\n|location2=Peachtree Corners\n|location_group=city\n|mile=9.5\n|road=Winters Chapel Road / Amwiler Road\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Gwinnett\n|cspan=5\n|location=Peachtree Corners\n|lspan=5\n|mile=10.6\n|road=Jones Mill Road - Peachtree Corners Circle\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=11.2\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|140|name1=Jimmy Carter Boulevard|city1=Roswell|city2=Tucker}}\n|notes=No northern entrance|type=incomplete}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=11.6\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Gwinnett County|dir1=north|to1=yes|road=Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|city1=Duluth}}\n|notes=Northern end of freeway; northbound exit, southbound entrance\n}}{{GAint|road=Holcomb Bridge Road|mile=11.9|notes=Northern terminus of SR 141 Conn.}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=13.2\n|road=[[Spalding Drive]]}}\n{{GAint|mile=17.1|location=Johns Creek|lspan=3|county=Fulton|cspan=2|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=State Bridge Road|location1=[[Gwinnett Medical Center-Duluth]]}}}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=19.5\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|120|name1=Abbotts Bridge Road|city1=Alpharetta|city2=Duluth}}\n}}{{GAint|county1=Fulton|county2=Forsyth|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=McGinnis Ferry Road|location1=[[Emory Healthcare]] Johns Creek Hospital}}|mile=21.0}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Forsyth\n|cspan=2\n|location=none\n|mile=27.7\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|19|SR|400|name2=Hospitality Highway|location1=[[Atlanta]]|city2=Dahlonega}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|location=none\n|mile=28.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|9|name1=Atlanta Highway|city1=Milton|city2=Cumming}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete}}\n\n==Related routes==\n===Atlanta connector route===\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=GA\n|type=SR\n|subtype=Connector\n|route=141\n|location=[[Buckhead]], [[Atlanta]]\n|length_mi=0.9\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google Atlanta Conn\">{{Google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=Unknown+road&daddr=Lenox+Rd+NE&hl=en&ll=33.850833,-84.368026&spn=0.00948,0.013797&sll=33.850711,-84.361979&sspn=0.001194,0.001725&geocode=FVGFBAIdDb34-g%3BFe58BAIdNY34-g&oq=Bro&dirflg=h&mra=dme&mrsp=0&sz=19&t=m&z=16 |title=Overview map of SR&nbsp;141 Conn. (Atlanta) |access-date=June 28, 2013 }}</ref>\n|established=\n}}\n\n'''State Route&nbsp;141 Connector''' ('''SR&nbsp;141 Conn.''') is a {{convert|0.9|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Connector (road)|connecting route]] of SR&nbsp;141 that exists entirely within the [[Buckhead]] section of [[Atlanta]], in eastern [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]. It is known as '''Lenox Road NE''', as well as [[Paul Coverdell]] Memorial Parkway, for its entire length. It was built in the early 1990s in conjunction with [[Georgia State Route 400|SR&nbsp;400]] to serve area businesses and offices.\n\nIt begins at an [[Intersection (road)|intersection]] with the SR&nbsp;141 mainline (Peachtree Road NE) just northwest of the Buckhead Heights neighborhood of Atlanta. The highway heads northwest, curves to the west-southwest underneath, where it crosses SR&nbsp;400 (T. Harvey Mathis Parkway) with a [[single-point urban interchange]]. It curves to the southwest to meet its northern terminus, an intersection with [[Georgia State Route 237|SR&nbsp;237]] (Piedmont Road NE), at the [[Buckhead Forest]] neighborhood of Atlanta.<ref name=\"Google Atlanta Conn\"/>\n\nSR&nbsp;141 Conn. is not part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]], a system of roadways important to the nation's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=\"NHS Georgia\"/>\n\n{{jcttop|state=GA|county=Fulton|location=Atlanta|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|name1=Peachtree Road NE|city1=Chamblee|nolink1=y}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|dir1=north|to1=yes|road=Monarch Drive / Ritz Drive / Phipps Drive}}|notes=Interchange with left exit and entrance in each direction|mile=.1}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|400|city1=Atlanta|city2=Dahlonega}}|notes=[[Single-point urban interchange]]|mile=.5}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.9\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|237|name1=Piedmont Road NE}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n\n===Gwinnett County connector route===\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=GA\n|type=SR\n|subtype=Connector\n|route=141\n|location=West of [[Norcross, Georgia|Norcross]]\n|length_mi=0.8\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google GwinnettCounty Conn\">{{Google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/33.9436958,-84.2403193/33.9502545,-84.2351817/@33.9475041,-84.241007,16z/am=t/data=!3m1!4b1!4m3!4m2!3e0!5i1 |title=Overview map of SR&nbsp;141 Conn. (Gwinnett County) |access-date=March 5, 2017 }}</ref>\n|established=\n}}'''State Route 141 Connector (SR 141 Conn.)''' is a .8 mile long (1.3 km) connecting route of SR 141 that exists entirely within [[Gwinnett County, Georgia|Gwinnett County]]. It is just west of [[Norcross, Georgia|Norcross]]. The route at [[Georgia State Route 140|SR 140]] (Jimmy Carter Boulevard) and goes north along a [[frontage road]] parallel to SR 141/Peachtree Industrial Boulevard. After the split of SR 141 and Peachtree Industrial Boulevard, SR 141 Conn. merges with Peachtree Industrial Boulevard. The route then turns left onto Holcomb Bridge Road and ends at the intersection of Holcomb Bridge Road and SR 141. The route connects traffic from SR 140 to SR 141 north, since there is no direct entrance ramp between these two roads. SR 141 Conn. south does not exist because traffic can exit from SR 141 south directly to SR 140. \n\n{{jcttop|state=GA|county=Gwinnett|location=Peachtree Corners|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|140|name1=Jimmy Carter Boulevard}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}{{GAint|road=Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|notes=|mile=.3}}{{GAint|road=Holcomb Bridge Road / Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|notes=|mile=.6}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.8\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|name1=Peachtree Parkway}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}{{-}}\n\n===Peachtree Industrial Boulevard===\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=GA\n|type=\n|name=Peachtree Industrial Boulevard\n|location=[[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]]\u2013[[Buford, Georgia|Buford]]\n|length_mi=25.4\n|length_round=1\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google PIB\">{{https://www.google.com/maps/@34.0308926,-84.1783876,13z}}</ref>\n|established=\n}}\n\n'''Peachtree Industrial Boulevard''' is a road in the U.S. state of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] that begins in [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]] and ends in [[Buford, Georgia|Buford]]. Between [[Interstate 285 (Georgia)|Interstate 285]] and [[Georgia State Route 140|SR&nbsp;140]] (Jimmy Carter Boulevard), the road is concurrent with SR 141. North of SR 140, in Peachtree Corners, Peachtree Industrial Boulevard splits from SR 141 and continues to the northeast as a highway with at least four lanes and center median, traveling through the cities of [[Peachtree Corners, Georgia|Peachtree Corners]], [[Duluth, Georgia|Duluth]], [[Suwanee, Georgia|Suwanee]], [[Sugar Hill, Georgia|Sugar Hill]], and Buford. The portion of the road concurrent with SR 141 is maintained by the state; the rest is maintained by Gwinnett County.<ref name=\"City of Duluth\">{{cite web |title=Street Maintenance |url=http://www.duluthga.net/departments/public_works/street_maintenance.php |publisher=City of Duluth |access-date=December 29, 2013 }}</ref> \n\nPeachtree Industrial Boulevard was originally built in the 1960s. The portion of the road concurrent to SR 141 was upgraded to a [[Limited-access road|limited-access highway]] in the 1980s and 1990s. \n\nIn 2008, the section within the city limits of [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]] was renamed to Peachtree Boulevard, to reflect the changing nature of the city. <ref>https://atlanta.curbed.com/2015/1/30/9997144/peachtree-industrial-boulevard-and-the-new-chamblee</ref> Prior to this change, the \"industrial\" name extended until Peachtree Road merges in near the city line with present-day [[Brookhaven, Georgia|Brookhaven]]. In November 2018, the [[Doraville, Georgia|Doraville]] City Council passed a resolution to authorize the city manager to rename Peachtree Industrial Boulevard within the city limits to Peachtree Boulevard, following the changes made by Chamblee. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/major-dekalb-road-could-see-name-change-the-future/t6SFStrC6mUbI7MJ8VpQFI/|title=Major DeKalb road could see name change in the future|last=Habersham|first=Raisa|date=November 8, 2018|website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> However, these changes have not yet taken place.\n\nIn 2013, Gwinnett County decreased the speed limit the road to 45 mph between SR 141 (Peachtree Parkway) and [[Georgia State Route 20|SR 20]] (Nelson Brogdon Boulevard) and 50 mph between SR 20 and the [[Hall County, Georgia|Hall County]] line. The goal of the change was to reduce speeding and accidents. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gwinnettcounty.com/web/gwinnett/Home/Stories/ViewStory?story=New%20speed%20limits%20along%20Peachtree%20Industrial%20Boulevard|title=New speed limits along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard|last=|first=|date=September 11, 2013|website=www.gwinnettcounty.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, the Atlanta Regional Commission Board approved funding to equip intersections along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard with connected vehicle technology. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantaregional.org/news/press-releases/arc-board-approves-69-million-in-transportation-projects-across-gwinnett-county/|title=ARC Board Approves $69 Million in Transportation Projects across Gwinnett County|date=2018-06-27|website=ARC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nGwinnett County has looked at adding and improving sidewalks along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard. <ref>https://www.gwinnettcounty.com/static/departments/boc/pdf/2017%20SPLOST%20Transportation%20Projects.pdf</ref>\n\nThe [[Western Gwinnett Bikeway]] is a multi-use trail under construction along Peachtree Industrial Boulevard.{{jcttop|state=GA|length_ref=<ref name=\"Google\"/>}}{{GAint|county=Dekalb|location=Doraville|lspan=3|mile=0.0|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|13|dab1=Doraville|SR|141|name1=Motors Industrial Way|name2=Peachtree Boulevard|city1=Chamblee}}|cspan=3|type=concur|notes=Southern terminus; southern end of concurrency with SR 141; road continues as SR 141/Peachtree Boulevard}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=0.2\n|road={{jct|state=GA|I|285|name1=Atlanta Bypass / [[Georgia State Route 407|SR&nbsp;407]]|location1=[[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]|city2=Marietta|location3=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]]}}\n|notes=I-285, exit 31; southern end of freeway\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=1.0\n|road=Tilly Mill Road -  [[Georgia State University]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county1=DeKalb\n|county2=Gwinnett\n|location1=Doraville\n|location2=Peachtree Corners\n|location_group=city\n|mile=2.1\n|road=Winters Chapel Road / Amwiler Road\n|notes=\n}}\n{{GAint\n|county=Gwinnett\n|cspan=11\n|location=Peachtree Corners\n|lspan=4\n|mile=3.2\n|road=Jones Mill Road - Peachtree Corners Circle\n|notes=No southbound exit; SR 141 southbound exit via SR 140 exit\n|type=incomplete}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=3.8\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|140|name1=Jimmy Carter Boulevard|city1=Roswell|city2=Tucker}}\n|notes=No southbound exit|type=incomplete}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=4.2\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|141|dir1=north|to2=to|GA|400|road=Peachtree Parkway|city1=Cumming|city2=Dahlonega}}\n|notes=Northern end of freeway; northern end of concurrency with SR 141; northbound exit, southbound entrance\n}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR-Conn|141|dab1=Gwinnett County|dir1=north|name1=Holcomb Bridge Road}}|mile=4.5|notes=}}{{GAint|mile=10.3|location=Duluth|lspan=4|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=Pleasant Hill Road|location1=[[Gwinnett Medical Center-Duluth]]}}}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=11.6\n|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|120|name1=Abbotts Bridge Road / Duluth Highway|city1=Alpharetta|city2=Duluth}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=12.9\n|road={{jct|state=GA|US|23|GA|13|name2=Buford Highway|to1=yes|road=Rogers Bridge Road|location1=[[Rogers Bridge Park]]}}\n}}\n{{GAint\n|mile=14.0\n|road=Sugarloaf Parkway\n|notes=\n}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=|extra=hospital|road=McGinnis Ferry Road|location1=[[Emory Healthcare]] Johns Creek Hospital}}|mile=16.4|location=Suwanee|lspan=2}}{{GAint|road=Suwanee Buford Dam Road &ndash; [[Suwanee, Georgia|Suwanee]]|mile=17.9}}{{GAint|road={{jct|state=GA|SR|20|name1=Nelson Brogden Boulevard|city1=Cumming|city2=Lawrenceville}}|mile=21.8|location=Sugar Hill}}{{GAint|road=Cemetery Road / McEver Road|notes=Northern terminus; road continues as McEver Road|mile=25.4|location=Buford|county1=Gwinnett|county2=Hall}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete,concur}}\n\n== Orphaned segments ==\nThere are six road segments that previously carried State Route 141 or a derivative designation that no longer do.\n\n#  What is now Georgia SR 371 once was SR 141 between Georgia SR 9 and SR 20. It was changed to its present number in the early 1970s.\n#  The State Route 141 designation was previously used in DeKalb County between Tucker and US 78 in what is now Stone Mountain Park on what is now Hugh Howell Highway (SR 236) which was at the time named Rosser Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/CountyMapsArchive/DeKalb_1900s.zip|title=Georgia DOT Map Archive, DeKalb County 1900's, 1948 Map|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref>\n# Prior to construction of Peachtree Parkway and the extension and re-routing of SR 141 to Buckhead, SR 141 followed what is present day Medlock Bridge Road from its current intersection with Peachtree Parkway, into downtown Norcross and became North Peachtree Road, crossed the railroad tracks at Park Street, and then traveled on South Peachtree until its terminus at Buford Highway (SR 13). When plans were drawn to re-route SR 141 to its present alignment, GDOT changed the designation of this roadway to SR 141 Connector.  This designation stayed in effect until 1981, when this segment was turned over to the county and converted to local roads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/CountyMapsArchive/Gwinnett_1900s.zip|title=Georgia DOT Map Archive - Gwinnett County 1900's|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> What is now SR 141 between the Buckhead junction with Roswell Road (SR 9) and Motors Industrial Way (present day SR 13 Connector) was designated along with Motors Industrial Way as SR 13W before it was made part of the newly aligned SR 141.\n# With the construction of Interstate 85, Norcross Tucker road, which at the time was a contiguous road, was designated SR 141 Connector, and the small segment of South Peachtree Road between Buford Highway and Norcross Tucker Road was redesigned SR 141 Spur. The South Peachtree Road (SR 141 Spur) was converted to a local road in 1981 along with truncation of SR 141 Connector to Norcross Tucker Road between South Peachtree Rd in Norcross and Interstate 85.\n# As Jimmy Carter Boulevard was constructed in the 1970s, Norcross Tucker Road was split into North Norcross Tucker Road and South Norcross Tucker Road, and a portion of the road was incorporated into Jimmy Carter Boulevard. In 1981, Jimmy Carter Boulevard was designated as SR 141 Connector between Peachtree Industrial Boulevard and Interstate 85.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/CountyMapsArchive/Gwinnett_1900s.zip|title=Georgia DOT Map Archive - Gwinnett County 1900's|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> It was converted to State Route 140 in 1984-1985 timeframe<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/HwyAndTransportationMaps/1984_1985.pdf|title=GDOT State Highway Map 1984-1985|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref> and the SR 141 Connector designation was used for what is present day SR 141 Connector at the 141/Peachtree Industrial Boulevard interchange when the Jimmy Carter Boulevard/SR 141 intersection was upgraded to a grade separated intersection.\n#  The 17.5 mile segment of State Route 369 East of '''SR 9''' from North of Cumming to Gainesville was designated as SR 141 until 1970, when it was extended West to SR 20, and redesigned to its present-day number.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/HwyAndTransportationMaps/1970.pdf|title=1970 State Highway Map GDOT|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dot.ga.gov/DriveSmart/MapsData/Documents/HwyAndTransportationMaps/1971.pdf|title=1971 State Highway Map GDOT|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{portal-inline|Georgia (U.S. state)}} \n* {{portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n* [[Peachtree Street|Peachtree Road]]\n* [[Transportation in Atlanta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://georgiaroads.tripod.com/gahwy8.htm Georgia Roads (Routes 141 - 160)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100717222433/http://www.state-ends.com/georgia/014100/ Georgia State Route 141 on State-Ends.com]\n\n[[Category:State highways in Georgia (U.S. state)|141]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Fulton County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in DeKalb County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Gwinnett County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Forsyth County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Brookhaven, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Chamblee, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Doraville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Roads in Atlanta]]\n", "name_user": "Wes762", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMajor intersections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgia_State_Route_141"}
{"title_page": "Five Nights at Freddy's 4", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4: The Final Chapter\n| image = FNAF4Artwork.png\n| caption = [[Steam (software)|Steam]] storefront header\n| developer = [[Scott Cawthon]]\n| publisher = Scott Cawthon\n| series = ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's]]''\n| engine = [[Clickteam Fusion 2.5]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]]\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows'''{{Video game release|WW|{{start date|2015|7|23}}}}'''Android'''{{Video game release|WW|{{start date|2015|7|25}}}}'''iOS'''{{Video game release|WW|{{start date|2015|8|3}}}}'''Nintendo Switch''', '''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''{{Video game release|WW|November 29, 2019}}\n| genre = [[Survival horror]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Five Nights at Freddy's 4''''' is an [[Indie game|indie]] [[Adventure game#Point-and-click adventure games|point-and-click]] [[survival horror]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Scott Cawthon]]. It is the fourth installment of the ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's]]'' series. It was originally planned for release on October 31, 2015, the game was pushed forward to August 8, then again to July 23 when it was unexpectedly released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref name=FNAF4IGN>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/07/23/five-nights-at-freddys-4-jump-scares-a-surprise-early-release|title=Five Nights at Freddy's 4 Jump-Scares a Surprise Early Release|accessdate= July 23, 2015}}</ref> It was released for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices on July 25, 2015, and for [[iOS]] devices on August 3, 2015.  A [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] port was released on November 29, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2019/11/five-nights-at-freddys-1-2-3-and-4-for-ps4-xbox-one-and-switch-launch-november-29|title=Five Nights at Freddy\u2019s 1, 2, 3, and 4 for PS4, Xbox One, and Switch launch November 29|last=Romano|first=Sal|date=November 27, 2019|publisher=Games Radar|language=English}}</ref>\n\nAnnounced in mid-2015 under the [[working title]] ''Five Nights at Freddy's: The Final Chapter'', the game is considered a departure from the previous games, which took place in a security office. Instead, the game takes place in a child's bedroom, placing an emphasis on timing and auditory warnings to complete nights.\n\nUpon release, the game received polarizing reviews from critics; praise centered on its unsettling atmosphere, while others were divided over the game's new mechanics. ''Five Nights at Freddy's 4'' is the only game in the entire series that has no spoken dialogue. The fifth installment, ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's: Sister Location]]'', was released on October 7, 2016.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n<!-- Please do not add speculative content to this section or the plot section from YouTube videos, the FNAF Wiki, or your imagination as they are not considered reliable sources. -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bedroomviewfnaf4.jpg|thumb|left|Instead of the player being in an office they are in a child's bedroom]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Plushtrap.jpg|thumb|right|The \"Fun with Plushtrap\" minigame.]] -->\nUnlike previous ''Five Nights at Freddy's'' games, the game is not set in a security office, but in a child's bedroom; there are also no [[Closed-circuit television|security cameras]] and instead of \"Phone Guy\", the player is given on-screen instructions to help the player during the game.<ref name=\"KotakuAll\">{{cite web | url=http://kotaku.com/everything-we-know-about-five-nights-at-freddys-4-so-f-1720003919 | title=Everything We Know About Five Nights at Freddy's 4 (So Far) | publisher=Kotaku | date=July 24, 2015 | accessdate=July 25, 2015 | author=Hernandez, Patricia}}</ref> The player is equipped with a flashlight, similar to the [[Five Nights at Freddy's 2|second game]], although the light has unlimited power.<ref name= \"Destruct\">{{cite web | url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-five-nights-at-freddy-s-4-296612.phtml | title=Review: Five Nights at Freddy's 4 | publisher=[[Destructoid]] | date=July 24, 2015 | accessdate=July 25, 2015 | author=Rowen, Nic}}</ref> It can be used to ward away any animatronics seen down the hallway; however, if the player hears either Nightmare Bonnie's or Nightmare Chica's breathing at the door or they see Nightmare Fredbear or Nightmare upon turning on the flashlight, they must immediately close the door. Despite this, the door will eventually open ajar as the player walks away. The player must also monitor the closet to avoid getting attacked by Nightmare Foxy by closing it if necessary, similar to the [[Five Nights at Freddy's|first game]], as well as shooing three miniature animatronics nicknamed 'Freddles' by the FNAF community off the bed before they, once all three are together, summon Nightmare Freddy to attack the player. If the player is not careful in shining the light towards the hallways or leaves the doors, closet and bed unattended for too long, the player will be [[jumpscare]]d, leading to a [[game over]].\n\nAfter beating each night, the player may play a timed minigame titled \"Fun with Plushtrap\" (In Halloween update, Plushtrap is replaced by Nightmare Balloon Boy) in which a plush edition of Springtrap, the central animatronic in ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's 3]]'', must be lured to the top of an \"X\" marked on the ground within a specific amount of time. If the player succeeds, the player will start the next night at 2:00 A.M. (1:00 A.M. in challenge modes) Like the nightmare animatronics, this timed minigame becomes more challenging as the game progresses. The time bonus does not apply to the unlockable modes. Additionally, if the player gets a game over, the bonus is no longer valid for further plays of the same level.\n\nLike previous games, the game's main storyline takes place over five increasingly-difficult nights with unlockable extra levels. The first four nights will put the player against four animatronics: Nightmare Freddy, Nightmare Bonnie, Nightmare Chica and Nightmare Foxy (Nightmare Mangle in Halloween update). Nightmare Fredbear, who combines the scare tactics of the previous four, is the sole attacker on the fifth night. Completing all five nights will unlock an additional sixth night, where the four animatronics will haunt the player until Nightmare Fredbear takes over when the clock hits 4 AM. Completing the sixth night will unlock the \"Nightmare\" night, where the animatronics are very persistent and Nightmare Fredbear is replaced by the highly aggressive Nightmare, who has a unique game over screen compared to other animatronics. A secret code will unlock an eighth night or called as 20/20/20/20 mode based on the Custom Night modes from the first two games, which sets the [[Artificial intelligence|A.I.]] of the animatronics to maximum difficulty. Other unlockables include galleries of the various animatronics and jumpscares, as well as behind-the-scenes looks at the 3D-modelling process for Fredbear and Foxy.<ref name=\"Extras\">{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon| publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene =Extras menu| quote = }}</ref>\n\nAs in most of the previous entries of the series, the story of the game is revealed in interactive [[Retrogaming|Atari-style]] minigame sections between nights. Each of the minigames are set in a time frame corresponding to the five nights, beginning with \"5 days until the party\", up to \"0 days until the party.\"\n\n== Plot ==\nThe game starts with a minigame which shows a child who is locked in his bedroom with plush toys, which he calls his only friends.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Five Nights at Freddy's 4|developer=Scott Cawthon|publisher=|platform=[[Personal computer|PC]]|scene=Night 1 prologue|date=July 23, 2015|quote='''Boy:''' These are my friends.}}</ref> After the player survives the first night, the boy's Fredbear plush tells him that \"he\" (the boy's older brother) is hiding in the house, before the boy is jumpscared by him, who is wearing a Foxy mask.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 2 prologue| quote = '''Fredbear:''' Now he is hiding again. He won't stop until you find him.}}</ref> After the second night, the boy is abandoned at the pizzeria (implied to be the Fredbear's Family Diner briefly mentioned in the [[Five Nights at Freddy's 2|second]] game), only to be warned by Fredbear's voice that \"he\" is coming and that he must be brave; however, since the boy is afraid of the animatronics and costumed mascots, he ends up bawling. An [[Easter egg (interaction design)|easter egg]] during this scene briefly shows William Afton from the second and [[Five Nights at Freddy's 3|third]] games fitting someone into the Spring Bonnie suit.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 3 prologue| quote = '''Fredbear:''' You're too late. Hurry the other way and find someone who will help! You know what will happen if he catches you! You can find help if you can get past them. You need to be strong.}}</ref>\n\nAfter the third night, the minigame reveals that other children tease the boy, calling him a coward and crybaby,<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 4 prologue| quote = '''Boy 1:''' Aren't you the kid who always hides under the table and cries? Hahaha! No one else is scared! Why are you? Stop being such a baby!}}</ref> and that there are rumors of the animatronics coming to life at night and attempting to murder people.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 4 prologue| quote = '''Girl 2:''' You'd better watch out! I hear they come to life at night. And if you die, they hide your body and never tell anyone.}}</ref> The boy sees his plush toys as his only friends and generally eschews interaction with other people in favor of them. Another easter egg in this minigame establishes the time period, via a commercial or TV show named \"''Fredbear and Friends''\" dated 1983. After the fourth night, it is revealed that he was once locked in the building's parts and services room as a prank.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 prologue| quote = '''You:''' Please let me out. PLEASE! Please let me out...}}</ref> If the fifth night is completed, the boy is shown crying at his birthday party in the pizzeria, with his brother (alongside other bullies) wearing the masks of the animatronics to terrorize the boy.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 epilogue| quote = '''Your Brother's Friend:''' Wow, your brother is kind of a baby, isn't he? / '''Your Brother:''' It's hilarious.}}</ref> The bullies, deciding to prank the boy, grab him and try to get him close to the Fredbear animatronic's mouth for a \"kiss,\"<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 epilogue| quote = '''Your Brother:''' Why don't we help him get a closer look! He will love it. / '''You:''' Please! / '''Your Brother:''' Come on, guys, let's give this little man a lift. He wants to get up close and personal! / '''You:''' No! I don't want to go! / '''Your Brother:''' You heard the little man! He wants to get even closer! Ha ha ha!}}</ref> and end up stuffing the boy's head into the animatronic's mouth.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 epilogue| quote = '''Your Brother:''' Hey guys, I think the little man said he wants to give Fredbear a big kiss! On THREE! One...two...}}</ref> Suddenly, Fredbear, who was in the middle of singing, forcefully closes his mouth, due to the boy's tears activating the spring locks, and crushes the boy's head while the brother and his friends stare in sheer horror, realizing their mistake.\n \nAfter the sixth night, the boy hears his older brother apologizing to him<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 6 epilogue| quote = '''Voice:''' Can you hear me? I don't know if you can hear me. I'm sorry.}}</ref> as Fredbear promises him that no matter how many times he \"breaks,\" he and the others will always be there to \"put him back together\" and will always be his friends.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 6 epilogue| quote = '''Fredbear:''' You're broken. We're still your friends. Do you still believe that? I'm still here. I will put you back together.}}</ref> The characters then fade out one by one, and the faint sound of a [[electrocardiography|heart monitor]] flatlining can be heard, death of the boy and ending the minigames. Following this, the player unlocks Nightmare mode, which is the same as the sixth night with the exception of a new animatronic, Nightmare, a more aggressive version of Nightmare Fredbear.       \n\nThere is a divide in the community about who had the nightmares. Some say it\u2019s the bite victim, as he\u2019s scared of the animatronics and you play as him during the minigames. While, others say it\u2019s the older brother because, after seeing his brother get killed, he got nightmares because of [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]]( Post Traumactic Stress Disorder). \n\nIf the player completes Nightmare mode, an image of a locked metal trunk is displayed; if the player wiggles the padlocks, the game states that \"Perhaps some things are best left forgotten, for now.\"<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Nightmare epilogue}}</ref> Cawthon remained cryptic about what is inside the trunk, and eventually announced that he would not disclose what was in it. He gave only one clue: \"What's in the box? It's the pieces [of the franchise's story] put together.\"\n\nThroughout the game, if the screen is brightened or the player looks closely enough, the progression of the fate of the child can be seen through objects next to the bed. When the player turns to the bed, looking to the left of the Freddy plush, three objects appear at different points in time: a bottle of pills, an IV drip, and a vase of flowers.\n\nMany people think that the older brother in the minigames is Michael Afton, and that he presumably is the night guard in the first game, as he could have changed his last name.\n\n== Development and release ==\nBeginning April 27, 2015, Cawthon posted images on his website teasing at another game in the series, originally known as ''Five Nights at Freddy's: The Final Chapter''. The images, featuring the characters from the series, cryptically teased at a release on Halloween.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2015/04/28/five-nights-at-freddys-4-release-date/ | title = Five Night\u2019s at Freddy\u2019s 4 teased for Halloween release | first =Brenna | last = Hillier | date = April 28, 2015 | accessdate = May 16, 2015 | work = [[VG247]]|publisher = Videogaming 247 Ltd. }}</ref> A trailer was released on July 13, 2015, hinting that the game took place in the main character's house. The subtitle, ''The Final Chapter'', was dropped.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.polygon.com/2015/7/13/8955575/five-nights-at-freddys-4-trailer|title= Five Nights at Freddy's 4 trailer gets its first creepy trailer|author= Campbell, Colin|work= [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher= [[Vox Media]]|date= July 13, 2015|accessdate= July 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cnet.com/news/freddy-follows-you-home-in-trailer-for-five-nights-at-freddys-4/|title= Freddy follows you home in trailer for Five Nights at Freddy's 4|author= Gallagher, Danny|work= [[CNET]]|publisher= [[CBS Corporation]]|date= July 14, 2015|accessdate= July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA demo for the game was released to select YouTubers on July 21, 2015, with the full game being released on July 23, 2015.<ref name=FNAF4IGN/> The game was released for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices on July 25, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.gamezebo.com/2015/07/25/five-nights-at-freddys-4-is-now-on-android/|title= Five Nights at Freddy\u2019s  4 Is Now on Android|author= Jim Squires|publisher= [[Gamezebo]]|date= July 25, 2015|accessdate= July 29, 2015}}</ref> and for [[iOS]] devices on August 3, 2015. On October 31, 2015, two updates for the game were released. One consists of a set of cheat options, challenge modes, and an altered version of the \"Fun with Plushtrap\" minigame that uses a nightmare version of the character Balloon Boy (from ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's 2]]'') in place of Plushtrap. The second is a \"Halloween Edition\" that makes cosmetic changes to Nightmare Bonnie and Nightmare Chica, and introduces nightmare versions of the ''Five Nights at Freddy's 2'''s characters Mangle and The Puppet, (known as Nightmarionne in-game) the former replacing Nightmare Foxy and the latter replacing Nightmare. Nightmare Chica's cupcake is also replaced with a [[Jack-o-Lantern]].\n\n==Reception==\n{{VG reception\n| MC = (PC) 51/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/five-nights-at-freddys-4 |title=Five Nights at Freddy's 4 for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Corporation]] |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 4/10<ref name=\"Destruct\"/>\n| PCGUS = 70/100<ref name=\"PCG\">{{cite web|url= http://www.pcgamer.com/five-nights-at-freddys-4-review/|title= Five Nights at Freddy's 4 Review on PC Gamer|publisher= [[PC Gamer]]|date= August 5, 2015|accessdate= August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Escapist\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Gamezebo]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GZ\"/>\n| rev3 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev3Score = (iOS) {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2015/08/10/five-nights-at-freddys-4-review/ |title='Five Nights At Freddy's 4' Review \u2013 The Latest Freddy Gets The Worst Port Yet |last=Musgrave |first=Shaun |date=August 10, 2015 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nThe PC version of the game received an aggregate score of 51 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 6 reviews.<ref name= \"MC\"/>\n\n''[[Destructoid]]'' criticized the gameplay as being too confusing, and gave the game a review score of 4 out of 10.<ref name= \"Destruct\"/> ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'' gave the game a positive review score of 4 out of 5 stars saying that they liked the reworked mechanics, darker and emotional storyline, scary jumpscares, and sad ending but noted the game's bugs and glitches.<ref name= \"The Escapist\">{{cite web|url= http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/editorials/reviews/14363-Five-Nights-at-Freddy-s-4-Review-Worth-Playing|title= Five Nights at Freddy's 4 Review - Change, Improve, Jumpscare|author= Angelo M. D'Argeno|work= [[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|publisher= [[Defy Media]]|date= July 28, 2015|accessdate= July 29, 2015}}</ref> Nadia Oxford of [[Gamezebo]] gave it 4 out of 5 stars in her review praising it for its intense environment, creepy sounds and graphics, and jumpscares. She criticised the game for being difficult to survive in certain environments when relying on audio cues and the Android version not containing the story-centric minigames.<ref name= \"GZ\">{{cite web|url= http://www.gamezebo.com/2015/07/30/five-nights-at-freddys-4-review-hey-listen/|title= Five Nights at Freddy\u2019s 4 Review: Hey! Listen!|author= Nadia Oxford|publisher= [[GameZebo]]|date= July 30, 2015|accessdate= August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.scottgames.com/}}\n\n{{Five Nights at Freddy's}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Five Nights at Freddy's|4]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Horror video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Works about missing people]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:Video games about robots]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video game prequels]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1983]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4: The Final Chapter\n| image = FNAF4Artwork.png\n| caption = [[Steam (software)|Steam]] storefront header\n| developer = [[Scott Cawthon]]\n| publisher = Scott Cawthon\n| series = ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's]]''\n| engine = [[Clickteam Fusion 2.5]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]]\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows'''{{Video game release|WW|{{start date|2015|7|23}}}}'''Android'''{{Video game release|WW|{{start date|2015|7|25}}}}'''iOS'''{{Video game release|WW|{{start date|2015|8|3}}}}'''Nintendo Switch''', '''PlayStation 4''', '''Xbox One'''{{Video game release|WW|November 29, 2019}}\n| genre = [[Survival horror]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Five Nights at Freddy's 4''''' is an [[Indie game|indie]] [[Adventure game#Point-and-click adventure games|point-and-click]] [[survival horror]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Scott Cawthon]]. It is the fourth installment of the ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's]]'' series. It was originally planned for release on October 31, 2015, the game was pushed forward to August 8, then again to July 23 when it was unexpectedly released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref name=FNAF4IGN>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/07/23/five-nights-at-freddys-4-jump-scares-a-surprise-early-release|title=Five Nights at Freddy's 4 Jump-Scares a Surprise Early Release|accessdate= July 23, 2015}}</ref> It was released for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices on July 25, 2015, and for [[iOS]] devices on August 3, 2015.  A [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] port was released on November 29, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2019/11/five-nights-at-freddys-1-2-3-and-4-for-ps4-xbox-one-and-switch-launch-november-29|title=Five Nights at Freddy\u2019s 1, 2, 3, and 4 for PS4, Xbox One, and Switch launch November 29|last=Romano|first=Sal|date=November 27, 2019|publisher=Games Radar|language=English}}</ref>\n\nAnnounced in mid-2015 under the [[working title]] ''Five Nights at Freddy's: The Final Chapter'', the game is considered a departure from the previous games, which took place in a security office. Instead, the game takes place in a child's bedroom, placing an emphasis on timing and auditory warnings to complete nights.\n\nUpon release, the game received polarizing reviews from critics; praise centered on its unsettling atmosphere, while others were divided over the game's new mechanics. ''Five Nights at Freddy's 4'' is the only game in the entire series that has no spoken dialogue. The fifth installment, ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's: Sister Location]]'', was released on October 7, 2016.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n<!-- Please do not add speculative content to this section or the plot section from YouTube videos, the FNAF Wiki, or your imagination as they are not considered reliable sources. -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bedroomviewfnaf4.jpg|thumb|left|Instead of the player being in an office they are in a child's bedroom]] -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Plushtrap.jpg|thumb|right|The \"Fun with Plushtrap\" minigame.]] -->\nUnlike previous ''Five Nights at Freddy's'' games, the game is not set in a security office, but in a child's bedroom; there are also no [[Closed-circuit television|security cameras]] and instead of \"Phone Guy\", the player is given on-screen instructions to help the player during the game.<ref name=\"KotakuAll\">{{cite web | url=http://kotaku.com/everything-we-know-about-five-nights-at-freddys-4-so-f-1720003919 | title=Everything We Know About Five Nights at Freddy's 4 (So Far) | publisher=Kotaku | date=July 24, 2015 | accessdate=July 25, 2015 | author=Hernandez, Patricia}}</ref> The player is equipped with a flashlight, similar to the [[Five Nights at Freddy's 2|second game]], although the light has unlimited power.<ref name= \"Destruct\">{{cite web | url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-five-nights-at-freddy-s-4-296612.phtml | title=Review: Five Nights at Freddy's 4 | publisher=[[Destructoid]] | date=July 24, 2015 | accessdate=July 25, 2015 | author=Rowen, Nic}}</ref> It can be used to ward away any animatronics seen down the hallway; however, if the player hears either Nightmare Bonnie's or Nightmare Chica's breathing at the door or they see Nightmare Fredbear or Nightmare upon turning on the flashlight, they must immediately close the door. Despite this, the door will eventually open ajar as the player walks away. The player must also monitor the closet to avoid getting attacked by Nightmare Foxy by closing it if necessary, similar to the [[Five Nights at Freddy's|first game]], as well as shooing three miniature animatronics nicknamed 'Freddles' by the FNAF community off the bed before they, once all three are together, summon Nightmare Freddy to attack the player. If the player is not careful in shining the light towards the hallways or leaves the doors, closet and bed unattended for too long, the player will be [[jumpscare]]d, leading to a [[game over]].\n\nAfter beating each night, the player may play a timed minigame titled \"Fun with Plushtrap\" (In Halloween update, Plushtrap is replaced by Nightmare Balloon Boy) in which a plush edition of Springtrap, the central animatronic in ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's 3]]'', must be lured to the top of an \"X\" marked on the ground within a specific amount of time. If the player succeeds, the player will start the next night at 2:00 A.M. (1:00 A.M. in challenge modes) Like the nightmare animatronics, this timed minigame becomes more challenging as the game progresses. The time bonus does not apply to the unlockable modes. Additionally, if the player gets a game over, the bonus is no longer valid for further plays of the same level.\n\nLike previous games, the game's main storyline takes place over five increasingly-difficult nights with unlockable extra levels. The first four nights will put the player against four animatronics: Nightmare Freddy, Nightmare Bonnie, Nightmare Chica and Nightmare Foxy (Nightmare Mangle in Halloween update). Nightmare Fredbear, who combines the scare tactics of the previous four, is the sole attacker on the fifth night. Completing all five nights will unlock an additional sixth night, where the four animatronics will haunt the player until Nightmare Fredbear takes over when the clock hits 4 AM. Completing the sixth night will unlock the \"Nightmare\" night, where the animatronics are very persistent and Nightmare Fredbear is replaced by the highly aggressive Nightmare, who has a unique game over screen compared to other animatronics. A secret code will unlock an eighth night or called as 20/20/20/20 mode based on the Custom Night modes from the first two games, which sets the [[Artificial intelligence|A.I.]] of the animatronics to maximum difficulty. Other unlockables include galleries of the various animatronics and jumpscares, as well as behind-the-scenes looks at the 3D-modelling process for Fredbear and Foxy.<ref name=\"Extras\">{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon| publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene =Extras menu| quote = }}</ref>\n\nAs in most of the previous entries of the series, the story of the game is revealed in interactive [[Retrogaming|Atari-style]] minigame sections between nights. Each of the minigames are set in a time frame corresponding to the five nights, beginning with \"5 days until the party\", up to \"0 days until the party.\"\n\n== Plot ==\nThe game starts with a minigame which shows a child who is locked in his bedroom with plush toys, which he calls his only friends.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Five Nights at Freddy's 4|developer=Scott Cawthon|publisher=|platform=[[Personal computer|PC]]|scene=Night 1 prologue|date=July 23, 2015|quote='''Boy:''' These are my friends.}}</ref> After the player survives the first night, the boy's Fredbear plush tells him that \"he\" (the boy's older brother) is hiding in the house, before the boy is jumpscared by him, who is wearing a Foxy mask.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 2 prologue| quote = '''Fredbear:''' Now he is hiding again. He won't stop until you find him.}}</ref> After the second night, the boy is abandoned at the pizzeria (implied to be the Fredbear's Family Diner briefly mentioned in the [[Five Nights at Freddy's 2|second]] game), only to be warned by Fredbear's voice that \"he\" is coming and that he must be brave; however, since the boy is afraid of the animatronics and costumed mascots, he ends up bawling. An [[Easter egg (interaction design)|easter egg]] during this scene briefly shows William Afton from the second and [[Five Nights at Freddy's 3|third]] games fitting someone into the Spring Bonnie suit.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 3 prologue| quote = '''Fredbear:''' You're too late. Hurry the other way and find someone who will help! You know what will happen if he catches you! You can find help if you can get past them. You need to be strong.}}</ref>\n\nAfter the third night, the minigame reveals that other children tease the boy, calling him a coward and crybaby,<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 4 prologue| quote = '''Boy 1:''' Aren't you the kid who always hides under the table and cries? Hahaha! No one else is scared! Why are you? Stop being such a baby!}}</ref> and that there are rumors of the animatronics coming to life at night and attempting to murder people.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 4 prologue| quote = '''Girl 2:''' You'd better watch out! I hear they come to life at night. And if you die, they hide your body and never tell anyone.}}</ref> The boy sees his plush toys as his only friends and generally eschews interaction with other people in favor of them. Another easter egg in this minigame establishes the time period, via a commercial or TV show named \"''Fredbear and Friends''\" dated 1983. After the fourth night, it is revealed that he was once locked in the building's parts and services room as a prank.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 prologue| quote = '''You:''' Please let me out. PLEASE! Please let me out...}}</ref> If the fifth night is completed, the boy is shown crying at his birthday party in the pizzeria, with his brother (alongside other bullies) wearing the masks of the animatronics to terrorize the boy.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 epilogue| quote = '''Your Brother's Friend:''' Wow, your brother is kind of a baby, isn't he? / '''Your Brother:''' It's hilarious.}}</ref> The bullies, deciding to prank the boy, grab him and try to get him close to the Fredbear animatronic's mouth for a \"kiss,\"<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 epilogue| quote = '''Your Brother:''' Why don't we help him get a closer look! He will love it. / '''You:''' Please! / '''Your Brother:''' Come on, guys, let's give this little man a lift. He wants to get up close and personal! / '''You:''' No! I don't want to go! / '''Your Brother:''' You heard the little man! He wants to get even closer! Ha ha ha!}}</ref> and end up stuffing the boy's head into the animatronic's mouth.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 5 epilogue| quote = '''Your Brother:''' Hey guys, I think the little man said he wants to give Fredbear a big kiss! On THREE! One...two...}}</ref> Suddenly, Fredbear, who was in the middle of singing, forcefully closes his mouth, due to the boy's tears activating the spring locks, and crushes the boy's head while the brother and his friends stare in sheer horror, realizing their mistake.\n \nAfter the sixth night, the boy hears his older brother apologizing to him<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 6 epilogue| quote = '''Voice:''' Can you hear me? I don't know if you can hear me. I'm sorry.}}</ref> as Fredbear promises him that no matter how many times he \"breaks,\" he and the others will always be there to \"put him back together\" and will always be his friends.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Night 6 epilogue| quote = '''Fredbear:''' You're broken. We're still your friends. Do you still believe that? I'm still here. I will put you back together.}}</ref> The characters then fade out one by one, and the faint sound of a [[electrocardiography|heart monitor]] flatlining can be heard, death of the boy and ending the minigames. Following this, the player unlocks Nightmare mode, which is the same as the sixth night with the exception of a new animatronic, Nightmare, a more aggressive version of Nightmare Fredbear.       \n\nThere is a a divide in the community about who had the nightmares. Some say it\u2019s the bite victim, as he\u2019s scared of the animatronics and you play as him during the minigames. While, others say it\u2019s the older brother because, after seeing his brother get killed, he got nightmares because of [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]]( Post Traumactic Stress Disorder). \n\nIf the player completes Nightmare mode, an image of a locked metal trunk is displayed; if the player wiggles the padlocks, the game states that \"Perhaps some things are best left forgotten, for now.\"<ref>{{cite video game| title = Five Nights at Freddy's 4| developer = Scott Cawthon | publisher = | date = July 23, 2015| platform = [[Personal computer|PC]]| scene = Nightmare epilogue}}</ref> Cawthon remained cryptic about what is inside the trunk, and eventually announced that he would not disclose what was in it. He gave only one clue: \"What's in the box? It's the pieces [of the franchise's story] put together.\"\n\nThroughout the game, if the screen is brightened or the player looks closely enough, the progression of the fate of the child can be seen through objects next to the bed. When the player turns to the bed, looking to the left of the Freddy plush, three objects appear at different points in time: a bottle of pills, an IV drip, and a vase of flowers.\n\nMany people think that the older brother in the minigames is Michael Afton, and that he presumably is the night guard in the first game, as he could have changed his last name.\n\n== Development and release ==\nBeginning April 27, 2015, Cawthon posted images on his website teasing at another game in the series, originally known as ''Five Nights at Freddy's: The Final Chapter''. The images, featuring the characters from the series, cryptically teased at a release on Halloween.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2015/04/28/five-nights-at-freddys-4-release-date/ | title = Five Night\u2019s at Freddy\u2019s 4 teased for Halloween release | first =Brenna | last = Hillier | date = April 28, 2015 | accessdate = May 16, 2015 | work = [[VG247]]|publisher = Videogaming 247 Ltd. }}</ref> A trailer was released on July 13, 2015, hinting that the game took place in the main character's house. The subtitle, ''The Final Chapter'', was dropped.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.polygon.com/2015/7/13/8955575/five-nights-at-freddys-4-trailer|title= Five Nights at Freddy's 4 trailer gets its first creepy trailer|author= Campbell, Colin|work= [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher= [[Vox Media]]|date= July 13, 2015|accessdate= July 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cnet.com/news/freddy-follows-you-home-in-trailer-for-five-nights-at-freddys-4/|title= Freddy follows you home in trailer for Five Nights at Freddy's 4|author= Gallagher, Danny|work= [[CNET]]|publisher= [[CBS Corporation]]|date= July 14, 2015|accessdate= July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA demo for the game was released to select YouTubers on July 21, 2015, with the full game being released on July 23, 2015.<ref name=FNAF4IGN/> The game was released for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices on July 25, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.gamezebo.com/2015/07/25/five-nights-at-freddys-4-is-now-on-android/|title= Five Nights at Freddy\u2019s  4 Is Now on Android|author= Jim Squires|publisher= [[Gamezebo]]|date= July 25, 2015|accessdate= July 29, 2015}}</ref> and for [[iOS]] devices on August 3, 2015. On October 31, 2015, two updates for the game were released. One consists of a set of cheat options, challenge modes, and an altered version of the \"Fun with Plushtrap\" minigame that uses a nightmare version of the character Balloon Boy (from ''[[Five Nights at Freddy's 2]]'') in place of Plushtrap. The second is a \"Halloween Edition\" that makes cosmetic changes to Nightmare Bonnie and Nightmare Chica, and introduces nightmare versions of the ''Five Nights at Freddy's 2'''s characters Mangle and The Puppet, (known as Nightmarionne in-game) the former replacing Nightmare Foxy and the latter replacing Nightmare. Nightmare Chica's cupcake is also replaced with a [[Jack-o-Lantern]].\n\n==Reception==\n{{VG reception\n| MC = (PC) 51/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/five-nights-at-freddys-4 |title=Five Nights at Freddy's 4 for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Corporation]] |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 4/10<ref name=\"Destruct\"/>\n| PCGUS = 70/100<ref name=\"PCG\">{{cite web|url= http://www.pcgamer.com/five-nights-at-freddys-4-review/|title= Five Nights at Freddy's 4 Review on PC Gamer|publisher= [[PC Gamer]]|date= August 5, 2015|accessdate= August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Escapist\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Gamezebo]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"GZ\"/>\n| rev3 = ''[[TouchArcade]]''\n| rev3Score = (iOS) {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2015/08/10/five-nights-at-freddys-4-review/ |title='Five Nights At Freddy's 4' Review \u2013 The Latest Freddy Gets The Worst Port Yet |last=Musgrave |first=Shaun |date=August 10, 2015 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nThe PC version of the game received an aggregate score of 51 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 6 reviews.<ref name= \"MC\"/>\n\n''[[Destructoid]]'' criticized the gameplay as being too confusing, and gave the game a review score of 4 out of 10.<ref name= \"Destruct\"/> ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'' gave the game a positive review score of 4 out of 5 stars saying that they liked the reworked mechanics, darker and emotional storyline, scary jumpscares, and sad ending but noted the game's bugs and glitches.<ref name= \"The Escapist\">{{cite web|url= http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/editorials/reviews/14363-Five-Nights-at-Freddy-s-4-Review-Worth-Playing|title= Five Nights at Freddy's 4 Review - Change, Improve, Jumpscare|author= Angelo M. D'Argeno|work= [[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|publisher= [[Defy Media]]|date= July 28, 2015|accessdate= July 29, 2015}}</ref> Nadia Oxford of [[Gamezebo]] gave it 4 out of 5 stars in her review praising it for its intense environment, creepy sounds and graphics, and jumpscares. She criticised the game for being difficult to survive in certain environments when relying on audio cues and the Android version not containing the story-centric minigames.<ref name= \"GZ\">{{cite web|url= http://www.gamezebo.com/2015/07/30/five-nights-at-freddys-4-review-hey-listen/|title= Five Nights at Freddy\u2019s 4 Review: Hey! Listen!|author= Nadia Oxford|publisher= [[GameZebo]]|date= July 30, 2015|accessdate= August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.scottgames.com/}}\n\n{{Five Nights at Freddy's}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Five Nights at Freddy's|4]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Horror video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Works about missing people]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:Video games about robots]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video game prequels]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1983]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Five_Nights_at_Freddy%27s_4"}
{"title_page": "Sheet bend", "text_new": "{{Knot-details\n| name= Sheet bend\n| image= Schotstek rechts.jpg\n| names=becket bend, weaver's knot, weaver's hitch\n| type= bend\n| origin= \n| related= [[Bowline]]\n| releasing= \n| strength= 48%\u201358%\n| uses= joining two ropes of different diameters\n| caveat= \n| abok_number= (simple) #1, #66, #1431; (double) #488, #1434; (weaver's) #2, #485;\n}}\n\nThe '''sheet bend''' (also known as '''becket bend''', '''weaver's knot''' and '''weaver's hitch''') is a [[Bend knot|bend]]. It is practical for joining lines of different diameter or rigidity. \n\nIt is quick and easy to tie, and is considered so essential it is the first knot given in the ''[[Ashley Book of Knots]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=The Ashley Book of Knots|last=Ashley|first=Clifford W.|publisher=Doubleday|year=1944|isbn=|location=|pages=9,18}}</ref> Additionally, it is one of the six knots given in the [[International Guild of Knot Tyers]]' Six Knot Challenge, along with the [[clove hitch]], [[bowline]], [[Reef knot|reef knot (square knot)]], [[round turn and two half-hitches]], and [[sheepshank]]. \n\nThe sheet bend is related in structure to the bowline; like the bowline, it has a tendency to work loose when not under load. For increased security, it is sometimes recommended that one add another turn in the smaller end, making a [[Sheet bend#Double sheet bend|double sheet bend]]; in most cases, however, a single sheet bend should suffice. \n\nAs a bend, its advantages lie in its simplicity and non-jamming properties. \n\nIt is commonly taught in [[Boy Scouts]]. \n\n==Definition==\nThe term \"sheet bend\" derives from its use bending ropes to sails (sheets).  It is mentioned in David Steel's 1794 book ''Elements and Practice of Rigging and Seamanship'' but was used by Neolithic peoples for tying the meshes of fishing nets.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shaw|first=John|title=The Directory of Knots|publisher=Grange Books|place=Rochester|date=2004|page=35}}</ref> The name \"weaver's knot\" comes from its historic use in textile mills. Even in modern operations, weavers are taught to use this particular knot when correcting broken threads in the [[Warp (weaving)|warp]]. \n\n==Method==\n[[File:QSM Weaver's knot.webm|thumb|right|Weaver at [[Queen Street Mill]] demonstrating a weaver's knot]]\n[[Image:Weavers knot.jpg|thumb|right|Steps in tying a weaver's knot]]\nThe sheet bend may be tied by various methods: the basic \"rabbit through the hole\" method of forming a [[half hitch]] in the bight of the larger rope, by a more expedient method shown in Ashley as ABoK #1431 (similar to the method used by an experienced sailor or mountaineer to tie a bowline) or by a trick method (ABoK#2562), involving upsetting a noose knot over a short end of the \"larger\" rope. Lines of equal size may be joined with a sheet bend, but when one is larger, it plays the simpler role of the \"eye\" (red line shown in the infobox), rather than the half-hitch (in green)\n\nOne type of weaver's knot is [[topology|topologically]] equivalent to a sheet bend, but is tied (usually in smaller stuff) with a different approach. Sheet bends are also used for netting.\n[[Image:P\u00eache DSC03035.JPG|thumb|right|A fish net made from sheet bends]]\nNotice that, to have any strength, the two free ends should end up on the same side of the knot<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ropeinc.com/knots-splicing.html|title=Knots and Splicing|publisher=ropeinc.com|at=Single Sheet Bend}}</ref> (see below). Under even moderate load, a left-hand sheet bend will quickly slip and release completely.\n<gallery>\nImage:Schotstek rechts.jpg|Secure \nImage:Schotstek links.jpg|Insecure (left-hand sheet bend<ref name=\"ashley16\">Clifford W. Ashley, ''The Ashley Book of Knots'' (New York: Doubleday, 1944), #67 and #1432</ref>)\n</gallery>\n\n==Double sheet bend==\nWhen lines are of unequal diameter or rigidity it is necessary for security to \"double\" the sheet bend by making an additional round turn below the first and again bringing the working end back under itself. The free ends should end up on the same side of the knot for maximum strength.\n<gallery>\nImage:Double sheet bend 2 rotated 180.jpg|The double sheet bend\n</gallery>\n\n==Security==\nA study of 8 different bends using climbing rope of equal diameter said the sheet bend was weak.  In one test, it pulled apart with less than half the pressure that other knots withstood.  The authors recommend \"2 half hitches on the bend back line and overhand knot on turn thru line.\"  Even with these, it was always a bottom performer and the double sheet bend did little better. However, the [[butterfly bend]] did the best.<ref>[http://caves.org/section/vertical/nh/50/knotrope-hold.html Knot Break Strength vs Rope Break Strength]</ref>\n\nAfter performing security testing, Ashley wrote with regard to the Sheet Bend: \"Some readers may be surprised to find the Sheet Bend with so low a rating, but these tests were made in exceptionally slippery material. The Sheet Bend is the most practical of bends and quite secure enough for ordinary purposes.\"\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Sheet bends}}\n*[[List of bend knots]]\n*[[List of knots]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://gumroad.com/l/lyNmTu cheap double sheet bend knot 3d model]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Knots}}\n\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Knot-details\n| name= Sheet bend\n| image= Schotstek rechts.jpg\n| names=becket bend, weaver's knot, weaver's hitch\n| type= bend\n| origin= \n| related= [[Bowline]]\n| releasing= \n| strength= 48%\u201358%\n| uses= joining two ropes of different diameters\n| caveat= \n| abok_number= (simple) #1, #66, #1431; (double) #488, #1434; (weaver's) #2, #485;\n}}\n\nThe '''sheet bend''' (also known as '''becket bend''', '''weaver's knot''' and '''weaver's hitch''') is a [[Bend knot|bend]]. It is practical for joining lines of different diameter or rigidity. \n\nIt is quick and easy to tie, and is considered so essential it is the first knot given in the ''[[Ashley Book of Knots]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=The Ashley Book of Knots|last=Ashley|first=Clifford W.|publisher=Doubleday|year=1944|isbn=|location=|pages=9,18}}</ref> Additionally, it is one of the six knots given in the [[International Guild of Knot Tyers]]' Six Knot Challenge, along with the [[clove hitch]], [[bowline]], [[Reef knot|reef knot (square knot)]], [[round turn and two half-hitches]], and [[sheepshank]]. \n\nThe sheet bend is related in structure to the bowline; like the bowline, it has a tendency to work loose when not under load. For increased security, it is sometimes recommended that one add another turn in the smaller end, making a [[Sheet bend#Double sheet bend|double sheet bend]]; in most cases, however, a single sheet bend should suffice. \n\nAs a bend, its advantages lie in its simplicity and non-jamming properties. \n\nIt is commonly taught in [[Boy Scouts]]. \n\n==Definition==\nThe term \"sheet bend\" derives from its use bending ropes to sails (sheets).  It is mentioned in David Steel's 1794 book ''Elements and Practice of Rigging and Seamanship'' but was used by Neolithic peoples for tying the meshes of fishing nets.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shaw|first=John|title=The Directory of Knots|publisher=Grange Books|place=Rochester|date=2004|page=35}}</ref> The name \"weaver's knot\" comes from its historic use in textile mills. Even in modern operations, weavers are taught to use this particular knot when correcting broken threads in the [[Warp (weaving)|warp]]. \n\n==Method==\n[[File:QSM Weaver's knot.webm|thumb|right|Weaver at [[Queen Street Mill]] demonstrating a weaver's knot]]\n[[Image:Weavers knot.jpg|thumb|right|Steps in tying a weaver's knot]]\nThe sheet bend may be tied by various methods: the basic \"rabbit through the hole\" method of forming a [[half hitch]] in the bight of the larger rope, by a more expedient method shown in Ashley as ABoK #1431 (similar to the method used by an experienced sailor or mountaineer to tie a bowline) or by a trick method (ABoK#2562), involving upsetting a noose knot over a short end of the \"larger\" rope. Lines of equal size may be joined with a sheet bend, but when one is larger, it plays the simpler role of the \"eye\" (red line shown in the infobox), rather than the half-hitch (in green)\n\nOne type of weaver's knot is [[topology|topologically]] equivalent to a sheet bend, but is tied (usually in smaller stuff) with a different approach. Sheet bends are also used for netting.\n[[Image:P\u00eache DSC03035.JPG|thumb|right|A fish net made from sheet bends]]\nNotice that, to have any strength, the two free ends should end up on the same side of the knot<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ropeinc.com/knots-splicing.html|title=Knots and Splicing|publisher=ropeinc.com|at=Single Sheet Bend}}</ref> (see below). Under even moderate load, a left-hand sheet bend will quickly slip and release completely.\n<gallery>\nImage:Schotstek rechts.jpg|Secure \nImage:Schotstek links.jpg|Insecure (left-hand sheet bend<ref name=\"ashley16\">Clifford W. Ashley, ''The Ashley Book of Knots'' (New York: Doubleday, 1944), #67 and #1432</ref>)\n</gallery>\n\n==Double sheet bend==\nWhen lines are of unequal diameter or rigidity it is necessary for security to \"double\" the sheet bend by making an additional round turn below the first and again bringing the working end back under itself. The free ends should end up on the same side of the knot for maximum strength.\n<gallery>\nImage:Double sheet bend 2 rotated 180.jpg|The double sheet bend\n</gallery>\n\n==Security==\nA study of 8 different bends using climbing rope of equal diameter said the sheet bend was weak.  In one test, it pulled apart with less than half the pressure that other knots withstood.  The authors recommend \"2 half hitches on the bend back line and overhand knot on turn thru line.\"  Even with these, it was always a bottom performer and the double sheet bend did little better. However, the [[butterfly bend]] did the best.<ref>[http://caves.org/section/vertical/nh/50/knotrope-hold.html Knot Break Strength vs Rope Break Strength]</ref>\n\nAfter performing security testing, Ashley wrote with regard to the Sheet Bend: \"Some readers may be surprised to find the Sheet Bend with so low a rating, but these tests were made in exceptionally slippery material. The Sheet Bend is the most practical of bends and quite secure enough for ordinary purposes.\"\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Sheet bends}}\n*[[List of bend knots]]\n*[[List of knots]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Knots}}\n\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Zaripov999", "label": "safe", "comment": "add external link to 3d model", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheet_bend"}
{"title_page": "Hayes, Bromley", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Hayes, Hillingdon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox UK place|\n|country =                 England\n|region=                   London\n|population=               15,906\n|population_ref=           (2011 Census. Hayes and Coney Hall Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13688626&c=Hayes+and+Coney+Hall&d=14&e=62&g=6320934&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1476121051656&enc=1|title=Bromley Ward population 2011|accessdate=10 October 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics| work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n|official_name=            Hayes\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.378|0.0192|display=inline,title}}\n|london_borough=           Bromley\n|constituency_westminster= [[Beckenham (UK Parliament constituency)|Beckenham]]     \n|post_town=                BROMLEY\n|postcode_area=            BR  \n|postcode_district =       BR2 \n|dial_code=                020\n|os_grid_reference=        TQ405665\n|static_image_name= Hayes Street BR2 with the parish church - geograph.org.uk - 43878.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Hayes''' is a suburban area of South East [[Greater London|London]], England, within the [[London Borough of Bromley]] and the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Kent]]. It is located south of [[Bromley]], and {{convert|11|miles|km}} south-east of [[Charing Cross]] and it neighbours [[Coney Hall]].\n\n==The ancient village==\nThe name ''Hayes'' is recorded from 1177 as ''hoese'' from the Anglo-Saxon meaning \"a settlement in open land overgrown with shrubs and rough bushes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=BRO035|title=London Gardens Online|website=www.londongardensonline.org.uk|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wikikent.co.uk/history-of-Hayes-Kent.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817064528/http://wikikent.co.uk/history-of-Hayes-Kent.shtml |archivedate=17 August 2013  }}</ref> It formed an ancient, and later civil, parish of [[Kent]] of around {{convert|1282|acre|km2}}.<ref>Vision of Britain - [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10095165&c_id=10001043 Hayes parish] ([http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10095165&c_id=10001043 historic boundaries] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001800/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10095165&c_id=10001043 |date=1 October 2007 }})</ref> The village stood at the junction of Hayes Lane, leading north to [[Bromley]] (one mile distant), and what is now known as Pickhurst Lane, leading west to [[West Wickham]]. The centre of the old village is now called ''Hayes Street''. The village school was here, as is the parish church of [[St Mary the Virgin, Bromley|St Mary the Virgin]]. Parts of the church date back to the thirteenth century; however it was subject to [[Victorian restoration|heavy restoration]]s by [[George Gilbert Scott]] and [[John Oldrid Scott]] in the nineteenth century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cherry |first1= Bridget |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus   |title=London 2: South  |edition=   |series=The Buildings of England |volume= |year=1990  |origyear=1983 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=   |isbn=0-14-071047-7  |page= 187}}</ref>  The public house, also on Hayes Lane, is called \"The George\" (first recorded 1759<ref name=\"ISBN0906377005\">{{Cite book|title=A history of Hayes in the county of Kent.|last=Thompson)|first=H. P. (Henry Percy)|date=1978|publisher=Jackdaw Publishing|isbn=0906377005|location=Beckenham|oclc=498598112}}</ref>) . Hayes Street Farm, still shown on modern maps, is to the north of the village centre.\n\nBoth [[William Pitt the Elder]], 1st Earl of Chatham (1708\u20131778), and [[William Pitt the Younger]] (1759\u20131806) lived at Hayes Place.<ref>Hayes Place was at {{gbmapping|TQ404663}} and is described on [http://www.victorianlondon.org/ql/queenslondon283.htm this page]</ref> The house was demolished in 1933 and the site redeveloped, but its occupants are remembered in such road names as Chatham and Pittsmead Avenues. Prior to being demolished, Hayes Place was owned by the Hambro family (of [[Hambros Bank]] fame) and a couple of roads bear the family names.\n\nAlthough the parish church of Hayes can trace its history back over 800 years, and local villains joined [[Jack Cade's Rebellion|Jack Cade]] in his rebellion of 1450, the story of Hayes became significant a little over a century ago, when Hayes became a popular place in which to live because bankers, stockbrokers and those who were \"something in the City\" bought property in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mpthewarren.com/about-us/history/|title=The Warren {{!}} History |website=www.mpthewarren.com|language=en-US|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1801, when the population was just 382, and 1921, it had almost tripled to 1010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentarchaeology.org.uk/research/tithes|title=Tithe Apportionments for Kent - Kent Archaeology Society|website=www.kentarchaeology.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe branch [[railway]] from [[Elmers End]], originally known as the [[West Wickham and Hayes Railway]], was opened on 29 May 1882.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edithsstreets.blogspot.co.uk/2010/02/thames-tributary-bourne-flowing-to.html|title=Thames Tributary Bourne flowing to the Ravensbourne - Hayes|website=edithsstreets.blogspot.co.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> [[Hayes railway station|Hayes station]] is a terminus<ref name=\"ISBN9780951517826\">{{Cite book|title=Hayes : a history of a Kentish village|last=historian)|first=Wilson, Jean (Local|date=2012|publisher=J. Wilson|others=Woodman, Trevor, 1939-2007.|isbn=9780951517826|location=Bromley|oclc=808490838}}</ref>.\n\nDuring the second world war, an anti-aircraft gun battery was locally based on Hayes Common, and the soldiers of the [[1st Canadian Division]]<ref name=\"ISBN9780951517833\">{{Cite book|title=Hayes: a history of a Kentish village|last=Wilson|first=Jean (Local Historian)|date=2012|publisher=J. Wilson|others=Woodman, Trevor, 1939-2007.|isbn=9780951517833|location=Bromley|oclc=808490838}}</ref> who manned it were barracked in local homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://branches.britishlegion.org.uk/branches/hayes/branch-information/history|title=History - Hayes (Kent) Branch - The Royal British Legion.|website=branches.britishlegion.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A 3-inch gun crew of 303rd Battery, 99th Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery, at Hayes Common in Kent, May 1940. H1387.jpg|thumb|A 3-inch gun crew of 303rd Battery, 99th Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery, at Hayes Common in Kent, May 1940. H1387]]\n\nThroughout the 20th century, the Hayes village area continued to grow and thrive. Further commercial development occurred on Station Approach because the increased traffic through the railway terminus created an incentive for growth. In the old village area ('Old Hayes'), the former village school was converted to a second, smaller village hall when the local primary school opened in 1937;<ref name=\"hps\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayes-pri.bromley.sch.uk/346/our-school-history|title=Our School History - Hayes Primary School|website=www.hayes-pri.bromley.sch.uk|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> it lies along George Lane, which was further expanded at around the same time to facilitate further suburban housing developments.\n\n==Modern suburban Hayes==\n\nTo cope with the increase in commuter traffic, the station was rebuilt in 1935, and ''Station Approach'' became the main shopping area,<ref name=\"gazetteer\">{{Cite web|url=http://hidden-london.com/gazetteer/hayes-bromley/|title=Hayes, Bromley - Hidden London|website=hidden-london.com|language=en-US|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> including a [[Post Office]], [[petrol station]], two mini-supermarkets and numerous small shops. It also contains a [[public house]] called The New Inn.\n\nMuch of the area to the west and north-west of the original village has been taken over by [[suburbia]]. [[West Wickham]] and Bromley are completely joined with Hayes; and [[Coney Hall]] estate, beyond the [[Orpington]] - [[Croydon]] road is also part of the pattern. To the east and south, however, the open space of [[Hayes Common]] precludes building of any kind.\n\nGrandfields Nursery in West Common Road was hit by a [[V-2 rocket]] in the late afternoon of 9 February 1945, killing four people, including three members of the Grandfield family. Our Lady of the Rosary Catholic Church was later built on the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catholic-hayes.org/past-present/|title=Past & Present|date=14 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe old village area along Hayes Street, also known as 'Old Hayes', today contains some small shops, though the local post office closed in 2004 (the nearest is now in the main shopping area near the station). The timbered cottage on the eastern side of Hayes Street was originally the village bakery, then it became a [[newsagent]]s called \"The Walnut Tree\", until 2006, when it changed to residential use. The former village school remains a second village hall; the local primary school in George Lane has expanded in size in recent years, and now has three class groups in each year. It is extremely popular, and many of its pupils go on to [[Hayes School]] in West Common Road.\n\nThe shopping area in ''Old Hayes'' functions as a second hub for commercial businesses, running along Hayes street opposite the church building. It consists of the public house, \"The George\", a mini-market, several hairdressers, a cycle shop, two coffee shops and a fish and chip shop. Next to the church is the village [[Public Library|public]] [[Bromley Borough Libraries Service|library]], occupying the old [[rectory]] building (since replaced by the new rectory), and is surrounded by the library gardens, a small area of parkland containing tennis courts.\n\nHayes Street Farm continues to play an important role in the village setting. Several public pathways and popular walking routes run through the farmland, and regular [[car boot sale]]s are hosted on the farm fields.\n\nThere is a group called Hayes Village Association (HVA) which meet regularly to inform people about local issues. They regularly liaise with Bromley Council on planning matters and they give a voice to residents and businesses on a variety of issues. HVA produce a quarterly magazine with local interest articles and events, as well as details of businesses in the locality.\n\n==Sports and leisure==\n\nThere are numerous playing fields and sports grounds around the periphery of Hayes: such as the Metropolitan Police Sports Ground at the Warren. It is also home, since 1927, to the world-famous Blackheath Harriers Athletics Club (now [[Blackheath and Bromley Harriers Athletic Club]]) at their clubhouse ''The [[Sydney Wooderson]] Centre''.\n\n* Hayes Town FC (Formed 2016). Members of the Surrey South Eastern Combination, based at [[Coney Hall]] FC's Tiepigs Lane ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/hayestownfootballclub|title=Hayes Town Football Club|website=www.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Beccehamians RFC \u2013 a Rugby Union Club founded in 1933 plays competitive rugby at Sparrows Den at the bottom of Corkscrew Hill near West Wickham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beccehamians.co.uk/|title=Beccehamian RFC Home Page|website=www.beccehamians.co.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Hayes Cricket Club,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayescricket.com/|title=Hayes (Kent) Cricket Club|website=www.hayescricket.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> based at the Warman Sport ground.\n* Bromley RFC \u2013 a Rugby union club started in 1886 and moved to Hayes Village in 1956 and are based at the Warman Sport ground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alondondir.com/UK_London/UK_And_Bromley/_Bromley_Recreation_and_Sports/160000-16751.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=21 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094829/http://www.alondondir.com/UK_London/UK_And_Bromley/_Bromley_Recreation_and_Sports/160000-16751.html |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/bromleyrfc/|title=Bromley RFC|website=www.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Norman Park Athletics Track \u2013  one of the main athletics tracks in Bromley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.openplay.co.uk/view/538/norman-park-athletics-track/|title=Norman Park Athletics Track |website=www.openplay.co.uk|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Bromley F.C.]] \u2013 A football club based at the [[Hayes Lane]] Stadium.\n* Hayes (Lawn) Tennis club,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayeskenttennis.org.uk/|title=Hayes Kent Lawn Tennis Club|website=www.hayeskenttennis.org.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> based at the Warman Sport ground.\n* Old Wilsonians Sports Club<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oldwilsonians.com/about/|title=About Old Wilsonians Sports Club|website=oldwilsonians.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> (on fields formerly known as Hayes Hill Sports Ground)\n* Urban [[Krav Maga]] based at the Old School.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n* Bigfoot Cycle club.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bigfootcc.co.uk/about/|title=About Us|date=30 October 2013|work=BigfootCC|access-date=24 June 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* Roebucks Cricket Club, based at Burton Pynsent House.\n\n==Arts and culture==\n* Hayes [[Philharmonic]] Choir - 1945 - May 2017 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayeschoir.co.uk/|title=Hayes Philharmonic Choir {{!}} Registered Charity 285667|website=www.hayeschoir.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Allegri Singers - A [[Chamber choir]] created in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allegrisingers.org.uk/|title=Allegri Singers|website=allegrisingers.org.uk|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Hayes Players - An [[Amateur theatre]] club founded in 1933<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayesplayers.org.uk/|title=The Hayes Players|website=www.hayesplayers.org.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n*Hayes Symphony Orchestra - A community [[orchestra]], created in 1947, that has three concerts a year\n\n==Transport==\n===Rail===\n[[Hayes railway station]] is the terminus / start point for '[[Mid-Kent line|Hayes line]]' services ran by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]  to and from London Charing Cross and London Cannon Street stations.\n\n===Buses===\nHayes is served by Transport For London bus routes including one route operating 24 hours per day.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Education ==\n\n* [[Hayes School]] - a mixed [[secondary school]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]]. Awarded WCSQM \"World Class\" status in October 2015. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayes.bromley.sch.uk/Hayes-School-is-World-Class-1|title=Hayes School is World Class|website=www.hayes.bromley.sch.uk|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Green Spaces ==\n* [[Hayes Common]] - a 79-[[Hectare]] area of public open land\n* Husseywell Park - <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=BRO043|title=London Gardens Online|website=www.londongardensonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Coney Hall Recreation Ground <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bromley.gov.uk/directory_record/1074475/coney_hall_recreation_ground |title=Archived copy |accessdate=10 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110205828/http://www.bromley.gov.uk/directory_record/1074475/coney_hall_recreation_ground |archivedate=10 November 2013  }}</ref>\n* Pickhurst Park\n* The Knoll - an Ornamental Ground of four and a half hectares with lakes and specimen forest trees<ref>http://www.kidsfunlondon.co.uk/kids-london/park/the-knoll.html</ref>\n\n== Notable residents==\n* [[William Pitt the Younger]].\n* [[Christopher Greener]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/11843442.Mourners_gather_in_Hayes_for_funeral_of_former_UK_s_tallest_man_Christopher_Greener/#|title=Mourners gather in Hayes for funeral of former UK's tallest man Christopher Greener|website=News Shopper|language=en|date=9 March 2015|access-date=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring areas'''\n|Northwest = [[Eden Park, London|Eden Park]]\n|North     = [[Bromley]]\n|Northeast = [[Bickley]]\n|West      = [[West Wickham]]\n|Centre    = Hayes\n|East      = [[Bromley Common]]\n|Southwest = [[Coney Hall]]\n|South     = [[Keston]]\n|Southeast = [[Farnborough, London|Farnborough]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Hayes: a History of a Kentish Village: Volume 1: The Stone Age to 1914 by Jean Wilson and Trevor Woodman  {{ISBN|978-0-9515178-2-6}}\n*Hayes: a History of a Kentish Village: Volume 2: 1914 to Modern Times by Jean Wilson and Trevor Woodman {{ISBN|978-0-9515178-3-3}}\n*A history of Hayes in the county of Kent by H. P Thompson {{ISBN|0-906377-00-5}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bromley.gov.uk/site/ Bromley]\n\n{{LB Bromley}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Bromley]]\n[[Category:Former civil parishes in London]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Hayes, Hillingdon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox UK place|\n|country =                 England\n|region=                   London\n|population=               15,906\n|population_ref=           (2011 Census. Hayes and Coney Hall Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13688626&c=Hayes+and+Coney+Hall&d=14&e=62&g=6320934&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1476121051656&enc=1|title=Bromley Ward population 2011|accessdate=10 October 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics| work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n|official_name=            Hayes\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.378|0.0192|display=inline,title}}\n|london_borough=           Bromley\n|constituency_westminster= [[Beckenham (UK Parliament constituency)|Beckenham]]     \n|post_town=                BROMLEY\n|postcode_area=            BR  \n|postcode_district =       BR2 \n|dial_code=                020\n|os_grid_reference=        TQ405665\n|static_image_name= Hayes Street BR2 with the parish church - geograph.org.uk - 43878.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Hayes''' is a suburban area of South East [[Greater London|London]], England, within the [[London Borough of Bromley]] and the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Kent]]. It is located south of [[Bromley]], and {{convert|11|miles|km}} south-east of [[Charing Cross]] and it neighbours [[Coney Hall]].\n\n==The ancient village==\nThe name ''Hayes'' is recorded from 1177 as ''hoese'' from the Anglo-Saxon meaning \"a settlement in open land overgrown with shrubs and rough bushes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=BRO035|title=London Gardens Online|website=www.londongardensonline.org.uk|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wikikent.co.uk/history-of-Hayes-Kent.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817064528/http://wikikent.co.uk/history-of-Hayes-Kent.shtml |archivedate=17 August 2013  }}</ref> It formed an ancient, and later civil, parish of [[Kent]] of around {{convert|1282|acre|km2}}.<ref>Vision of Britain - [http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10095165&c_id=10001043 Hayes parish] ([http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10095165&c_id=10001043 historic boundaries] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001800/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10095165&c_id=10001043 |date=1 October 2007 }})</ref> The village stood at the junction of Hayes Lane, leading north to [[Bromley]] (one mile distant), and what is now known as Pickhurst Lane, leading west to [[West Wickham]]. The centre of the old village is now called ''Hayes Street''. The village school was here, as is the parish church of [[St Mary the Virgin, Bromley|St Mary the Virgin]]. Parts of the church date back to the thirteenth century; however it was subject to [[Victorian restoration|heavy restoration]]s by [[George Gilbert Scott]] and [[John Oldrid Scott]] in the nineteenth century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cherry |first1= Bridget |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus   |title=London 2: South  |edition=   |series=The Buildings of England |volume= |year=1990  |origyear=1983 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=   |isbn=0-14-071047-7  |page= 187}}</ref>  The public house, also on Hayes Lane, is called \"The George\" (first recorded 1759<ref name=\"ISBN0906377005\">{{Cite book|title=A history of Hayes in the county of Kent.|last=Thompson)|first=H. P. (Henry Percy)|date=1978|publisher=Jackdaw Publishing|isbn=0906377005|location=Beckenham|oclc=498598112}}</ref>) . Hayes Street Farm, still shown on modern maps, is to the north of the village centre.\n\nBoth [[William Pitt the Elder]], 1st Earl of Chatham (1708\u20131778), and [[William Pitt the Younger]] (1759\u20131806) lived at Hayes Place.<ref>Hayes Place was at {{gbmapping|TQ404663}} and is described on [http://www.victorianlondon.org/ql/queenslondon283.htm this page]</ref> The house was demolished in 1933 and the site redeveloped, but its occupants are remembered in such road names as Chatham and Pittsmead Avenues. Prior to being demolished, Hayes Place was owned by the Hambro family (of [[Hambros Bank]] fame) and a couple of roads bear the family names.\n\nAlthough the parish church of Hayes can trace its history back over 800 years, and local villains joined [[Jack Cade's Rebellion|Jack Cade]] in his rebellion of 1450, the story of Hayes became significant a little over a century ago, when Hayes became a popular place in which to live because bankers, stockbrokers and those who were \"something in the City\" bought property in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mpthewarren.com/about-us/history/|title=The Warren {{!}} History |website=www.mpthewarren.com|language=en-US|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1801, when the population was just 382, and 1921, it had almost tripled to 1010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentarchaeology.org.uk/research/tithes|title=Tithe Apportionments for Kent - Kent Archaeology Society|website=www.kentarchaeology.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe branch [[railway]] from [[Elmers End]], originally known as the [[West Wickham and Hayes Railway]], was opened on 29 May 1882.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edithsstreets.blogspot.co.uk/2010/02/thames-tributary-bourne-flowing-to.html|title=Thames Tributary Bourne flowing to the Ravensbourne - Hayes|website=edithsstreets.blogspot.co.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> [[Hayes railway station|Hayes station]] is a terminus<ref name=\"ISBN9780951517826\">{{Cite book|title=Hayes : a history of a Kentish village|last=historian)|first=Wilson, Jean (Local|date=2012|publisher=J. Wilson|others=Woodman, Trevor, 1939-2007.|isbn=9780951517826|location=Bromley|oclc=808490838}}</ref>.\n\nDuring the second world war, an anti-aircraft gun battery was locally based on Hayes Common, and the soldiers of the [[1st Canadian Division]]<ref name=\"ISBN9780951517833\">{{Cite book|title=Hayes: a history of a Kentish village|last=Wilson|first=Jean (Local Historian)|date=2012|publisher=J. Wilson|others=Woodman, Trevor, 1939-2007.|isbn=9780951517833|location=Bromley|oclc=808490838}}</ref> who manned it were barracked in local homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://branches.britishlegion.org.uk/branches/hayes/branch-information/history|title=History - Hayes (Kent) Branch - The Royal British Legion.|website=branches.britishlegion.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A 3-inch gun crew of 303rd Battery, 99th Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery, at Hayes Common in Kent, May 1940. H1387.jpg|thumb|A 3-inch gun crew of 303rd Battery, 99th Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery, at Hayes Common in Kent, May 1940. H1387]]\n\nThroughout the 20th century, the Hayes village area continued to grow and thrive. Further commercial development occurred on Station Approach because the increased traffic through the railway terminus created an incentive for growth. In the old village area ('Old Hayes'), the former village school was converted to a second, smaller village hall when the local primary school opened in 1937;<ref name=\"hps\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayes-pri.bromley.sch.uk/346/our-school-history|title=Our School History - Hayes Primary School|website=www.hayes-pri.bromley.sch.uk|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> it lies along George Lane, which was further expanded at around the same time to facilitate further suburban housing developments.\n\n==Modern suburban Hayes==\n\nTo cope with the increase in commuter traffic, the station was rebuilt in 1935, and ''Station Approach'' became the main shopping area,<ref name=\"gazetteer\">{{Cite web|url=http://hidden-london.com/gazetteer/hayes-bromley/|title=Hayes, Bromley - Hidden London|website=hidden-london.com|language=en-US|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> including a [[Post Office]], [[petrol station]], two mini-supermarkets and numerous small shops. It also contains a [[public house]] called The New Inn.\n\nMuch of the area to the west and north-west of the original village has been taken over by [[suburbia]]. [[West Wickham]] and Bromley are completely joined with Hayes; and [[Coney Hall]] estate, beyond the [[Orpington]] - [[Croydon]] road is also part of the pattern. To the east and south, however, the open space of [[Hayes Common]] precludes building of any kind.\n\nGrandfields Nursery in West Common Road was hit by a [[V-2 rocket]] in the late afternoon of 9 February 1945, killing four people, including three members of the Grandfield family. Our Lady of the Rosary Catholic Church was later built on the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catholic-hayes.org/past-present/|title=Past & Present|date=14 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe old village area along Hayes Street, also known as 'Old Hayes', today contains some small shops, though the local post office closed in 2004 (the nearest is now in the main shopping area near the station). The timbered cottage on the eastern side of Hayes Street was originally the village bakery, then it became a [[newsagent]]s called \"The Walnut Tree\", until 2006, when it changed to residential use. The former village school remains a second village hall; the local primary school in George Lane has expanded in size in recent years, and now has three class groups in each year. It is extremely popular, and many of its pupils go on to [[Hayes School]] in West Common Road.\n\nThe shopping area in ''Old Hayes'' functions as a second hub for commercial businesses, running along Hayes street opposite the church building. It consists of the public house, \"The George\", a mini-market, several hairdressers, a cycle shop, two coffee shops and a fish and chip shop. Next to the church is the village [[Public Library|public]] [[Bromley Borough Libraries Service|library]], occupying the old [[rectory]] building (since replaced by the new rectory), and is surrounded by the library gardens, a small area of parkland containing tennis courts.\n\nHayes Street Farm continues to play an important role in the village setting. Several public pathways and popular walking routes run through the farmland, and regular [[car boot sale]]s are hosted on the farm fields.\n\nThere is a group called Hayes Village Association (HVA) which meet regularly to inform people about local issues. They regularly liaise with Bromley Council on planning matters and they give a voice to residents and businesses on a variety of issues. HVA produce a quarterly magazine with local interest articles and events, as well as details of businesses in the locality.\n\n==Sports and leisure==\n\nThere are numerous playing fields and sports grounds around the periphery of Hayes: such as the Metropolitan Police Sports Ground at the Warren. It is also home, since 1927, to the world-famous Blackheath Harriers Athletics Club (now [[Blackheath and Bromley Harriers Athletic Club]]) at their clubhouse ''The [[Sydney Wooderson]] Centre''.\n\n* Hayes Town FC (Formed 2016). Members of the Surrey South Eastern Combination, based at [[Coney Hall]] FC's Tiepigs Lane ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/hayestownfootballclub|title=Hayes Town Football Club|website=www.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Beccehamians RFC \u2013 a Rugby Union Club founded in 1933 plays competitive rugby at Sparrows Den at the bottom of Corkscrew Hill near West Wickham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beccehamians.co.uk/|title=Beccehamian RFC Home Page|website=www.beccehamians.co.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Hayes Cricket Club,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayescricket.com/|title=Hayes (Kent) Cricket Club|website=www.hayescricket.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> based at the Warman Sport ground.\n* Bromley RFC \u2013 a Rugby union club started in 1886 and moved to Hayes Village in 1956 and are based at the Warman Sport ground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alondondir.com/UK_London/UK_And_Bromley/_Bromley_Recreation_and_Sports/160000-16751.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=21 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094829/http://www.alondondir.com/UK_London/UK_And_Bromley/_Bromley_Recreation_and_Sports/160000-16751.html |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/bromleyrfc/|title=Bromley RFC|website=www.pitchero.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Norman Park Athletics Track \u2013  one of the main athletics tracks in Bromley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.openplay.co.uk/view/538/norman-park-athletics-track/|title=Norman Park Athletics Track |website=www.openplay.co.uk|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Bromley F.C.]] \u2013 A football club based at the [[Hayes Lane]] Stadium.\n* Hayes (Lawn) Tennis club,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayeskenttennis.org.uk/|title=Hayes Kent Lawn Tennis Club|website=www.hayeskenttennis.org.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> based at the Warman Sport ground.\n* Old Wilsonians Sports Club<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oldwilsonians.com/about/|title=About Old Wilsonians Sports Club|website=oldwilsonians.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref> (on fields formerly known as Hayes Hill Sports Ground)\n* Urban [[Krav Maga]] based at the Old School.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n* Bigfoot Cycle club.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bigfootcc.co.uk/about/|title=About Us|date=30 October 2013|work=BigfootCC|access-date=24 June 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* Roebucks Cricket Club, based at Burton Pynsent House.\n\n==Arts and culture==\n* Hayes [[Philharmonic]] Choir - 1945 - May 2017 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayeschoir.co.uk/|title=Hayes Philharmonic Choir {{!}} Registered Charity 285667|website=www.hayeschoir.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Allegri Singers - A [[Chamber choir]] created in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allegrisingers.org.uk/|title=Allegri Singers|website=allegrisingers.org.uk|language=en|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Hayes Players - An [[Amateur theatre]] club founded in 1933<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayesplayers.org.uk/|title=The Hayes Players|website=www.hayesplayers.org.uk|access-date=4 July 2017}}</ref>\n*Hayes Symphony Orchestra - A community [[orchestra]], created in 1947, that has three concerts a year\n\n==Transport==\n===Rail===\n[[Hayes railway station]] is the terminus / start point for '[[Mid-Kent line|Hayes line]]' services ran by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]  to and from London Charing Cross and London Cannon Street stations.\n\n===Buses===\nHayes is served by Transport For London bus routes including one route operating 24 hours per day.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Education ==\n\n* [[Hayes School]] - a mixed [[secondary school]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]]. Awarded WCSQM \"World Class\" status in October 2015. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hayes.bromley.sch.uk/Hayes-School-is-World-Class-1|title=Hayes School is World Class|website=www.hayes.bromley.sch.uk|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Green Spaces ==\n* [[Hayes Common]] - a 79-[[Hectare]] area of public open land\n* Husseywell Park - <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=BRO043|title=London Gardens Online|website=www.londongardensonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Coney Hall Recreation Ground <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bromley.gov.uk/directory_record/1074475/coney_hall_recreation_ground |title=Archived copy |accessdate=10 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110205828/http://www.bromley.gov.uk/directory_record/1074475/coney_hall_recreation_ground |archivedate=10 November 2013  }}</ref>\n* Pickhurst Park\n* The Knoll - an Ornamental Ground of four and a half hectares with lakes and specimen forest trees<ref>http://www.kidsfunlondon.co.uk/kids-london/park/the-knoll.html</ref>\n\n== Notable residents==\n* [[William Pitt the Younger]].\n* [[Christopher Greener]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/11843442.Mourners_gather_in_Hayes_for_funeral_of_former_UK_s_tallest_man_Christopher_Greener/#|title=Mourners gather in Hayes for funeral of former UK's tallest man Christopher Greener|website=News Shopper|language=en|date=9 March 2015|access-date=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring areas'''\n|Northwest = [[Eden Park, London|Eden Park]]\n|North     = [[Bromley]]\n|Northeast = [[Bickley]]\n|West      = [[West Wickham]]\n|Centre    = Hayes\n|East      = [[Bromley Common]]\n|Southwest = [[Coney Hall]]\n|South     = [[Keston]]\n|Southeast = [[Farnborough, London|Farnborough]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Hayes: a History of a Kentish Village: Volume 1: The Stone Age to 1914 by Jean Wilson and Trevor Woodman  {{ISBN|978-0-9515178-2-6}}\n*Hayes: a History of a Kentish Village: Volume 2: 1914 to Modern Times by Jean Wilson and Trevor Woodman {{ISBN|978-0-9515178-3-3}}\n*A history of Hayes in the county of Kent by H. P Thompson {{ISBN|0-906377-00-5}}\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hkva.org.uk/ Hayes Village Association]\n*[http://www.hayescricket.co.uk/ Hayes Cricket Club]\n*[http://www.bandbhac.org.uk/ Blackheath & Bromley Harriers AC - founded in 1869]\n*[http://hayesweatherstation.info/ Hayes Weather Station]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130817064528/http://wikikent.co.uk/history-of-Hayes-Kent.shtml Hayes on Wikikent]\n*[http://www.hayessymphony.org.uk/ Hayes Symphony Orchestra]\n{{LB Bromley}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Bromley]]\n[[Category:Former civil parishes in London]]\n", "name_user": "Charlesdrakew", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:acceptable link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hayes,_Bromley"}
{"title_page": "Willie Mays", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Other people|William Mays}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name = Willie Mays\n| image = Willie Mays cropped.jpg{{!}}border\n| caption = Mays in 1961\n| position = [[Center fielder]]\n| bats = Right\n| throws = Right\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1931|5|6}}\n| birth_place = Westfield, [[Alabama]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate = May 25\n| debutyear = 1951\n| debutteam = New York Giants\n|finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate = September 9\n| finalyear = 1973\n| finalteam = New York Mets\n|statleague = MLB\n| stat1label = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value = .302\n| stat3label = [[Home run]]s\n| stat3value = 660\n| stat2label = [[Hit (baseball)|Hit]]s\n| stat2value = 3,283\n| stat4label = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat4value = 1,903\n| stat5label = [[Stolen bases]]\n| stat5value = 338\n| teams =\n'''Negro leagues'''\n* [[Birmingham Black Barons]] ({{by|1948}}\u2013{{by|1950}})\n'''Major League Baseball'''\n* [[San Francisco Giants|New York / San Francisco Giants]] ({{mlby|1951}}\u2013{{mlby|1952}}, {{mlby|1954}}\u2013{{mlby|1972}})\n* [[New York Mets]] ({{mlby|1972}}\u2013{{mlby|1973}})\n| highlights =\n* 24\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1954 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1954]]\u2013[[1973 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1973]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{Wsy|1954}})\n* 2\u00d7 [[NL MVP]] (1954, 1965)\n* [[NL Rookie of the Year]] (1951)\n* 12\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1957\u20131968)\n* [[Roberto Clemente Award]] (1971)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting champion]] (1954)\n* 4\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|NL home run leader]] (1955, 1962, 1964, 1965)\n* 4\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual stolen base leaders|NL stolen base leader]] (1956\u20131959)\n* Hit [[List of Major League Baseball single-game home run leaders|4 home runs in one game]] on April 30, 1961\n* [[San Francisco Giants#Retired numbers|San Francisco Giants No. 24]] retired\n* [[San Francisco Giants Wall of Fame]]\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Time Team]]\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n| hofdate = [[1979 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1979]]\n| hofvote = 94.7% (first ballot)\n}}\n\n'''Willie Howard Mays, Jr.''' (born May 6, 1931), nicknamed \"'''The Say Hey Kid'''\", is an [[Americans|American]] former [[professional baseball]] [[center fielder]], who spent almost all of his 22-season [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) career playing for the [[San Francisco Giants|New York/San Francisco Giants]], before finishing with the [[New York Mets]]. He is regarded as one of the greatest baseball players of all time and was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in [[1979 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1979]].\n\nMays won two National League (NL) [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] (MVP) awards, ended his career with 660 [[home run]]s\u2014third at the time of his retirement and currently fifth all-time\u2014and won a record-tying 12 [[Gold Glove]] awards beginning in 1957, when the award was introduced.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/mlb_awards_content.jsp?content=gold_gloves_history MLB Awards | MLB.com: History<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMays shares the record of most [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Games]] played with 24, with [[Hank Aaron]] and [[Stan Musial]].<ref name=\"sportsdatallc.com\">Sportsdata. Midsummer Classics: Celebrating MLB's All-Star Game. \"there were two games a year from 1959 to 1962\" ...\"all players who were named to the AL or NL roster were credited one appearance per season.\" Retrieved July 18, 2013 {{cite web|url=http://www.sportsdatallc.com/2012/07/09/midsummer-classics-celebrating-mlbs-all-star-game |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 5, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330031638/http://www.sportsdatallc.com/2012/07/09/midsummer-classics-celebrating-mlbs-all-star-game/ |archivedate=March 30, 2015 }}</ref><ref>Baseball Almanac: Miscellaneous All-Star Game Records, All-Star Game Record Book, \"Most Games Played\", Aaron, Mays, Musial, 24. Retrieved July 21, 2013. [http://www.baseball-almanac.com/rb_asm.shtml]</ref> In appreciation of his All-Star record, [[Ted Williams]] said \"They invented the All-Star Game for Willie Mays.\"<ref>[http://www.baseballhall.org/hof/mays-willie National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum: The Hall of Famers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>''Willie's Time'', by [[Charles Einstein]].</ref>\n\nMays' career statistics and his longevity in the pre-[[performance-enhancing drugs]] era have drawn speculation that he may be the finest [[five-tool player]] ever, and many surveys and expert analyses, which have examined Mays' relative performance, have led to a growing opinion that Mays was possibly the greatest all-around offensive baseball player of all time.<ref name=Greatest /> In 1999, Mays placed second on ''[[The Sporting News]]''{{'}}s \"List of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players\", making him the highest-ranking living player. Later that year, he was also elected to the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]. Mays is one of five National League players to have had eight consecutive 100-RBI seasons, along with [[Mel Ott]], [[Sammy Sosa]], [[Chipper Jones]], and [[Albert Pujols]]. Mays hit over 50 home runs in 1955 and 1965, representing the longest time span between 50-plus home run seasons for any player in [[Major League Baseball]] history. His final [[Major League Baseball]] appearance came on October 16 during Game 3 of the [[1973 World Series]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nMays was born in 1931 in Westfield, Alabama, a former primarily black [[company town]] near [[Fairfield, Alabama|Fairfield]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Jesse Chambers |url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2013/08/new_documentary_film_remembers.html |title=New film remembers long-gone West Jefferson community of Westfield, home of Mays, Clemon |newspaper=The Birmingham News |date=August 2, 2013 }}</ref><ref>Mays, p. 19</ref> His father, Cat Mays, was a talented baseball player with the Negro team for the local iron plant.<ref name=\"mainbooksource\">{{cite book|title=Willie Mays: The Life, the Legend|author=James S. Hirsch|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|isbn=978-1-4165-4790-7|year=2010|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781416547907/page/11 11]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781416547907/page/11}}</ref> His mother, Annie Satterwhite, was a gifted basketball and track star in high school.<ref name=\"Hirsch, p. 12\">Hirsch, p. 12</ref> His parents never married<ref name=\"Hirsch, p. 12\"/> and separated when Mays was three.<ref>Mays, p. 18</ref> Mays was raised by his father growing up.<ref>Mays, pp. 18-25</ref> His father worked as a railway porter when Mays was born, but he later got a job at the steel mills in Westfield so he could be closer to home. When two girls in Mays's neighborhood were orphaned, his father took them in. Sarah and Ernestine helped raise young Willie, who always saw these two as his aunts.<ref>Mays, pp. 18-19</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=African American Pioneers of Baseball|last=Freedman|first=Lew|publisher=Lew Freedman|year=2007|isbn=978-0-313-33851-9|location=Greenwood Press, 88 Post Road West, Westport, CT 06881|pages=152}}</ref><ref>Hirsch, p. 13</ref> His father exposed him to baseball at an early age, playing catch with his son by the time Willie was five.<ref>Hirsch, p. 14</ref> At age 10, Mays was allowed to sit on the bench of his father's games in the Birmingham Industrial League, which Mays remembered as attracting six thousand fans per game at times.<ref>Mays, pp. 16-17</ref><ref name=\"Hirsch, p. 15\">Hirsch, p. 15</ref>\n\nMays played multiple sports at Fairfield Industrial High School, averaging a then-record 17 points a game in [[basketball]] and more than 40 yards a punt in [[American football|football]], while also playing quarterback.<ref>[http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/authors/w/willie_mays.html Willie Mays Quotes \u2013 BrainyQuote<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Since he started playing professional baseball while still in high school, he quit playing high school sports when he was 16.<ref>Mays, p. 32</ref> Mays graduated from Fairfield in 1950.<ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Willie_Mays.aspx Willie Mays Facts, information, pictures | Encyclopedia.com articles about Willie Mays<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Professional baseball==\n\n===Negro leagues===\nMays' [[professional baseball]] career began in 1947, while he was still in high school; he played briefly with the [[Chattanooga Choo-Choos]] in [[Tennessee]] during the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlbemuseum.com/history/players/mays.html|title=Willie Mays|work=Negro Leagues Baseball Museum|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Later that year, Mays joined the [[Birmingham Black Barons]] of the [[Negro American League]]. He had first caught the eye of Barons' manager [[Piper Davis]] in tenth grade, when Davis had Mays try out for the team. Davis encouraged Mays to work on hitting the [[curveball]], coached him periodically for a couple years, and gave Mays a chance to play for the Barons starting in 1947, when Mays was just 16.<ref>Mays, pp. 24, 26, 30</ref> When E. T. Oliver, principal at Mays's high school, threatened to suspend Mays for playing professional ball, Davis and Mays's father convinced him that Mays would still be able to concentrate on his studies.<ref>Mays, p. 32</ref> Mays helped Birmingham win the pennant and advance to the 1948 [[Negro League World Series]], which they lost 4-1 to the [[Homestead Grays]]. Mays hit a respectable .262 for the season, but it was also his excellent fielding and baserunning that made him a standout.<ref>Hirsch, p. 38-48</ref>\n\nOver the next several years, a number of major league baseball franchises sent scouts to watch him play. The first was the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]]. The scout who discovered him, Bud Maughn, had been following him for over a year and referred him to the Braves, who then packaged a deal that called for $7,500 down and $7,500 in 30 days. They also planned to give Mays $6,000. The obstacle in the deal was that Tom Hayes, owner of the [[Birmingham Black Barons]], wanted to keep Mays for the balance of the season. Had the team been able to act more quickly, the Braves franchise might have had both Mays and [[Hank Aaron]] in their outfield from 1954 to 1973. The [[Brooklyn Dodgers]] also scouted him and wanted Ray Blades to negotiate a deal, but they were too late. The New York Giants had already signed Mays for $4,000 and assigned him to their Class-B affiliate in [[Trenton, New Jersey]].<ref>June 22, 1950 letter from Eddie Montague to Jack Schwarz</ref>\n\n===Minor leagues===\nAccording to Mays, Eddie Montague had been sent to Birmingham to scout [[Alonzo Perry]] as a potential first baseman for the [[Sioux City Soos]] of the Class-A [[Western League (1900\u20131958)|Western League]], but Montague became interested in Mays instead after watching a doubleheader.<ref>Mays, pp. 44-45</ref> Due to a scandal in Sioux City concerning a Native American's burial in a whites-only cemetery at the time, Sioux City decided not to take Mays, and he was assigned to the [[Trenton Giants]] of the [[Interstate League]] instead.<ref>Mays, pp. 45-46</ref>\n\nAfter Mays batted .353 in Trenton, he began the 1951 season with the class AAA [[Minneapolis Millers]] of the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]]. During his short time span in Minneapolis, Mays played with two other future Hall of Famers: [[Hoyt Wilhelm]] and [[Ray Dandridge]]. Batting .477 in 35 games and playing excellent defense, Mays was called up to the Giants on May 24, 1951. Mays was at a [[movie theater]] in [[Sioux City, Iowa]] when he found out he was being called up. A message flashed up on the screen that said:  \"WILLIE MAYS CALL YOUR HOTEL.\"<ref>''The Giants of the Polo Grounds'' by Noel Hynd (1988). New York: Doubleday. page 358. {{ISBN|0-385 23790-1}}</ref>{{efn|Mays's autobiography has the account slightly differently. He remembered the houselights coming on in the middle of a movie and someone mounting the stage to announce, \"If Willie Mays is in the audience, would he please report immediately to his manager at the hotel.\"<ref>Mays, p. 60</ref>}} He appeared in his first major league game the next day in [[Philadelphia]]. Mays moved to [[Harlem, New York]], where his mentor was a [[New York State Boxing Commission]] official and former Harlem Rens basketball legend  \"Strangler\" [[Frank Forbes]].\n\n===Major leagues===\n\n====New York Giants (1951\u20131957)====\nMays began his major league career on a sour note, with no hits in his first 12 [[at bat]]s. On his 13th at-bat, however, he hit a towering home run up and over the left field roof of the [[Polo Grounds]] off future [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Warren Spahn]].<ref>[http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00016223.html ESPN.com: Mays brought joy to baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Spahn later joked, \"I'll never forgive myself. We might have gotten rid of Willie forever if I'd only struck him out.\"  Mays' batting average improved steadily throughout the rest of the season. Although his .274 average, 68 RBI and 20 homers (in 121 games) were among the lowest of his career, he still won the 1951 [[MLB Rookie of the Year award|Rookie of the Year Award]]. During the [[1951 New York Giants (MLB) season|Giants']] comeback in August and September 1951 to tie the [[1951 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Dodgers]] in the pennant race, Mays' fielding and strong throwing arm were instrumental to several important Giants victories.<ref>''Willie Mays'', by Matt von Albade, Tempo Books, Grosset & Dunlop, Inc. NY. copyright 1966, pp. 60\u201375 first printing, August 1966, [[Library of Congress]] Number 66-17205</ref> Mays was in the [[On-deck|on-deck circle]] when [[Bobby Thomson]] hit the [[Shot Heard 'Round the World (baseball)|Shot Heard 'Round the World]] against [[Ralph Branca]] and the Brooklyn Dodgers to win the three-game playoff 2-1 after the teams were tied at the end of the regular season.\n[[File:The Catch.png|thumb|left|The Catch: Mays hauls in [[Vic Wertz]]'s drive near the wall in Game 1 of the [[1954 World Series]].]]\n\nThe Giants went on to meet the [[1951 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] in the [[1951 World Series]]. In Game 1, Mays, [[Hank Thompson (baseball)|Hank Thompson]] and [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Monte Irvin]] comprised the first all-[[African-American]] outfield in major league history four years after the color line was broken.<ref>''Willie Mays'', by Arnold Hano, Tempo Books, Grosset & Dunlop, Inc. NY. copyright 1966, p.80 first printing, August 1966, [[Library of Congress]] Number 66-17205</ref> Mays hit poorly while the Giants lost the series 4\u20132. The six-game set was the only time that Mays and retiring Yankee slugger [[Joe DiMaggio]] (Mays's boyhood hero) would compete against each other.<ref>''[[The World Series|The Series]]'', an illustrated history of Baseball's postseason showcase, 1903\u20131993, [[The Sporting News]], copyright 1993, The Sporting News Publishing Co. pp. 144\u2013145 {{ISBN|0-89204-476-4}}</ref><ref>Mays, p. 92</ref>\n\n[[File:1952 Bowman Willie Mays.jpg|thumb|right|1952 [[Bowman Gum]] Willie Mays]]\n\n====U.S. Army (1952\u201353)====\nThe United States Army [[Conscription in the United States|drafted]] Mays in 1952 during the [[Korean War]] (1950\u201353) and he subsequently missed most of that season and all of the 1953 season. Mays spent much of his time in the Army playing baseball at [[Fort Eustis]], Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=388&pid=9039 |title=BIOPROJ.SABR.ORG :: The Baseball Biography Project<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=February 24, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070202211853/http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=388&pid=9039 |archive-date=February 2, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was at Fort Eustis that Mays learned the [[Glossary_of_baseball_(B)#basket_catch|basket catch]] from a fellow Fort Eustis outfielder, Al Fortunato. Mays missed about 266 games due to military service.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hanson |first=John A. |url=https://www.army.mil/article/200712/baseball_great_and_the_fort_eustis_connection |title=Baseball Great and the Fort Eustis Connection|work=U.S. Army |date=February 15, 2018|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====1954-57====\n\nIn 1954, Mays returned to the Giants and hit for a league-leading .345 batting average while slugging 41 home runs en route to his only World Series championship. Mays won the National League [[MLB Most Valuable Player award|Most Valuable Player Award]] and the [[Hickok Belt]] as top professional athlete of the year. He also became the first player in history to hit 30 home runs before the All-Star Game<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/30-or-more-home-runs-before-mlb-all-star-game-c266214234|title=Players with at least 30 HR by All-Star Game}}</ref> and was selected as an All-Star for the first of 19 consecutive seasons (20 total).<ref name=\"baseballhall.org\">Baseball Hall of Fame, Willie Mays, ''\"20-time All-Star\"'' [http://baseballhall.org/hof/Mays-willie] Retrieved April 10, 2015</ref><ref>Donnelly, Patrick. SportsData LLC. (2012). [http://www.sportsdatallc.com/2012/07/09/midsummer-classics-celebrating-mlbs-all-star-game ''Midsummer Classics: Celebrating MLB's All-Star Game''. 1959\u20131962: \" 'all players who were named to the AL or NL roster were credited with one appearance per season' \"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330031638/http://www.sportsdatallc.com/2012/07/09/midsummer-classics-celebrating-mlbs-all-star-game/ |date=March 30, 2015 }}, SportsData. Retrieved April 10, 2015.</ref> Mays had 38 through July 28, but around that time, manager [[Leo Durocher]] asked him to stop swinging for home runs, explaining that the team wanted him to reach base more so run producers like [[Monte Irvin]], [[Dusty Rhodes (outfielder)|Dusty Rhodes]], or [[Hank Thompson (baseball)|Hank Thompson]] could try to drive him home.<ref>Mays, pp. 112-113</ref><ref name=\"1954 Mays\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mayswi01&t=b&year=1954|title=Willie Mays 1954 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Mays only hit five home runs after July 8 but upped his batting average from .326 to .345 to win the batting title, becoming the first Giant to lead the league in average since [[Bill Terry]] hit .401 in 1930.<ref name=\"1954 Mays\"/><ref>Mays, p. 114</ref> The Giants won the [[National League pennant winners 1901-68|National League pennant]] and the [[1954 World Series]], sweeping the [[1954 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]] in four games. The 1954 series is perhaps best remembered for \"[[The Catch (baseball)|The Catch]]\", an over-the-shoulder running grab by Mays in deep center field of the Polo Grounds of a long drive off the bat of [[Vic Wertz]] during the eighth inning of Game 1. Considered the iconic image of Mays' playing career and one of baseball's most memorable fielding plays,<ref name=\"espn.go.com\">[http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00215053.html ESPN.com: The Say Hey Kid<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the catch prevented two Indian runners from scoring, preserving a tie game. Mays said he realized as he ran that he was going to have to make a running catch, which is why he did not turn to look at it until the ball was almost at the wall.<ref>Mays, pp. 117-118</ref> The Giants won the game in the 10th inning on a three-run home run by [[Dusty Rhodes (outfielder)|Dusty Rhodes]], with Mays scoring the winning run. The 1954 World Series was the team's last championship while based in New York. The next time the franchise won was 56 years later when the [[San Francisco Giants]] won the World Series in 2010.\n\n[[File:Willie Mays 1954.png|thumb|195px| Mays in 1954.]]\nMays went on to perform at a high level each of the last three years the Giants were in New York. In the middle of May, 1955, Durocher asked him to try for more home runs.<ref>Mays, pp. 128-29</ref> Mays led the league with 51. In 1956, he hit 36 homers and stole 40 bases, being only the second player, and first National League player, to join the \"[[30\u201330 club]]\". In 1957, the first season the [[Gold Glove]] award was presented, he won the first of 12 consecutive [[Gold Glove Award]]s. At the same time, Mays continued to finish in the National League's top-five in a variety of offensive categories. Mays, [[Roberto Clemente]] (also with 12), [[Al Kaline]], [[Andruw Jones]], [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]] and [[Ichiro Suzuki]] are the only outfielders to have ten or more career Gold Gloves. In 1957, Mays became the fourth player in major league history to join the [[20\u201320\u201320 club]] (2B, 3B, HR), something no player had accomplished since 1941. Mays also stole 38 bases that year, making him the second player in baseball history (after [[Frank Schulte]] in 1911) to reach 20 in each of those four categories (doubles, triples, homers, steals) in the same season.\n\n====San Francisco Giants (1958\u20131972)====\nAfter the 1957 season, the Giants franchise relocated to San Francisco, California. Mays bought two homes in San Francisco, then lived in nearby [[Atherton, California|Atherton]].<ref>[http://www.outsidelands.org/sw5.php Streetwise: Willie Mays \u2013 Western Neighborhoods Project \u2013 San Francisco History<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\"linge\">{{cite book |last1=Linge |first1=Mary Kay |title=Willie Mays: A Biography |date=2005 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=9780313334016 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H1cI1Q4PLBQC |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>{{rp|151}} Manager [[Bill Rigney]] wanted him to challenge [[Babe Ruth]]'s single-season home run record that year and did not play Mays much in spring training in hopes of using his best hitter every day in 1958.<ref>Mays, p. 148</ref> As he had in 1954, Mays vied for the National League batting title in 1958 until the final game of the season. Moved to the leadoff slot the last day to increase his at bats, Mays collected three hits in the game to finish with a career-high .347, but [[Philadelphia Phillies]]' [[Richie Ashburn]] won the title with a .350 batting average.<ref>Mays, p. 150</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SFN/SFN195809280.shtml|title=St. Louis Cardinals at San Francisco Giants Box Score, September 28, 1958|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Mays did manage to share the inaugural [[MLB Player of the Month|NL Player of the Month award]] with Stan Musial in May (no such award was given out in April until 1969), batting .405 with 12&nbsp;HR and 29 RBI; he won a second such award in September (.434, 4 HR, 18 RBIs). He played all but two games for the Giants, but his 29 home runs were his lowest total since returning from the military.\n\nOwner [[Horace Stoneham]] made Mays the highest-paid player in baseball with a $75,000 contract for 1959; Mays would be the highest-paid player through the 1972 season, with the exceptions of 1962 (when he and [[Mickey Mantle]] tied at $90,000) and 1966 (when [[Sandy Koufax]] received more in his final season).<ref>{{cite web|last=Haupert|first=Michael|url=https://sabr.org/research/mlbs-annual-salary-leaders-1874-2012|title=MLB's annual salary leaders since 1874|work=SABR|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Mays had his first serious injury in 1959, a collision with [[Sammy White (baseball)|Sammy White]] in spring training that resulted in 35 stitches in his leg and two weeks of exhibition ball missed; however, he was ready for the start of the season.<ref>Mays, p. 152</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mayswi01&t=b&year=1959|title=Willie Mays 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> During a series against the Reds in August, Mays also broke a finger but kept it a secret from other teams in order to keep opposing pitchers from throwing at it.<ref>Mays, p. 153</ref> In 1959, the Giants led by two games with only eight games to play, but only won two of their remaining games and finished fourth, as their pitching staff collapsed due to overwork of their top hurlers. The Dodgers won the pennant following a playoff with the [[Milwaukee Braves]].<ref>''The Sports Encyclopedia: Baseball (6th edition), 1985.</ref> As he did in New York, Mays would \"play around\" with kids playing sandlot ball in San Francisco. On three occasions in 1959 or 1960, he visited Julius Kahn Playground, five blocks from where he lived, including one time Giant players [[Jim Davenport]] and [[Tom Haller]].{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}{{clarify|date=September 2016}}\n\n[[Alvin Dark]] was hired to manage the Giants before the start of the 1961 season and named Mays team captain. The improving Giants finished 1961 in third place and won 85 games, more than any of the previous six campaigns. Mays had one of his best games on April 30, 1961, [[List of Major League Baseball single-game home run leaders|hitting four home runs]] and driving in eight runs in a 14\u20134 win against the Milwaukee Braves at [[County Stadium]]. Mays went 4-for-5 at the plate and was on deck for a chance to hit a record fifth home run when the Giants' half of the ninth inning ended.<ref>[http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1961/B04300MLN1961.htm April 30, 1961 box score and play-by-play]. Mays flied out to center field in leading off the fifth.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thebaseballpage.com/baseball-history/willie-mays-hits-4-homeruns |title=Willie Mays hits 4 homeruns |work=thebaseballpage.com |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 10, 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Mays is the only Major Leaguer to have both three triples in a game and four home runs in a game.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PHI/PHI196009150.shtml September 15, 1960 San Francisco Giants at Philadelphia Phillies Play by Play and Box Score] ''Baseball-Reference''</ref><ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MLN/MLN196104300.shtml April 30, 1961 San Francisco Giants at Milwaukee Braves Box Score and Play by Play] ''Baseball-Reference''</ref> According to Mays, the four-homer game came after a night in which he got sick eating spareribs; Mays was not even sure he would play the next day until batting practice.<ref>Mays, pp. 166-167</ref>\n\nMays led the team in eight offensive categories in 1962. He hit a game-winning home run in the eighth inning against [[Turk Farrell]] of the [[Houston Astros|Houston Colt .45's]] in the Giants' final regularly-scheduled game of the year September 30, forcing the team into a tie for first place with the [[1962 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>Mays, p. 176</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SFN/SFN196209300.shtml|title=Houston Colt .45s at San Francisco Giants Box Score, September 30, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 23, 2020</ref> The Giants went on to win a three-game playoff series against the Dodgers, advancing to play in the [[1962 World Series|World Series]]. The Giants lost to the [[1962 New York Yankees season|Yankees]] in seven games, and Mays batted .250 with two extra-base hits. It was his last World Series appearance as a member of the Giants.\n\nBefore the 1963 season, Mays signed a contract worth a record-setting $105,000 per season ({{Inflation|US|105000|1963|fmt=eq}}) in the same offseason during which [[Mickey Mantle]] signed a deal for what would have been a record-tying $100,000 per season.<ref name=\"linge\" />{{rp|125}}\n\nIn the 1963 and 1964 seasons Mays batted in over 100 runs and hit 85 total home runs. On July 2, 1963, Mays played in a game when future [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Fame]] members [[Warren Spahn]] and [[Juan Marichal]] each threw 15 scoreless innings. In the bottom of the 16th inning, Mays hit a home run off Spahn for a 1\u20130 Giants victory.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SFN/SFN196307020.shtml July 2, 1963 Milwaukee Braves at San Francisco Giants Box Score and Play by Play] ''Baseball-Reference''</ref> He won his third NL Player of the Month Award in August (.387, 8 HR, 27 RBI). Normally the third hitter in the lineup, Mays was moved to fourth in the lineup in 1964 before returning to third in subsequent years.<ref>Mays, p. 238</ref> Mays took part in another long game May 31, 1964, when, after playing all nine innings of the first Game of a doubleheader against the [[New York Mets]], he played all 23 innings of the Giants' 8-6 victory in Game 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYN/NYN196405312.shtml|title=San Francisco Giants at New York Mets Box Score, May 31, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> He was moved to [[shortstop]] for three innings of the game and grew so tired over the course of it that he used a 31-ounce bat (four ounces smaller than his standard) for his final at bat, in the 23rd inning.<ref>Mays, pp. 213-14</ref>\n\nA torn shoulder muscle sustained in a game against Atlanta impaired Mays's ability to throw in 1965. He compensated for this by keeping the injury a secret from opposing players, making two or three practice throws before games to discourage players from running on him.<ref>Mays, p. 217</ref> Mays won his second MVP award in 1965 behind a career-high 52 home runs. On August 22, 1965, Mays and [[Sandy Koufax]] acted as peacemakers during a 14-minute brawl between the Giants and Dodgers after San Francisco pitcher [[Juan Marichal]] had bloodied Dodgers catcher [[John Roseboro]] with a bat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCI/is_10_59/ai_65131125/pg_6 |title=Letting Off Steam \u2013 confrontations between players, fans and umpires |first=George |last=Vass |year=2000 |work=Baseball Digest |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014021253/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCI/is_10_59/ai_65131125/pg_6 |archivedate=October 14, 2008 }}</ref> Mays grabbed Roseboro by the waist and helped him off the field, then tackled [[Lou Johnson]] to keep him from attacking an umpire. Johnson kicked him in the head and nearly knocked him out. After the brawl, Mays hit a game-winning three-run home run against the Koufax, but he did not finish the game, feeling dizzy after the home run.<ref>Mays, pp. 222-223</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SFN/SFN196508220.shtml|title=Los Angeles Dodgers at San Francisco Giants Box Score, August 22, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Mays also won his fourth and final NL Player of the Month award in August (.363, 17&nbsp;HR, 29 RBI), while setting the NL record for most home runs in the month of August (since tied by Sammy Sosa in 2001). On September 13, 1965, he hit his 500th career home run off [[Don Nottebart]]. Warren Spahn, off whom Mays hit his first career home run, was his teammate at the time. After the home run, Spahn greeted Mays in the dugout, asking \"Was it anything like the same feeling?\" Mays replied \"It was exactly the same feeling. Same pitch, too.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/archive/2004/04/15/SPGKS61N7V12.DTL | title=The majesty of Mays | first=Charles | last=Einstein | date=April 15, 2004 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>{{efn|Mays's autobiography records the conversation slightly differently. \"I threw you the first one and now I've seen the five-hundredth,\" Spahn said. \"Was it the same feeling?\" \"Same feeling. Same pitch,\" Mays replied.<ref name=\"p. 225\">Mays, p. 225</ref>}} The next night, Mays hit one that he considered his most dramatic. With the Giants trailing the Astros by two runs with two outs in the ninth, Mays swung and missed at the first two pitches, took three balls to load the count, and fouled off three pitches before hitting the tying home run off [[Claude Raymond (baseball)|Claude Raymond]] on the ninth pitch of the at bat. The Giants went on to win 6-5 in 10 innings.<ref name=\"p. 225\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/HOU/HOU196509140.shtml|title=San Francisco Giants at Houston Astros Box Score, September 14, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMays played in over 150 games for 13 consecutive years (a major-league record) from 1954 to 1966. Mays tied [[Mel Ott]]'s NL record of 511 home runs on April 24 against the Astros. After that, he went nine days without a home run. \"I started thinking home run every time I got up,\" Mays explained his slump.<ref>Mays, p. 231</ref> He finally set the record May 4 with his 512th against [[Claude Osteen]] of the Dodgers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mayswi01&t=b&year=1966|title=Willie Mays 1966 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In 1966, his last with 100 RBIs, Mays finished third in the National League MVP voting. It was the ninth and final time he finished in the top five in the voting for the award.<ref>He also finished sixth in the balloting three times.</ref><ref>[https://www.baseballprospectus.com/news/article/2278/they-wuz-robbed-tales-of-head-scratching-mvp-voting/ They Wuz Robbed: Tales of Head-Scratching MVP Voting], ''Baseball Prospectus'', Mark Armour, September 5, 2003.  This article presents a case that Mays should have won the MVP for the National League a minimum of 5 times and perhaps as many as 9 times.  Instead, the author argues his case that baseball writers like to both spread the wealth and recognize key players on pennant-winning teams.</ref> In 1970, the ''[[Sporting News]]'' named Mays as the 1960s \"Player of the Decade.\"\n\nMays had 12 home runs and 38 RBI through his first 60 games of 1967 but went into a slump after that.<ref name=\"1967 Mays\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mayswi01&t=b&year=1967|title=Willie Mays 1967 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> He came down with a fever July 14 and asked manager [[Herman Franks]]'s permission for the night off but then had to play anyway after [[Ty Cline]], his replacement, hurt himself in the first inning. Mays left the game after the sixth due to fatigue and spent the next five days in a hospital. \"After I got back into the lineup, I never felt strong again for the rest of the season.\"<ref>Mays, p. 236</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SFN/SFN196707140.shtml|title=Houston Astros at San Francisco Giants Box Score, July 14, 1967|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In 141 games (his lowest total since returning from the war), Mays hit .263 with 83 runs scored, 128 hits, and 22 home runs. He had only 70 RBI for the year, the first time since 1958 he had failed to reach 100.\n\n\"Maybe if I played a little first base in 1968, I could keep from getting tired,\" Mays speculated in his autobiography, but he only played one game at the position all year.<ref>Mays, p. 237</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mayswi01&t=b&year=1968|title=Willie Mays 1968 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In Houston for a series against the Astros May 6, Mays was presented by Astro owner [[Roy Hofheinz]] with a 569-pound birthday cake for his 37th birthday\u2014the pounds represented all the home runs Mays had hit in his career. After sharing some of it with his teammates, Mays sent the rest to the [[Texas Children's Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1968/05/20/people|title=People|work=Sports Illustrated|date=May 20, 1968|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> He played 148 games and upped his batting average to .289, accumulating 84 runs scored, 144 hits, 23 home runs, and 79 RBI.\n\nIn 1969, new Giants' manager [[Clyde King]] moved Mays to the leadoff role. King explained to Mays that this was because he was not \"hitting home runs like he used to.\" Mays did not complain about the move in public that year but privately chafed at it, saying in his 1988 autobiography it was like \"[[O. J. Simpson]] blocking for the [[Fullback (gridiron football)|fullback]].\"<ref>Mays, pp. 238-39</ref> Mays hit his 600th home run off San Diego's [[Mike Corkins]] in September 1969. He said of the milestone, \"Winning the game was more important to me than any individual achievements.\"<ref>Mays, p. 241</ref> Plagued by injuries that season, he managed only 13 home runs. Mays enjoyed a resurgence in 1970, hitting 28 homers, and got off to a fast start in 1971, the year he turned 40. He had 15 home runs and a .290 average at the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] break but faded down the stretch, only hitting three home runs and batting .241 for the rest of the year.<ref name=\"1971 Mays\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mccovwi01&t=b&year=1971|title=Willie Mays 1971 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> One reason he hit so few home runs was that Mays walked 112 times, 30 more times than he had at any point in his career. This was partly because [[Willie McCovey]], who often batted behind Mays in the lineup, missed several games with injuries, causing pitchers to pitch carefully to Mays so they could concentrate on getting less-skilled hitters out.<ref>Mays, p. 246</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mccovwi01&t=b&year=1971|title=Willie McCovey 1971 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Mays helped the Giants win the division title that year, but they lost the [[NLCS]] to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].\n\nDuring his time on the Giants, Mays and fellow player [[Bobby Bonds]] were friends. When Bobby's son, [[Barry Bonds]], was born, Bobby asked Mays to be Barry's godfather. Mays and the younger Bonds have maintained a close relationship ever since.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://blogcritics.org/sports/article/q-are-barry-bonds-and-willie/ |title=Q: Are Barry Bonds and Willie Mays Related? {{!}} Blogcritics |access-date=February 19, 2013 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20130414102119/http://blogcritics.org/sports/article/q-are-barry-bonds-and-willie/ |archive-date=April 14, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n====New York Mets (1972\u201373)====\nIn May 1972, 41-year-old Mays was traded to the [[New York Mets|Mets]] for pitcher [[Charlie Williams (pitcher)|Charlie Williams]] and $50,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|50000|1972|r=-4}}}} today).<ref name=\"trade\">{{cite web |title=Mays Trade (at bottom) |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mayswi01.shtml |accessdate=October 22, 2006}}</ref> At the time, the Giants franchise was losing money. Owner [[Horace Stoneham]] could not guarantee Mays a pension after retirement and the Mets offered Mays a coaching position upon his retirement.<ref>Shaun McCormack, ''Willie Mays'' (Rosen Publishing Group, 2003).</ref>\n\nMays had remained popular in New York long after the Giants had left for San Francisco, and the trade was seen as a public relations coup for the Mets. Mets owner [[Joan Whitney Payson|Joan Payson]], who was a minority shareholder of the Giants when the team was in New York, had long desired to bring Mays back to his baseball roots and was instrumental in making the trade.<ref>Post, Paul; and Lucas, Ed. [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCI/is_3_62/ai_96992901 \"Turn back the clock: Willie Mays played a vital role on '73 mets; despite his age, future Hall of Famer helped young New York club capture the 1973 National League pennant\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506110035/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCI/is_3_62/ai_96992901 |date=May 6, 2007 }}, ''[[Baseball Digest]]'', March 2003. Accessed July 15, 2008. \"Mets owner Joan Payson had always wanted to bring the 'Say Hey Kid' back to his baseball roots, and she finally pulled it off in a deal that shocked the baseball world.\"</ref> In his Mets debut on a rainy Sunday afternoon at [[Shea Stadium]] on May 14, 1972, Mays put New York ahead to stay with a fifth-inning home run against [[Don Carrithers]] and his former team, the Giants. On August 16, 1973 of the following season, in a game against the [[Cincinnati Reds]] with [[Don Gullett]] on the mound, Mays hit a fourth inning solo home run over the right-center field fence. It was the 660th and final home run of his major league career.\n\nMays played a season and a half with the Mets before retiring; he appeared in 133 games. The Mets honored him on September 25, 1973 (Willie Mays Night), where he thanked the New York fans and said goodbye to baseball. He considered making that his final game, but Payson convinced him to finish out the season.<ref>Mays, p. 256</ref> He finished his career in the [[1973 World Series]], which the [[1973 New York Mets season|Mets]] lost to the [[1973 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] in seven games. Mays got the first hit of the Series, but had only seven at-bats (with two hits). The final hit of his career came in Game 2, a key single to help the Mets win. He also fell down in the outfield during a play where he was hindered by the glare of the sun and by the hard outfield. Mays later said, \"growing old is just a helpless hurt.\" His final at bat came on October 16, in Game 3 where he came in as a pinch hitter but grounded into a [[force play]]. Mays had made his 20th and last All-Star appearance (20 seasons)<ref name=\"baseballhall.org\"/> and 24th All-Star Game appearance<ref name=\"sportsdatallc.com\"/> on July 24, 1973 when he was used as a pinch hitter.\n\nIn 1972 and 1973, Mays was the oldest regular position player in baseball. At age 42, he became the oldest position player to appear in a World Series game.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Willie's Time'', by [[Charles Einstein]]</ref>\nMays retired after the 1973 season with a lifetime batting average of .302 and 660 home runs. His lifetime total of 7,095 outfield [[putouts]] remains the major league record.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/PO_of_career.shtml |title=Career Leaders & Records for Putouts as OF |website=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=February 11, 2011}}</ref> Mays is the only major league player to have hit a home run in every inning from the 1st through the 16th innings.<ref>[http://sabr.org/research/offbeat-record-held-willie-mays An Offbeat Record Held By Willie Mays | SABR<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He finished his career with a record 22 extra-inning home runs.  He has the third-highest career [[power\u2013speed number]], behind [[Barry Bonds]] and [[Rickey Henderson]], at 447.1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/power_speed_number_progress.shtml |title=Progressive Leaders & Records for Power-Speed # |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.sabr.org/brj/index.php/thunder-and-lightning |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415210240/http://research.sabr.org/brj/index.php/thunder-and-lightning |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 15, 2013 |title=Thunder and Lightning |publisher=Research.sabr.org |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nMays was a popular figure in [[Harlem, New York|Harlem]]. Magazine photographers were fond of chronicling his participation in local stickball games with kids. It was said that in the urban game of hitting a rubber ball with an adapted broomstick handle, Mays could hit a shot that measured \"six sewers\" (the distance of six consecutive New York City manhole covers, nearly 300 feet).<ref>[http://www.500hrc.com/600-hrc-articles/willie-mays-learned-to-hit-curveball-playing-stickball-with-kids-during-rookie-year-in-the-bigs.html Jim Rednour, ''Willie Mays Learned To Hit Curveball Playing Stickball with Kids During Rookie Year In The Bigs''] Retrieved April 9, 2011,</ref><ref>[http://harlembespoke.blogspot.com/2011/01/see-willie-mays-in-harlem.html Willie Mays & Stickball in Harlem] Retrieved April 9, 2011</ref> Once he got married, Mays stopped playing stickball in order to devote more time to his family.<ref>Mays, p. 133</ref>\n\nSudden collapses plagued Mays sporadically throughout his career, which occasionally led to hospital stays. He attributed them to his style of play. \"My style was always to go all out, whether I played four innings or nine. That's how I played all my life, and I think that's the reason I would suddenly collapse from exhaustion or nervous energy or whatever it was called.\"<ref>Mays, p. 148</ref>\n\nDuring his career, Mays would charge a hundred dollars per on-air interview, more than the standard twenty-five dollars at the time. However, he would split the money four ways and give it to the last four players on the Giants' roster.<ref>Mays, p. 270</ref>\n\n==Post-MLB baseball==\n[[File:First Lady Betty Ford and Queen Elizabeth II of Great Britain Greeting Baseball Player Willie Mays in the Receiving Line on the South Driveway of the White House Prior to a State Dinner Honoring Her Majesty and Prince Philip.jpg|thumb|Mays with [[Queen Elizabeth II]] (center) and First Lady [[Betty Ford]] (left) at the [[White House]] in 1976]]\n[[File:Willie Mays George W Bush 1.jpg|thumb|Mays walks with [[George W. Bush|President Bush]], July 30, 2006]]\nAfter Mays retired as a player, he remained an active personality. Just as he had during his playing days, Mays continued to appear on various TV shows, in films and in other forms of non-sports-related media. He remained in the New York Mets organization as their hitting instructor until the end of the 1979 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mays on the IMDBb |url=http://imdb.com/name/nm0563092/ |accessdate=October 22, 2006}}</ref> It was there where he taught future Mets star [[Lee Mazzilli]] his famous basket catch.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newyork.mets.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080908&content_id=3438789&vkey=news_nym&fext=.jsp&c_id=nym |title=For Mazzilli, nothing like meeting Mays |website= mlb.com |first=Marty|last=Noble|date=September 8, 2008 |access-date=August 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216001646/http://newyork.mets.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080908&content_id=3438789&vkey=news_nym&fext=.jsp&c_id=nym |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 1979, Mays was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in his first year of eligibility. He garnered 409 of the 432 ballots cast (94.68%);<ref>http://www.baseballhalloffame.org/history/hof_voting/year/1979.htm{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=Red Director |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> referring to the other 23 voters, acerbic ''[[New York Daily News]]'' columnist [[Dick Young (sportswriter)|Dick Young]] wrote, \"If Jesus Christ were to show up with his old baseball glove, some guys wouldn't vote for him. He [[Stations of the Cross|dropped the cross three times]], didn't he?\"<ref name=\"espn.go.com\" /> In his induction speech, Mays said, \"What can I say? This country is made up of a great many things. You can grow up to be what you want. I chose baseball, and I loved every minute of it. I give you one word\u2014love. It means dedication. You have to sacrifice many things to play baseball. I sacrificed a bad marriage and I sacrificed a good marriage. But I'm here today because baseball is my number one love.\"<ref>Mays, p. 262</ref>\n\nMays took up [[golf]] a few years after his promotion to the major leagues and quickly became an accomplished player, playing to a handicap of about nine.<ref name=\"page 276\">Mays, p. 276</ref> \"I realized I could use a sport to keep me active once I hung up the glove,\" Mays said of golf. \"I approach it the same way I did baseball. I want to win.\"<ref name=\"page 276\"/> He discovered during the 1960s \"that people would pay tremendous amounts of money just to play a round of golf with me. And, what the heck, I loved golf.\"<ref>Mays, p. 227</ref> After he retired, he played golf frequently in the San Francisco area.<ref>''Willie Mays: The Life, The Legend'', by James Hirsch, 2010.</ref>\n\nShortly after his Hall of Fame election, Mays took a job at the Park Place Casino (now [[Bally's Atlantic City]]) in [[Atlantic City]], [[New Jersey]]. While there, he served as a Special Assistant to the Casino's President and as a greeter. After being told by [[Baseball Commissioner]] [[Bowie Kuhn]] that he could not be a coach and baseball goodwill ambassador while at the same time working for Bally's, Mays chose to terminate his baseball relationships.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19791030&id=lktNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FjMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5264,5004502 Mays leaves baseball]</ref> In 1985 [[Peter Ueberroth]], Kuhn's successor, decided to allow Mays and [[Mickey Mantle]] to return to baseball.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2506&dat=19850319&id=iQBgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rQwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1143,6453714 Ueberroth reinstates Mays, Mantle to baseball]</ref> Like Mays, Mantle had gone to work for an Atlantic City casino and had to give up any baseball positions he held.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=19830209&id=2lUvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=39oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1579,1421041 Bowie bounces Mantle]</ref>\n\nAt the [[Pittsburgh drug trials]] in 1985, former Mets teammate [[John Milner]] testified that Mays kept a bottle of liquid amphetamine in his locker at [[Shea Stadium]]. Milner admitted, however, that he had never seen Mays use amphetamines and Mays himself denied ever having taken any drugs during his career.<ref>{{cite web|date=September 13, 1985|title=Mays' Locker Was Source of Amphetamines--Milner|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-09-13/sports/sp-22701_1_willie-mays|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSince 1986, Mays has served as Special Assistant to the President of the San Francisco Giants. Mays' number 24 is retired by the San Francisco Giants. [[Oracle Park]], the Giants stadium, is located at 24 ''Willie Mays Plaza''. In front of the main entrance to the stadium is a larger-than-life statue of Mays. He also serves on the advisory board of the [[Baseball Assistance Team]], a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization dedicated to helping former Major League, Minor League, and Negro league players through financial and medical difficulties.\n\n==Special honors and tributes==\n[[File:Willie Mays 2008-09-28.jpg|thumb|Mays on September 28, 2008]]\n{{MLBBioRet\n| Image = SFGiants_24.png\n| Name = Willie Mays\n| Number = 24\n| Team = San Francisco Giants\n| Year = 1972\n}}\nFollowing Mays's MVP season of 1965, [[Sargent Shriver]], head of the United States [[Job Corps]], and Vice President [[Hubert H. Humphrey]] asked Mays to speak to kids in the Job Corps. \"Willie, the kids will listen to you. All you have to do is talk to them. They look up to you,\" Humphrey told Mays. Set to go on a nationwide tour, Mays passed out for five to ten minutes just before a meeting in [[Salt Lake City]]. He returned to San Francisco to rest, and Lou Johnson (whom he'd battled in a brawl earlier that year) stepped in to take his place.<ref>Mays, pp. 227-28</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1965/11/29/people|title=People|work=Sports Illustrated|date=November 29, 1965|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1966/01/10/people|title=People|work=Sports Illustrated|date=January 10, 1966|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Mays received the Golden Plate Award of the [[Academy of Achievement|American Academy of Achievement]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Golden Plate Awardees of the American Academy of Achievement |website=www.achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url=  https://achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/#sports}}</ref>\n\nWhen Mays' [[godson]] [[Barry Bonds]] tied him for third on the all-time home run list, Mays greeted and presented him with a diamond-studded [[Olympic torch]] (given to Mays when he carried the torch during its tour through the United States). In 1992, when Bonds signed a free agent contract with the Giants, Mays personally offered Bonds his retired #24 (the number Bonds wore in [[Pittsburgh Pirates|Pittsburgh]]) but Bonds declined, electing to wear #25 instead, honoring his father, [[Bobby Bonds]], who wore that number with the Giants.<ref>{{Cite news |date=December 11, 1992 |title=Bonds to Wear No. 25 |newspaper=New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/11/sports/sports-people-baseball-bonds-to-wear-no-25.html}}</ref>\n\nWillie Mays Day was proclaimed by former mayor [[Willie Brown (politician)|Willie Brown]] and reaffirmed by mayor [[Gavin Newsom]] to be every May 24 in San Francisco, paying tribute not only to his birth in the month (May 6), but also to his name (Mays) and jersey number (24). The date is also the anniversary of his call-up to the major leagues.<ref>''Willie Mays: The Life, The Legend'', by [[James S. Hirsch|James Hirsch]]</ref>\n\nOn May 24, 2004, during the 50-year anniversary of [[The Catch (baseball)|The Catch]], Mays received an honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters degree from [[Yale University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yale.edu/opa/campus/2004_commencement/honorands.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 22, 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040604042534/http://www.yale.edu/opa/campus/2004_commencement/honorands.html |archivedate=June 4, 2004 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 6, 2005, he received the [[Bobby Bragan Youth Foundation]] ''Lifetime Achievement Award'' for his accomplishments on and off the field.\n\nOn July 30, 2006, he was the Tee Ball Commissioner at the 2006 [[White House Tee Ball Initiative]].<ref>[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2006/07/20060724-1.html White House South Lawn Tee Ball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn June 10, 2007, Mays received an honorary [[doctorate]] from [[Dartmouth College]].\n\nAt the [[2007 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2007 All-Star Game]] in San Francisco, Mays received a special tribute for his legendary contributions to the game and threw out the ceremonial first pitch.\n\nOn December 5, 2007, California Governor [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] and First Lady [[Maria Shriver]] inducted Mays into the [[California Hall of Fame]], located at [[The California Museum for History, Women and the Arts]].<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=California Museum |title=Mays inducted into California Hall of Fame |url=http://www.californiamuseum.org/Exhibits/Hall-of-Fame/inductees.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110182937/https://www.californiamuseum.org/Exhibits/Hall-of-Fame/inductees.html |date=January 10, 2008 |url-status=dead |archivedate=January 10, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barack Obama and Willie Mays in Air Force One 2009-07-14.jpg|thumb|President Barack Obama and Mays aboard Air Force One, July 14, 2009.]]\nOn June 4, 2008, Community Board 10 in [[Harlem]] voted unanimously to give the name \"Willie Mays Drive\" to an eight-block service road that connects to the Harlem River Drive from 155th Street to 163rd Street, running adjacent to the Polo Grounds.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lombardi |first=Frank |date=July 5, 2008 |title=Street fight leaves Willie Mays benched |newspaper=New York Daily News |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2008/07/05/2008-07-05_street_fight_leaves_willie_mays_benched.html}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2009, Mays gave the commencement address at [[San Francisco State University]] and received an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters.\n\nOn July 14, 2009, he accompanied [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] to [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] aboard [[Air Force One]] for the [[Major League Baseball|Major League]] [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]].<ref>{{YouTube|4pbOtfa7_ok|Willie Mays aboard Air Force One with President Obama}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2010, he was inducted into the African-American Ethnic Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.budwinter.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/OaklandInductionCeremony_HOFver2.pdf|title=African American Ethnic Sports Hall of Fame Annual Bay Area Induction Ceremony|work=budwinter.com|accessdate=July 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814055134/http://www.budwinter.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/OaklandInductionCeremony_HOFver2.pdf|archive-date=August 14, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2010, on the occasion of his 79th birthday, Mays appeared on the floor of the [[California State Senate]] where they proclaimed it Willie Mays Day in the state.\n\nOn May 15, 2010, Mays was awarded the Major League Baseball Beacon of Life Award at the Civil Rights game at Great American Ball Park.\n\nMays has been mentioned or referenced in many popular songs. [[The Treniers]] recorded the song \"Say Hey (The Willie Mays Song)\" in 1955. The band [[Widespread Panic]] makes reference to Mays in the song \"One Arm Steve\" from their album ''[['Til the Medicine Takes]]''. [[Terry Cashman]]'s song \"[[Talkin' Baseball]]\" has the refrain \"Willie, Mickey and the Duke\", which subsequently became the title of an award given by the New York Baseball Writers Association.<ref>[http://www.baseball-almanac.com/awards/willie_mickey_and_the_duke_award.shtml Willie, Mickey and the Duke Award]</ref> [[John Fogerty]] mentioned Mays, [[Ty Cobb]] and [[Joe DiMaggio]] in his song \"[[Centerfield (song)|Centerfield]]\". His name was also used on the album ''[[The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan]]'' in the song \"I Shall Be Free\", and in [[Gil Scott-Heron]]'s song \"[[The Revolution Will Not Be Televised]].\" [[Chuck Prophet]] and Kurt Lipschutz (pen name, klipschutz) co-wrote the song \"Willie Mays is Up at Bat\" for Prophet's 2012 ''[[Temple Beautiful]]'' album, a tribute to San Francisco. Mays is also mentioned in \"Our Song\" by singer-songwriter [[Joe Henry]] from the 2007 album ''[[Civilian s (Joe Henry album)|Civilians]]''.  He is also the subject of the 1994 [[Americana music]] song \"Homerun Willie\" by [[John Dunnigan]].\n\nMays was mentioned numerous times in [[Charles M. Schulz]]'s comic strip ''[[Peanuts]]''. One of the most famous of these strips was originally published on February 9, 1966. In it, [[Charlie Brown]] is competing in a class spelling bee and he is asked to spell the word, \"Maze\". He erroneously spells it M-A-Y-S and screams out his dismay when he is eliminated. When Charlie Brown is later sent to the principal's office for raising his voice at the teacher regarding the incident, he wonders if one day he will meet Willie Mays and will have a good laugh together about the incident.<ref>[http://schulzmuseum.org/willie-mays-and-a-charlie-brown-christmas/ Charles M. Schulz MuseumWillie Mays and A Charlie Brown Christmas | Charles M. Schulz Museum<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nWillie Mays Parkway and Willie Mays Park in [[Orlando, Florida]] were named after Mays.\n\nMays also appears on [[Calle 13 (band)|Calle 13]]'s \"Adentro\" music video, where he gives to lead singer, [[Ren\u00e9 P\u00e9rez]] a bag containing a pair of sunglasses, a [[Roberto Clemente]] baseball uniform, and a baseball bat signed by him, which then was used by Ren\u00e9 to destroy his own luxury car, a [[Maserati]], in an attempt to spread a message to youth about how irresponsible promoting of ostentatious luxury excesses in urban music as a status symbol, have them all killing each other.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calle 13 grab\u00f3 video junto al legendario beisbolista Willie Mays|url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/entretencion/musica/calle-13/calle-13-grabo-video-junto-al-legendario-beisbolista-willie-mays/2014-03-05/164733.html|publisher=Cooperativa.cl|accessdate=March 9, 2014|author=Cooperativa.cl|language=Spanish|year=2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cantor-Navas|first=Judy|title=Willie Mays Appears in Calle 13's New Video: Watch|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/5930141/willie-mays-appears-in-calle-13-video-watch-adentro|work=Billboard|publisher=Billboard.com|accessdate=March 9, 2014|date=March 6, 2014 <!-- 6:21 PM EST -->}}</ref>\n\nIn the movies ''[[Major League (film)|Major League]]'' and ''[[Major League II]]'', the center fielder for the [[Cleveland Indians]] is named Willie Mays Hayes. He was originally portrayed by a then-unknown [[Wesley Snipes]], but [[Omar Epps]] replaced Snipes in the sequel.\n\n===1956 Willie Mays Major League Negro-American All-Stars Tour===\nIn 1956, Mays persuaded many of Major League Baseball's biggest black stars to go on a tour around the country after the season had ended to play exhibition games. While much of the tour was undocumented, one venue was Andrews Field,<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/park.cgi?id=AR010 Andrews Field Minor League History] ''Baseball-Reference''</ref> located in [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], on October 16. Among the players who played in that game were Mays, [[Frank Robinson]], [[Hank Aaron]], [[Elston Howard]], [[Monte Irvin]], [[Gene Baker]], [[Charles Johnson (baseball, born 1909)|Charlie Johnson]], [[Sam Jones (baseball)|Sam Jones]], [[Hank Thompson (baseball)|Hank Thompson]] and [[Joe Black]].\n\n===Presidential Medal of Freedom===\n\nIn November 2015, Mays was awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] by [[President Barack Obama]] during a ceremony at the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2015/11/16/yogi-berra-willie-mays-are-recipients-of-presidential-medal-of-freedom-president-obama/75889844/ | title=Yogi Berra, Willie Mays are recipients of the Presidential Medal of Freedom | work=[[USA Today]] | date=November 16, 2015 | accessdate=November 16, 2015 | author=Boeck, Scott}}</ref><ref name=NBC112515>Phil Helsel \u2013 [http://www.aol.com/article/2015/11/24/obama-honoring-spielberg-streisand-and-more-with-medal-of-freed/21272337/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl3%7Csec1_lnk3%26pLid%3D-40526639 \"Obama honoring Spielberg, Streisand and more with medal of freedom,\"] ''NBC News'', November 24, 2015. Retrieved November 25, 2015</ref> At the ceremony Obama credited Mays' baseball career with his own success, saying, \"Willie also served our country: In his quiet example while excelling on one of America's biggest stages [he] helped carry forward the banner of civil rights\", adding, \"It's because of giants like Willie that someone like me could even think about running for president.\"<ref name=NBC112515/>\n\n===Willie Mays World Series Most Valuable Player Award===\n\nIn September 2017, Major League Baseball announced their decision to rename the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award]] after Mays, and it has since been referred to as the Willie Mays World Series Most Valuable Player Award. The first recipient of the rechristened award was Houston Astros Outfielder, [[George Springer]].\n\n==Television appearances==\nIn addition to appearances in baseball documentaries and on talk shows, Mays has appeared in several sitcoms over the years, always as himself. He appeared as the mystery guest during different incarnations of the long-running game show ''[[What's My Line?]]''. He was in three episodes of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'': \"Play Ball\" and \"My Son the Catcher\" (both 1964) and \"Calling Willie Mays\" (1966). Also in 1966, he appeared in the \"Twitch or Treat\" episode of ''[[Bewitched]]'', in which Darrin Stephens asks if Mays is a warlock, and Samantha Stephens replies, \"The way he hits?  What else?\"<ref>{{cite episode|first1=William|last1=Asher|first2=Robert Riley|last2=Crutcher|first3=James S.|last3=Henerson|title=Twitch or Treat|series=Bewitched|date=October 27, 1966|network=ABC|season=3}}</ref> \n\nIn 1989, Mays appeared in ''[[My Two Dads]]'', in the episode \"You Love Me, Right?\", and in the episode \"The Field\" of ''[[Mr. Belvedere]]''. Additionally, he performed \"Say Hey: The Willie Mays Song\" on episode 4.46 of the ''[[Colgate Comedy Hour]]'' in 1954.<ref>{{IMDb name|0563092|Willie Mays}}</ref> Years later, Mays made a cameo appearance on a 2004 episode of ''[[Wheel of Fortune (American game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'', while the series was taping on location in [[San Francisco]]. On February 10, 2010, Mays appeared on ''[[The Daily Show]]'', discussing his career and a new biography, ''Willie Mays: The Life, the Legend'', by [[James S. Hirsch]].<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://thedailyshow.cc.com/episodes/f1nm9c/february-10--2010---willie-mays |title=FEBRUARY 10, 2010 \u2013 WILLIE MAYS|work=[[The Daily Show]] |date = February 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMays also voiced himself in the 1972 animated film ''[[Willie Mays and the Say-Hey Kid]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMays married Marghuerite Wendell Chapman (1926\u20132010), a woman who had been married twice before, in 1956. Mays said, \"We decided to get married so quickly, we had to go to [[Elkton, Maryland]], where you didn't have to wait.\"<ref name=\"page six\"/><ref>Mays, pp. 133-134</ref> They adopted a son Michael, five days after he was born in 1959.<ref name=\"page six\">Hirsch, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"page 152\">Mays, p. 152</ref> Mays remembered driving Michael around the block as an infant to put him to sleep.<ref name=\"page 152\"/> The couple separated in 1962, with Marghuerite taking Michael for the majority of the time. They formally divorced in 1963. The divorce hearings often took place the mornings of Giants games, once causing Mays to be late to one.<ref>Mays, pp. 201-02</ref> Eight years later, Mays married Mae Louise Allen.<ref name=\"Mae obit\"/> [[Wilt Chamberlain]] gave Mays her number in 1961, and they had their first date in Pittsburgh when the Giants were in town for a Pirates game. They dated off and on the next several years before Mays finally proposed; they were married in Mexico City over Thanksgiving weekend in 1971.<ref>Mays, pp. 248-249</ref> She died on April 19, 2013, after a long battle with Alzheimer's disease.<ref name=\"Mae obit\">{{cite news |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/giants/2013/04/19/willie-mays-wife-mae-dies-at-74/ |title=Willie Mays' wife, Mae, dies at 74 |first=John |last=Shea |date=April 19, 2013 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Mays's 3,000th hit in 1971, the Giants presented Michael with a four-year college scholarship.<ref>Mays, p. 243</ref>\n\nWhen Mays first joined the Giants, Forbes made arrangements for him to stay with David and Anna Goosby, who lived on St. Nicholas Avenue and 151st Street. \"Mrs. Goosby reminded me of my Aunt Sarah, the way she took care of me,\" Mays said. \"Her husband was a kind man who had retired from the railroad. They made me feel at home.\"<ref>Mays, p. 75</ref> Just before his marriage in 1956, he bought a home near [[Columbia University]] in Upper Manhattan.<ref>Mays, p. 134</ref> When the Giants moved to San Francisco, Mays bought a house in the Sherwood Woods neighborhood adjacent to [[St. Francis Wood, San Francisco]] in 1957.<ref name=\":0\">Kelley, T., VerPlanck, C., & Williams, Al. (2016) ''African American Historic Context Statement'' Retrieved November 12, 2019 from San Francisco Planning Department Website: https://default.sfplanning.org/Preservation/african_american_HCS/AfricanAmericanHistoricContextStatement_Draft_Jan2016.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419101944/http://default.sfplanning.org/Preservation/african_american_HCS/AfricanAmericanHistoricContextStatement_Draft_Jan2016.pdf |date=April 19, 2019 }}</ref> However, the purchase was initially met with backlash from neighbors who urged developer Walter Gnesdiloff to reconsider the repercussions \"if colored people moved in\".<ref name=\":0\" /> According to Mays, when mayor [[George Christopher]] heard he had been denied housing, he offered to share his house with Mays and his wife until they could get one. Ultimately, Mays and his wife moved into the house in November of 1957, and Mays wrote that when a brick was thrown through the window, \"Some neighbors actually called to ask if they could help. So I didn't feel concerned about racial tensions in my neighborhood once the [1958] season was about to start.\"<ref>Mays, pp. 146-47</ref> They only lived there for two years before moving back to New York.<ref>Mays, p. 154</ref> {{As of|2000}}, Mays lived in [[Atherton, California]], in a house he bought in 1969.<ref>{{cite news |first=Glen |last=Dickey |url=https://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Fans-Must-Learn-To-Let-Go-of-Stars-2755911.php |title=Fans Must Learn To Let Go of Stars |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=June 9, 2000 }}</ref>  \n\nA frequent traveler, Mays is one of 66 holders of [[American Airlines]]' lifetime passes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/05/business/la-fi-0506-golden-ticket-20120506|title=The frequent fliers who flew too much|last=Bensinger|first=Ken|date=May 5, 2012|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Mays will publish his memoir, ''24: Life Stories and Lessons from the Say Hey Kid'' (with John Shea; St. Martin's Press, 2020).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.macmillan.com/24/williemays/9781250230423|title=24 {{!}} Willie Mays {{!}} Macmillan|website=US Macmillan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==\"Say Hey Kid\" and other nicknames==\n[[File:Willie Mays tribute display, AT&T Park.JPG|thumb|Willie Mays tribute display at Oracle Park in San Francisco, California]]\n\nIt is not clear how Mays became known as the \"Say Hey Kid.\" One story is that in 1951, Barney Kremenko, a writer for the ''[[New York Journal]]'', began to refer to Mays as the 'Say Hey Kid' after he overheard Mays say, \"'Say who,' 'Say what,' 'Say where,' 'Say hey'\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Mays earns his nickname |url=http://espn.go.com/classic/s/000725williemaysadd.html |accessdate=October 21, 2006}}</ref> Another story is that Jimmy Cannon created the nickname because Mays did not know everybody's names when he arrived in the minors. \"You see a guy, you say, 'Hey, man. Say hey, man,'\" Mays said. \"Ted [Williams] was the 'Splinter'. Joe [DiMaggio] was 'Joltin' Joe'. Stan [Musial] was 'The Man'. I guess I hit a few home runs, and they said 'There goes the 'Say Hey Kid.''\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Article on Mays |url=http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/05/03/SPGV1IJEEB1.DTL |accessdate=October 21, 2006 | first=John | last=Shea | date=May 3, 2006 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nYears before he became the \"Say Hey Kid\", when he began his professional career with the Black Barons, Mays was called \"Buck\" by teammates and fans.<ref name=\"buck\">{{cite web |last= |first= |authorlink= |year= |url=http://www.coe.ksu.edu/nlbemuseum/history/players/mays.html |title=eMuseum: Willie Mays |publisher=Negro Leagues Baseball Museum |accessdate=March 9, 2007}}</ref> Some Giants players referred to him, their team captain, as \"Cap.\"\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[Bay Area Sports Hall of Fame]]\n*[[500 home run club]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball home run records]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career doubles leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career triples leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career stolen bases leaders]]\n*[[3,000 hit club]]\n*[[30\u201330 club]]\n*[[20\u201320\u201320 club]]\n*[[50 home run club]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual runs scored leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual stolen base leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual triples leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball single-game home run leaders]]\n*[[Major League Baseball titles leaders]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Greatest>\n* {{cite book |last=Allen |first=Bob |last2=Gilbert |first2=Bill |title=The 500 Home Run Club: Baseball's 16 Greatest Home Run Hitters from Babe Ruth to Mark McGwire |publisher=Sports Publishing LLC |year=2000 |page=145 |isbn=1-58261-289-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lombardi |first=Stephen M. |title=The Baseball Same Game: Finding Comparable Players from the National Pastime |publisher=[[iUniverse]] |year=2005 |page=86 |isbn=0-595-35457-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kalb |first=Elliott |title=Who's Better, Who's Best in Baseball?: Mr. Stats Sets the Record Straight on the Top 75 Players of All Time |publisher=McGraw-Hill Professional |year=2005 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/whosbetterwhosbe0000kalb_x9l5/page/35 35\u201336] |isbn=0-07-144538-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/whosbetterwhosbe0000kalb_x9l5/page/35 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Shannon |first=Mike |authorlink=Mike Shannon |title=Willie Mays: Art in the Outfield |publisher=University of Alabama Press |year=2007 |pages=89 |isbn=978-0-8173-1540-5}}\n* {{cite book |last=Markusen |first=Bruce |title=Roberto Clemente: The Great One |publisher=Sports Publishing LLC |year=2000 |page=140 |isbn=1-58261-312-5}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hinton |first=Chuck |authorlink=Chuck Hinton |title=My Time at Bat: A Story of Perseverance |publisher=Christian Living Books |year=2002 |page=59 |isbn=1-56229-003-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Barra |first=Allen |title=Brushbacks and Knockdowns: The Greatest Baseball Debates of Two Centuries |publisher=Macmillan Publishers |year=2004 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312322472/page/36 36] |isbn=0-312-32247-X |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312322472/page/36 }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/10260/ten-reasons-willie-mays-is-greatest-ever|title=Ten Reasons Willie Mays is the Greatest Ever|publisher=ESPN}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/197503-willie-mays-the-greatest-ballplayer-of-all-time|title=Willie Mays: The Greatest Ballplayer of All-Time|publisher=bleacherreport.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n* David Pietrusza, Matthew Silverman & Michael Gershman, ed. (2000). ''Baseball: The Biographical Encyclopedia''. Total/''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.\n* ''Willie's Time: A Memoir of Another America'', by Charles Einstein\n* ''Willie Mays'', by Arnold Hano, Tempo Books, Grosset & Dunlop, Inc. NY. copyright 1966, first printing, August 1966, {{lccn|6617205}}\n*{{cite book|last=Mays|first=Willie|title=Say Hey: The Autobiography of Willie Mays|location=New York|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=1988|isbn=0671632922}}\n* ''The Series, An Illustrated History of Baseball's Postseason Showcase, 1903\u20131993'', ''[[The Sporting News]]'', copyright 1993, The Sporting News Publishing Co. {{ISBN|0-89204-476-4}}/\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{bbhof|mays-willie}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=118495|espn=24790|br=m/mayswi01|fangraphs=1008315|brm=mays--002wil|retro=M/Pmaysw101}}\n{{Negro-league-stats|brn=mays--002wil}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/64f5dfa2 Willie Mays] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-1252 Willie Mays article, Encyclopedia of Alabama]\n*[http://www.startribune.com/local/blogs/119570269.html May 1951: ''Minneapolis Tribune'' account of Mays' first home game as a Minneapolis Miller]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091004172920/http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/23153/willie-mays-say-hey Willie Mays: Say Hey!] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[Life magazine]]''\n*[https://achievement.org/achiever/willie-mays/#interview Willie Mays Biography and Interview on American Academy of Achievement]\n<br>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before = ''none''<br />[[Lew Burdette]]<br />[[Willie McCovey]]<br />[[Pete Rose]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|Major League Player of the Month]]|years = May 1958 (with [[Stan Musial]])<br />September 1958<br />August 1963<br />August 1965}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Frank Thomas (outfielder)|Frank Thomas]]<br />[[Hank Aaron]] & [[Harvey Haddix]]<br />[[Billy Williams (left fielder)|Billy Williams]]<br />[[Juan Marichal]]}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Rocky Colavito]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Batters with 4 home runs in one game]]|years = April 30, 1961}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Mike Schmidt]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Willie Mays|list1=\n\n{{MLBACT}}\n{{MLBATT}}\n{{NL MVP's}}\n{{NL home run champions}}\n{{NL batting title}}\n{{NL stolen base champions}}\n{{Major League Baseball All-Star Game MVPs}}\n{{Roberto Clemente Award}}\n{{NL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{The Sporting News MLB Player of the Year Award}}\n{{Sporting News MLB Rookie of the year|state=collapsed