{"title_page": "Cobyrinate a,c-diamide synthase", "text_new": "{{Infobox enzyme\n| Name = Cobyrinate a,c-diamide synthase\n| EC_number = 6.3.5.11\n| CAS_number = \n| IUBMB_EC_number = 6/3/5/11\n| GO_code = \n| image = \n| width = \n| caption =\n}}\n'''Cobyrinate a,c-diamide synthase''' ({{EC number|6.3.5.11}}), ''cobyrinic acid a,c-diamide synthetase'', ''CbiA (gene)'') is an [[enzyme]] which [[catalysis|catalyses]] the [[chemical reaction]]<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fresquet V, Williams L, Raushel FM | title = Mechanism of cobyrinic acid a,c-diamide synthetase from Salmonella typhimurium LT2 | journal = Biochemistry | volume = 43 | issue = 33 | pages = 10619\u201327 | date = August 2004 | pmid = 15311923 | doi = 10.1021/bi048972x }}</ref>\n\n: 2 ATP + [[cobyrinate]] + 2 L-[[glutamine]] + 2 H<sub>2</sub>O <math>\\rightleftharpoons</math> 2 ADP + 2 [[phosphate]] + cobyrinate a,c-diamide + 2 L-glutamate (overall reaction)\n:(1a) ATP + cobyrinate + L-glutamine + H<sub>2</sub>O <math>\\rightleftharpoons</math> ADP + phosphate + cobyrinate c-monamide + L-glutamate\n:(1b) ATP + cobyrinate c-monamide + L-glutamine + H<sub>2</sub>O <math>\\rightleftharpoons</math> ADP + phosphate + cobyrinate a,c-diamide + L-glutamate\n\nThis enzyme is a [[glutamine amidotransferase]], part of the biosynthetic pathway to [[cobalamin]] (vitamin B<sub>12</sub>) in [[anaerobic organism|anaerobic]] [[bacteria]] such as ''[[Salmonella typhimurium]]'' and ''[[Bacillus megaterium]]''. \n==See also==\n* [[Cobalamin biosynthesis]]\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MeshName|Cobyrinate+a,c-diamide+synthase}}\n\n{{Ligases CO CS and CN}}\n{{Enzymes}}\n{{Portal bar|Biology|border=no}}\n\n[[Category:EC 6.3.5]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox enzyme\n| Name = Cobyrinate a,c-diamide synthase\n| EC_number = 6.3.5.11\n| CAS_number = \n| IUBMB_EC_number = 6/3/5/11\n| GO_code = \n| image = \n| width = \n| caption =\n}}\n'''Cobyrinate a,c-diamide synthase''' ({{EC number|6.3.5.11}}, ''cobyrinic acid a,c-diamide synthetase'', ''CbiA (gene)'') is an [[enzyme]] which [[catalysis|catalyses]] the [[chemical reaction]]<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fresquet V, Williams L, Raushel FM | title = Mechanism of cobyrinic acid a,c-diamide synthetase from Salmonella typhimurium LT2 | journal = Biochemistry | volume = 43 | issue = 33 | pages = 10619\u201327 | date = August 2004 | pmid = 15311923 | doi = 10.1021/bi048972x }}</ref>\n\n: 2 ATP + [[cobyrinate]] + 2 L-[[glutamine]] + 2 H<sub>2</sub>O <math>\\rightleftharpoons</math> 2 ADP + 2 [[phosphate]] + cobyrinate a,c-diamide + 2 L-glutamate (overall reaction)\n:(1a) ATP + cobyrinate + L-glutamine + H<sub>2</sub>O <math>\\rightleftharpoons</math> ADP + phosphate + cobyrinate c-monamide + L-glutamate\n:(1b) ATP + cobyrinate c-monamide + L-glutamine + H<sub>2</sub>O <math>\\rightleftharpoons</math> ADP + phosphate + cobyrinate a,c-diamide + L-glutamate\n\nThis enzyme is a [[glutamine amidotransferase]], part of the biosynthetic pathway to [[cobalamin]] (vitamin B<sub>12</sub>) in [[anaerobic organism|anaerobic]] [[bacteria]] such as ''[[Salmonella typhimurium]]'' and ''[[Bacillus megaterium]]''. \n==See also==\n* [[Cobalamin biosynthesis]]\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MeshName|Cobyrinate+a,c-diamide+synthase}}\n\n{{Ligases CO CS and CN}}\n{{Enzymes}}\n{{Portal bar|Biology|border=no}}\n\n[[Category:EC 6.3.5]]\n", "name_user": "Michael D. Turnbull", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added missing )", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cobyrinate_a,c-diamide_synthase"}
{"title_page": "Komala of the Toilers of Kurdistan", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Komala \u2013 Reform Faction\n| logo = The Official Logo Of Komala.png\n| logo_size = 100px\n| caption = \n| colorcode = Red\n| leader = Omar Ilkhanizade \n| foundation = {{start date and age|2007|10}}\n| split = [[Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan]]\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]\n| headquarters = [[Sulaymaniyah]], [[Kurdistan Region]], [[Iraq]]\n| international = \n| country = Iran\n| country2 = Iraq\n| founder = \n| flag = [[File:Flag of Komala.png|200px]]\n}}\nThe '''Organization of the Toilers of Kurdistan'''<ref name=\"Romano and Gurses\">{{citation|last1=Romano|first1=David|last2=Gurses|first2=Mehmet|title=Conflict, Democratization, and the Kurds in the Middle East: Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Syria|date=2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-40999-7|page=75|edition=1st|doi=10.1057/9781137409997_4}}</ref> ({{lang-ku|{{lang|fa|\u06a9\u06c6\u0645\u0647\u200c\u06b5\u0647\u200c\u06cc \u0632\u0647\u200c\u062d\u0645\u0647\u200c\u062a\u06a9\u06cc\u0634\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u06a9\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}}}}, {{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0648\u0645\u0644\u0647 \u0632\u062d\u0645\u062a\u06a9\u0634\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}}), also known as the '''Komala \u2013 Reform Faction''',<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\"/> is an armed [[Communism|communist]] and [[Kurdish separatism in Iran|separatist]] [[ethnic party]] of [[Kurds in Iran]], currently exiled in northern [[Iraq]].\n\nIt split from the [[Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan]] in October 2007 over internal disagreements<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\">{{citation|first1=Hashem|last1=Ahmadzadeh|first2=Gareth|last2=Stansfield|title=The Political, Cultural, and Military Re-Awakening of the Kurdish Nationalist Movement in Iran|journal=Middle East Journal|volume=64|number=1|date=2010|pages=11-27|jstor=20622980}}</ref> and is led by Omar Ilkhanizade.<ref name=\"Romano and Gurses\"/><ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\"/>\n== History ==\n{{Main|Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan#History}}\n==See also==\n{{Komala offshoots}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{citation|title=Iran's Kurdish Opposition Considers Negotiations|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/0fb92b0db4e623dcde3ee6f673cf0f53|date=18 July 2019|work=Associated Press}}\n{{Iran-party-stub}}\n{{Iranian exiled parties}}\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Banned political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Banned Kurdish parties]]\n[[Category:Banned communist parties]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Marxist parties]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Left-wing militant groups in Iran]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Kurdistan Region]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Iran]]\n[[Category:Militant opposition to the Islamic Republic of Iran]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Komala \u2013 Reform Faction\n| logo = The Official Logo Of Komala.png\n| logo_size = 100px\n| caption = \n| colorcode = Red\n| leader = Omar Ilkhanizade \n| foundation = {{start date and age|2007|10}}\n| split = [[Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan]]\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]\n| headquarters = [[Sulaymaniyah]], [[Kurdistan Region]], [[Iraq]]\n| international = \n| country = Iran\n| country2 = Iraq\n| founder = \n| flag = [[File:Flag of Komala.png|200px]]\n}}\nThe '''Organization of the Toilers of Kurdistan'''<ref name=\"Romano and Gurses\">{{citation|last1=Romano|first1=David|last2=Gurses|first2=Mehmet|title=Conflict, Democratization, and the Kurds in the Middle East: Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Syria|date=2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-40999-7|page=75|edition=1st|doi=10.1057/9781137409997_4}}</ref> ({{lang-ku|{{lang|fa|\u06a9\u06c6\u0645\u0647\u200c\u06b5\u0647\u200c\u06cc \u0632\u0647\u200c\u062d\u0645\u0647\u200c\u062a\u06a9\u06cc\u0634\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u06a9\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}}}}, {{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0648\u0645\u0644\u0647 \u0632\u062d\u0645\u062a\u06a9\u0634\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}}), also knwon as the '''Komala \u2013 Reform Faction''',<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\"/> is an armed [[Communism|communist]] and [[Kurdish separatism in Iran|separatist]] [[ethnic party]] of [[Kurds in Iran]], currently exiled in northern [[Iraq]].\n\nIt split from the [[Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan]] in October 2007 over internal disagreements<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\">{{citation|first1=Hashem|last1=Ahmadzadeh|first2=Gareth|last2=Stansfield|title=The Political, Cultural, and Military Re-Awakening of the Kurdish Nationalist Movement in Iran|journal=Middle East Journal|volume=64|number=1|date=2010|pages=11-27|jstor=20622980}}</ref> and is led by Omar Ilkhanizade.<ref name=\"Romano and Gurses\"/><ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\"/>\n== History ==\n{{Main|Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan#History}}\n==See also==\n{{Komala offshoots}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{citation|title=Iran's Kurdish Opposition Considers Negotiations|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/youtube/0fb92b0db4e623dcde3ee6f673cf0f53|date=18 July 2019|work=Associated Press}}\n{{Iran-party-stub}}\n{{Iranian exiled parties}}\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Banned political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Banned Kurdish parties]]\n[[Category:Banned communist parties]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Marxist parties]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Left-wing militant groups in Iran]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Kurdistan Region]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Iran]]\n[[Category:Militant opposition to th