 || 48\n|-\n| 12 Apr || 9 || 218 || 0 || 6 || 83 || 1,719 || 0 || 48\n|-\n| 13 Apr || 1 || 219 || 0 || 6 || 54 || 1,773 || 5 || 53\n|-\n| 14 Apr || 4 || 223 || 1 || 7 || 62 || 1,835 || 0 || 53\n|-\n| 15 Apr || 5 || 228 || 1 || 8 || 137 || 1,972 || 16 || 69\n|-\n| 16 Apr || 6 || 234 || 1 || 9 || 142 || 2,114 || 4 || 73\n|-\n| 17 Apr || 2 || 236 || 0 || 9 || 109 || 2,223 || 9 || 82\n|- \n| 18 Apr || 3 || 239 || 0 || 9 || 97 || 2,320 || 5 || 87\n|- \n| 19 Apr || 0 || 239 || 0 || 9 || 127 || 2,447 || 10 || 97\n|- \n| 20 Apr || 0 || 239 || 1 || 10 || 44 || 2,491 || 15 || 112\n|- \n| 21 Apr || 2 || 241 || 0 || 10 || 70 || 2,561 || 11 || 123\n|- \n| 22 Apr || 2 || 243 || 0 || 10 || 74 || 2,635 || 11 || 134\n|- \n| 23 Apr || 2 || 245 || 0 || 10 || 92 || 2,727 || 5 || 139\n|- \n| 24 Apr || 0 || 245 || 1 || 11 || 69 || 2,796 || 16 || 155\n|- \n| 25 Apr || 0 || 245 || 1 || 12 || 68 || 2,864 || 12 || 167\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n! Total\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 245\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 12\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 2,864\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 167\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jersey]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Isle of Man]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2020 in Guernsey|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Crown dependencies|Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guernsey]]\n", "name_user": "Formulaonewiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTesting results:corrected", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Guernsey"}
{"title_page": "John Schehr", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Schehr\n| image         = \n| caption       =\n| imagesize     =  \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 9 February 1896\n| birth_place   = [[Ottensen]], [[Altona|Altona, Hamburg]], [[German empire|Germany]]\n| death_date    = 1/2 February 1934 (overnight)\n| death_place   = [[:de:Sch\u00e4ferberg|Sch\u00e4ferberg / Kilometerberg (hill)]], [[Wannsee|Berlin-Wannsee]], [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n| occupation    = Skilled metal worker<br>Dock worker<br>Political activist<br>Party officer<br>Politician<br>[[Communist Party of Germany|Party]] leader<br>Gestapo murder victim\n| party         =  [[Social Democratic Party of Germany |SPD]]<br>[[Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany|USPD]]<br>[[Communist Party of Germany|KPD]]\n|spouse         =  Anna\n|parents        = \n|children       = \n|alma_mater     = \n| nationality   = \n}}\n\n'''John Schehr''' (9 February 1896 - 1 February 1934) was a [[Germany|German]] political activist who became a [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]] politician and ultimately, following the arrest on 3 March 1933 of [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], Chairman (leader) of [[Communist Party of Germany|the party]].   By this time [[Nazi Germany|the country]] was very rapidly [[Gleichschaltung| being transformed]] into a [[one-party state|one-]][[Nazi Party|party]] [[Enabling Act of 1933 |dictatorship]], meaning that the party John Schehr led was outlawed, with those members of the leadership team who had not escaped abroad now living \"underground\" (unregistered) and in hiding.   Schehr was nevertheless arrested on 13 November 1933 and taken to [[Columbia concentration camp|a Berlin concentration camp]]. He died when he was one of four men shot by [[Gestapo]] officials, reportedly \"while escaping\" during an overnight transport, following arrest.<ref name=JSlauHDK>{{cite web |title= Schehr, John  * 9.2.1896  \u2020 1.2.1934|work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/john-schehr?ID=5063 |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=JSlautGDW>{{cite web|url=https://www.gdw-berlin.de/en/recess/biographies/index_of_persons/biographie/view-bio/john-schehr/?no_cache=1|title=John Schehr:  February 09, 1896 - February 01, 1934 |publisher= Gedenkst\u00e4tte Deutscher Widerstand (German Resistance Memorial Center), Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name= JSlautFreundeskreisET>{{cite web|url=http://www.etg-ziegenhals.de/John_Schehr.html|title=John Schehr (1896 \u2013 1934) |publisher= Freundeskreis \u201eErnst Th\u00e4lmann\u201c e.V., Ziegenhals-Berlin|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Aftermath of World War II|National Socialist nightmare ended]] Schehr and his three murdered comrades became celebrated, for the benefit of a new generation, in the [[German Democratic Republic|German Democratic Republic (East Germany: 1949-1989)]] by means of a poem written, probably, shortly after the killing, by [[Erich Weinert]].<ref name=JohnSchehruGenossen>{{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130304112709/http://www.mdr.de/mdr-figaro/hoerspiel/feature/johnschehr100.html|date=2 March 2013| title=John Schehr und Genossen|work=Ein Mord, ein Mythos und die Folgen|publisher=[[MDR Fernsehen |MDR]] (\"Figaro\"), [[Leipzig]]|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n=== Provenance and early years ===\nJohn \"Jonny\" Schehr was born into a working-class family in the [[Ottensen]] quarter of [[Altona|Altona, Hamburg]], at that time a robustly independent municipality, but [[Greater Hamburg Act|subsequently - in 1937 -  subsumed]] into [[Hamburg]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   His father worked as a [[hairdresser]].<ref name=JSlautFS/>   As a boy he was particularly close to his mother, born Martha Fischer.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   John Schehr's younger brother, Franz, later recalled that the family always read [[:de:Hamburger Echo|the Hamburger Echo]] and [[:de:Der wahre Jacob|Wahre Jacob]], both staunchly [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] newspapers.<ref name=JSlautFS>:{{cite web|page=4|work=Franz Schehr: Erinnerung an den Bruder|url= https://www.thaelmann-gedenkstaette.de/GSETHP/Rundbriefe/RB40.pdf|publisher=Kuratorium Gedenkst\u00e4tte Ernst Th\u00e4lmann e.V.:  article reproduced in \"Rundbrief aus dem Th\u00e4lmann-Haus\" from \"John Schehr 1896-1934. Biographische Skizze: DKP Kreis Altona und Kuratorium \u201eGedenkst\u00e4tteErnst  Th\u00e4lmann\u201c  e.V.,  Hamburg  1984|date=February 2004|author=Franz Schehr|title=John Schehr und Genossen |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   Schehr attended school locally in [[Ottensen]] and then completed an apprenticeship as a [[:de:Schlosserei|skilled metal worker]] with \"Firma Meier\" (Gerberstra\u00dfe), an Altona manufacturing company.<ref name=JSlautFS/>    Towards the end of 1912, still aged only 16, joined the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany |Social Democratic Party (''\"Sozialdemokratische Partei Deutschlands\"''/ SPD)]].<ref name=JSlautGDW/>   The next year he also joined the Transport Workers' Union<!--- Transportarbeitergewerkschaft ---><ref name=JSlautDieLinke>{{cite web|title=John Schehr und Genossen|page=2|publisher=Kreisvorstand DIE LINKE, Potsdam |work=Potsdams andere Seiten|url=https://www.dielinke-potsdam.de/fileadmin/potsdam/PAS/2017/PaS_Maerz_2017.pdf|date=March 2017 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   He was working during this period [[Port of Hamburg|on the Hamburg docks]], which is how he came to know [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]].\n\n=== War years and the beginnings of the Communist Party ===\nIn 1916 or 1917 Schehr was conscripted into an artillery regiment and sent to serve at [[Neuf-Brisach|Neu Breisach]], an important [[Fortification|redoubt]] which at that time was part of [[German empire|Germany]].     Without intending it, he found himself promoted to the rank of a [[Unteroffizier|\"sub-officer\" (''\"Unteroffizier\"'')]].   It is recorded that during one retreat he skilfully led his troops so that they avoided capture.   His brother Walter Schehr was killed in action in 1916.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   The 1914 decision of the party leadership to [[Burgfriedenspolitik|vote in favour]] of [[War bond|war funding]] and forego criticism of the government for the duration of hostilities during the [[First World War|war]] had been contentious among party activists from the outset, and the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] finally split over the issue of support for the war in 1917.   John Schehr, like his mentor [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], was one of a large number of mainly left-wing party members who moved across to the breakaway [[Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany|Independent Social Democratic Party (''\" Unabh\u00e4ngige Sozialdemokratische Partei Deutschlands\"'' / USPD)]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=JSlautFS/>   After the war there was no immediate return to his skilled work, but [[Port of Hamburg|the docks]] continued to function and he joined his brother Franz in work as a [[stevedore]] till 1924.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   In 1919 when, in its turn, the [[Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany|USPD)]], [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann |Th\u00e4lmann]] and Schehr, were among the early recruits to the newly launched [[Communist Party of Germany |Communist Party]] in the wake of the so-called [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919 |November revolutions]].<ref name=JSlautGDW/>    Almost all the USPD activists in the Hamburg district made the same move, which can be seen in large measure as a tribute to Ernst Th\u00e4lmann's oratorical and political powers of persuasion.   Schehr quickly became an energetic party activist:  his brother recalled later that during the early 1920s he was out almost every evening, undertaking party work.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   \n\n=== From party activist to party officer ===\n1923 was a year of [[Hyperinflation in the Weimar Republic|intensified destitution]] across [[Weimar Germany|Germany]], and a number of [[Cuno strikes|major disturbances]].  In Hamburg Schehr took part in the storming the [[Ottensen]] police station, which was one of police stations in and around Hamburg attacked on 23 October in the context of that year's  [[Hamburg Uprising|October uprising]], carefully planned and choreographed by Ernst Th\u00e4lmann on behalf of [[Communist Party of Germany |the party]].<ref name=JSlautFS/>   In 1924 Schehr became a party \"Polleiter\" (''loosely, \"policy head\"'') for [[Altona, Hamburg| Altona]] where he was already, by this time, a municipal councillor.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   He also regained his skilled work [[Port of Hamburg|on the docks]].   The next year he accepted a fulltime job working within [[Communist Party of Germany |the party]] apparatus, however.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   It is clear that John Schehr's advancement in the national party over the next few years owed much to the friendship and political patronage of [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], but he evidently had many friends and admirers among local party activists.   A particular friend and political ally was [[:de:Etkar Andr\u00e9 |Etkar Andr\u00e9]].<ref name=JSlautFS/> \n\n=== Party advancement ===\nIt was nevertheless more likely to have been as a result, primarily, of [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann|Th\u00e4lmann's]] backing that in 1925, at the tenth party congress, John Schehr was elected to membership of the party appeal's commission (''\"Beschwerdekommissio\"'').   The same congress also voted Schehr onto the list of candidates for [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD|the Party Central Committee]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   The dire economic situation during the early 1920s made this a period of expansion for the [[Communist Party of Germany |communists]] in the industrial regions, and during 1925 John Schehr was appointed to lead the party organisation in the recently established [[Harburg-Wilhelmsburg]] sub-district (''\"Unterbezirksleiter\"'') in succession to [[:de:Johann Skjellerup |Johann Skjellerup]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=UBLinHWlautCG/>   The appointment was of short duration, however, since in March 1926 the fulltime paid position was abolished, possibly to save money and possibly in response to a decline in party membership locally.<ref name=UBLinHWlautCG>{{cite web|url=http://www.harbuch.de/frische-themen-artikel/radli3.html|title=Die radikale Linke in Harburg-Wilhelmsburg|work=Nachtrag 2: Organisatorische St\u00e4rken und Schw\u00e4chen, interne Fraktionsk\u00e4mpfe 1924-1931|publisher=Dr. Christian Gotthardt, Hamburg|author=Christian Gotthardt|date=April 2018|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>   In 1927 he was appointed \"Orgleiter\" (''loosely \"Head of Administration\"'') for the party's important Hamburg-Wasserkante district (to the west and north of Hamburg),<ref name=JSlautGDW/><ref name=\"EvansGeary2015\">{{cite book|author1=Anthony McElligott (author) |author2=Dick Geary (compiler-editor)|title=Mobilising the unemployed:  the KPD and the Unemployed Workers' Movement in Hamburg-Altona during the Weimar Republic|work=The German Unemployed (Routledge Revivals): Experiences and Consequences of Mass Unemployment from the Weimar Republic to the Third Reich|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SUfLCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT289 |date=5 June 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-54203-2|pages=288\u2013294}}</ref> thereby becoming a key member of the regional party executive under the leadership of regional party secretary [[:de:John Wittorf |John Wittorf]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>\n\n=== Wittorf affair ===\nAlso in 1927 Schehr was again a delegate at the party's eleventh party congress, held that year in [[Essen]].   Again he was voted onto the list of candidates for [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD |the Party Central Committee]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   As a member of the Control Commission for the Hamburg-Wasserkante party organisation, Schehr was implicated in concealing the embezzlement of party funds by [[:de:John Wittorf |John Wittorf]] during the course of a scandal that blew up in 1928.  [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]] was, by some criteria, more heavily and directly implicated, and he was indeed briefly ousted from the [[Central Committee|party Central Committee]], but [[Joseph Stalin]], whose influence over the [[Communist Party of Germany|German party leadership]] was immense, intervened to have Th\u00e4lmann reinstated.   From now on Th\u00e4lmann was seen by party comrades as [[Stalinism|\"Stalin's man\"]]:  it did his career no harm.<ref name=ETlauHDK>{{cite web|title= Th\u00e4lmann, Ernst  * 16.4.1886  \u2020  18.8.1944|work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/ernst-thaelmann |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   There was no intervention with such immediate impact on behalf of John Schehr who was stripped of all his party functions in October 1928.   There were even demands for Schehr to be excluded from the party, but that did not happen.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>\n\n=== Political recovery and advancement ===\nFollowing [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]]'s rehabilitation Schehr, as Th\u00e4lmann's respected prot\u00e9g\u00e9, quickly recovered his position in the party.  He was reinstated as [[Communist Party of Germany|party]] \"Orgleiter\" for the  Hamburg-Wasserkante district, retaining the post till March 1930.   In 1929, at the eleventh party congress (held in [[Wedding (Berlin)|Berlin-Wedding]]) Schehr was again present as a delegate, and he was yet again included on the candidates list for [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD |Central Committee membership]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref>Protokoll XII. Parteitag der KPD 1929</ref>   An [[East Germany|East German]] newspaper tribute which appeared in 1967 states that on this occasion he was elected to full membership of the [[Central Committee|party Central Committee]],<ref name=JSlautND>{{cite web|title=John Schehr  1896-1934|work=Der aus Altona geb\u00fcrtige Arbeitersohn, selbst gelernter Schlosser, kam schon vor den ersten Weltkrieg zur Arbeiterbewegung....|publisher=[[Neues Deutschland]], Berlin |url=https://www.nd-archiv.de/ausgabe/1967-03-01 |date=1 March 1967|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> but other more plausible sources [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD|refute this]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   It is nevertheless clear that by this stage John Schehr was widely respected and liked by party comrades<ref name=JSlautFS/> whereas his more formidable mentor, [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], who had been party leader since 1925, is more usually seen as having been widely feared within the party by this point.<ref name=ETlauHDK/>   \n\n=== Crisis years ===\nIn 1930 John Schehr took over the job of regional party secretary (''\"Polleiter\"'') with the [[Hanover]]-based regional leadership team (''\"Bezirksleitung\"'') for the Lower Saxony region in succession to [[:de:Willi Bohn |Willi Bohn]], whom the national party leadership had decided (at very short notice) should be sent to the [[International Lenin School]] in [[Moscow]] for two years of party training.<ref name=WBlauHDK>{{cite web|title=Bohn, Willi Karl   * 6.8.1900 \u2020 23.1.1985 |work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/willi-karl-bohn|publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   His slow but steady progression through the party ranks meant that he was beginning to emerge from behind [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann|Th\u00e4lmann's]] shadow.   Meanwhile a return to widespread economic austerity, as [[Weimar Germany|Germany]] worked through the savage backwash from the [[Great depression]], was creating a surge across Germany in support for the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]].   This was accompanied by increasing political polarisation leading, after [[July 1932 German federal election|1932]], to deadlock in the [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag (''national parliament'')]] whereby coalition with on or other of the two populist parties, the [[Nazi Party|National Socialists]] and the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communists]] was mathematically necessary for the more moderate parties to coalesce to form a majority coalition, but both extremist parties were unacceptable coaliation parties either for the moderate parties or form each other.   It was in the resulting context of intensifying crisis that in April 1932 John Schehr was elected to [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder des Landtages (Freistaat Preu\u00dfen) (4. Wahlperiode)|membership]] of the [[Landtag of Prussia|Prussian Landtag (''regional parliament'')]] in [[Berlin]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   Three months later, in [[July 1932 German federal election|July 1932]], he was elected to the  [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]].<ref name=JSlautDieLinke/>   (His [[Landtag of Prussia|Landtag]] seat was taken over by his party comrade [[:de:August T\u00fcnnermann|August T\u00fcnnermann]].<ref name=ATlauHDK>{{cite web|title=T\u00fcnnermann, August   * 18.8.1896   \u2020 23.12.1982 |work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1= [[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/ernst-thaelmann |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\nWithin the party Schehr's career continued to advance.   During the middle of 1932 he finally became a member of the [[Communist Party of Germany|party]] [[Central Committee]].   This came about not through any vote of delegates at a party congress, but as a result of being co-opted into membership by the existing members.   He relocated to [[Berlin]], becoming both secretary to the Central Committee and a member of its inner caucus, the Politburo.   Schehr was now, in all but name, deputy to the party leader, [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]].   His position in the party aparatus was further strengthened after [[Heinz Neumann]] was stripped of his party funcations and then officially condemned by the leadership in November 1932 and sent as a comintern emissary to [[Spain]].   (Neumann had clashed with Th\u00e4lmann whom he believed, along with [[Joseph Stalin]], was dangerously underestimating the strength of the threat presented by [[Adolf Hitler]].<ref name=HNlauHDK>{{cite web| title=Neumann, Heinz  * 6.7.1902   \u2020 26.11.1937  |work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1= [[Hermann Weber]]|author2= [[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/heinz-neumann |publisher= Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\nIt was probably in October or November 1932 that the police arrested John Schehr  and discovered \"important material\" concerning the [[Communist Party of Germany|party's]] illegal structures (which included a semi-secret quasi-military operation across the nation and a large \"political\" espionage network on a scale normally associated with foreign governments rather than with domestic political parties).<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   The arrest was apparently made \"because of an instruction from the Ministry of Defence\".<ref name=spiegel12993>{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-13682818.html|volume=12/1993|title=Einsamer Wolf unter W\u00f6lfen|work=Eine Moskauer Personalakte der Kommunistischen Internationale erhellt das Bild Herbert Wehners, der nach dem Krieg zum SPD-Vizevorsitzenden und Minister aufstieg. In den Terrorjahren 1937 bis 1941 lebte er - zusammen mit dem sp\u00e4teren DDR-Gr\u00fcnder Walter Ulbricht - in Moskau. Dort belastete er Genossen, die der sowjetischen Geheimpolizei zum Opfer fielen. Rettete er die eigene Haut? Oder suchte er S\u00fchne f\u00fcr Verr\u00e4ter?|author=Fritjof Meyer|date=22 March 1993|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>   Although sources differ wildly over the month of Schehr's 1932 arrest, it is apparent that he was released after eight days in detention.   Regardless of the legal basis for the arrest (which remains vague and unclear), as a member of the  [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag (''national parliament'')]] till some months after the [[Machtergreifung |r\u00e9gime change]] in 1933, John Schehr enjoyed certain privileges, and it would appear to have been on account of these that on this occasion his release came so swiftly.<ref name=JSlauHDK/> \n\n=== R\u00e9gime change ===\nThe [[Hitler cabinet|Hitler government]] exploited the continuing parliamentary and political deadlock to [[Machtergreifung |take power]] in January 1933.   They lost no time in [[Gleichschaltung|transforming Germany]] into a [[one-party state|one-]][[Nazi Party |party]] [[Enabling Act of 1933|dictatorship]].  Over the next few weeks the [[Communist Party of Germany |Communist party]] was outlawed and those of its leaders who had not already gone into hiding or emigrated were rounded up by the [[Gestapo|security services]].  On 7 February 1933 Schehr was one of the participants at the [[:de:Sporthaus Ziegenhals|\"illegal\" Sporthaus Ziegenhals meeting]] held just outside Berlin, and celebrated subsequently (especially during the \"East German\" years) as the last meeting held by the German Communist Party leadership before the participants were arrested and killed, or in some cases managed to escape abroad.<ref name= JSlautFreundeskreisET/><ref name= ZiegenhalsTeilnehmer>{{cite web |  url=http://www.etg-ziegenhals.de/Teilnehmer.html | title= Teilnehmer an der Tagung des ZK der KPD am 07. Februar 1933 | publisher=Freundeskreis \u201eErnst-Th\u00e4lmann-Gedenkst\u00e4tte\u201c e.V., Ziegenhals, K\u00f6nigs-Wusterhausen   | accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March 1933 [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]] was arrested as part of the wave of (apparently preplanned) political arrests that followed the [[Reichstag fire]].   It was the [[Comintern]], presumably under instructions from [[Joseph Stalin |Moscow]], that transferred the party chairmanship to John Schehr, as Th\u00e4lmann's de facto deputy.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   The chairmanship appointment meant that he became the official leader of the from now on \"underground\" Communist Party.   His leadership position came under challenge both from [[Walter Ulbricht]] and from [[Hermann Schubert]], suggesting that even if he had not been killed early the next year, the term of his leadership might still have been brief.<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=\"SchmitthennerGraml1970\">{{cite book|author1=Walter Schmitthenner|author2=Hermann Graml|title=Resistance in the labour movement: The German Communist Party (KPD)|work=The German Resistance to Hitler|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bFwcCy2MfvEC&pg=PA167|year=1970|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-01662-0|pages=164\u2013180}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest, detention, torture and killing/murder ===\nBy the second part of 1933 many more party comrades had found their way to Paris or Moscow, and John Schehr was the only member of a [[Communist Party of Germany|the party]] leadership team still hiding out in Germany.<ref name=\"Frank2009\">{{cite book|author=Mario Frank|title=Walter Ulbricht: Eine deutsche Biografie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QfNvCR_-L8cC&pg=PT112|date=26 January 2009|publisher=Siedler Verlag|isbn=978-3-641-01040-9|pages=112\u2013}}</ref>    The [[Gestapo|security services]] arrested him in [[Berlin]] on 13 November 1933.   This time there would be no question of their letting him go again a week later.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   He was taken to the [[Columbia concentration camp]], a former military police station on the edge of Berlin that had stood empy since 1929, till its conversion into a prison during 1933.<ref name= \"GeserickWirth2011\">{{cite book|author1=Gunther Geserick|author2=Ingo Wirth|author3=Klaus Vendura|title=Die Nacht der Langen Messer|work=Zeitzeuge Tod: Spektakul\u00e4re F\u00e4lle der Gerichtsmedizin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dBJ3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT203|date=25 July 2011|publisher=Militzke Verlag|isbn=978-3-86189-798-9|page=203}}</ref>    The [[Gestapo]] knew that Schehr was a senior party functionary and they did their best to extract statements from him, employing some of the worst forms of torture.   He suffered sever burns and there are also reports that one of his eyes was knocked out of its socket.   However, the Gestapo failed to extract from him the information that they sought.<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=JSlautHRS>{{cite web|author=[[:de:Hans-Rainer Sandvo\u00df|Hans-Rainer Sandvo\u00df]]|publisher=Gedenkst\u00e4tte Deutscher Widerstand, Berlin |issn= 0175-3592|date=October 1985|pages=168-169|title=Mord am Kilometerberg|work=Widerstand 1933 - 1945 in Steglitz und Zahlendorf |url= https://www.gdw-berlin.de/fileadmin/bilder/publikationen/Widerstand_in_Berlin/Widerstand%20in%20Steglitz%20und%20Zehlendorf_1986.pdf |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt had become known that the [[Gestapo|Security services]] had been employing a spy in the secret Berlin headquarters of the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]].   This was [[:de:Alfred Kattner|Alfred Kattner]], a one-time confidant of  [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]] who had been arrested in March 1933, tortured, persuaded to gather information for the [[Gestapo|security services]] and then, in August 1933, released.   It was believed that information gathered and passed on to his handlers by Kattner had enabled the Gestapo to arrest John Schehr, among others.  Kattner's role became known to comrades through the underground press during January 1934 and, after attempts to have him kidnapped and spirited away to Moscow had failed, on 1 February 1934 [[:de:Alfred Kattner|Alfred Kattner]] was shot dead by a party official called [[:de:Hans Schwarz (Parteifunktion\u00e4r)|Hans Schwarz]] in his [[:de:Nowawes|Nowawes]] apartment just outside Berlin.   The [[Nazi Party|National Socialist government]] was enraged by this turn of events.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   \n\nAt the time of Schehr's arrest other leading party activists were also captured, including [[Eugen Sch\u00f6nhaar]] and [[:de:Rudolf Schwarz (Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer) |Rudolf Schwarz]].   One response to Kattner's killing was an order for the immediate transfer of the men from the [[Columbia concentration camp]] to a facility at the [[Gro\u00dfer Wannsee|Wannsee]].   An overnight transport was arranged.   During the night of 1/2 February 1934 these three, together with [[:de:Erich Steinfurth|Erich Steinfurth]] (who had been arrested back in March 1933) were shot dead at the [[:de:Sch\u00e4ferberg|Sch\u00e4ferberg / Kilometerberg (hill)]] on the edge of [[Berlin]] by [[Gestapo]] personnel, allegedly \"while attempting to escape\".   In reality commentators agree that the murder was an act of quick retribution following the shooting the previous day of the government spy [[:de:Alfred Kattner|Alfred Kattner]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=ESlauHDK>{{cite web|title=Sch\u00f6nhaar, Eugen   * 29.10.1898, \u2020 1.2.1934|work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]]|url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363;-1424.html?ID=5120 |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>    The killings became widely known:  even at the time, the authorities made no attempt to refute the view that the authorities' motives for the \"act of reckoning\" were all too obvious.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>\n\n==The killer==\n{{Quote box|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|align=right|width=32%|\n\n'''John Schehr und Genossen'''<ref name=JSundGenossen>{{cite web|title=In Gedenken an John Schehr und Genossen|work=\"Leben ist das, was passiert, w\u00e4hrend du flei\u00dfig dabei bist, andere Pl\u00e4ne zu schmieden.\" John Lennon|publisher=Thomas Tr\u00fcten, Esslingen am Neckar|author=[[Erich Weinert]]|date= 21 March 2016|url=https://www.trueten.de/permalink/John-Schehr-und-Genossen.html|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEs geht durch die Nacht. Die Nacht ist kalt.<br>\nDer Fahrer bremst. Sie halten im Wald.<br>\nZehn Mann Geheime Staatspolizei.<br>\nVier Kommunisten sitzen dabei,<br>\nJohn Schehr und Genossen.\n\nDer Transportf\u00fchrer sagt: \"Kein Mensch zu sehn.\"<br>\nJohn Schehr fragt: \"Warum bleiben wir stehn?\"<br>\nDer F\u00fchrer fl\u00fcstert: \"Die Sache geht glatt!\"<br>\nNun wissen sie, was es geschlagen hat,<br>\nJohn Schehr und Genossen.\n\nSie sehn, wie die ihre Pistolen ziehn.<br>\nJohn Schehr fragt: \"Nicht wahr, jetzt m\u00fcssen wir fliehn?\"<br>\nDie Kerle lachen. \"Na, wird es bald?<br>\nRunter vom Wagen und rein in den Wald,<br>\nJohn Schehr und Genossen!\"\n{{right |''[[Erich Weinert]]''}}<br><br>\n\n''Going through the night.   The cold night.''<br>\n''The driver brakes.   They stop in the forest.''<br>\n''Ten men of the secret police.''<br>\n''Four communists sit alongside,''<br>\n''John Schehr and comrades!''\n\n''The leader of the transport says:  \"No one to be seen.\"<br>\n''John Schehr asks: \"why aren't we moving?\"<br>\n''The leader whispers: \"It's going smoothly!\"<br>\n''Now you [will] know, what it's about,<br>\n''John Schehr and comrades!''\n\n''They see how [their guards] draw their pistols.<br>\n''John Schehr asks:  \"Is it now that we must escape?\"<br>\n''The lads laugh.  \"well, will it be soon?<br>\n''Out of the transport and srtraight into the wood,<br>\n''John Schehr and comrades!\"''\n}}\nMuch later it was determined that the killer had been a police officer called [[:de:Bruno Sattler|Bruno Sattler]].   After the [[Second World War|war]] and the [[Nazi Germany|Nazi nightmare]] were over, on 11 August 1947, with Berlin divided into military zones of occupation, a clandestine operation was undertaken from the [[Soviet occupation zone]].   This involved the kidnapping from what was becoming known as \"West Berlin\" of Sattler, who was smuggled across to the east and secretly sentenced to life imprisonment.   He was officially (but incorrectly) declared dead in 1949.   Although John Schehr and his three fellow victims became heroic figures in the [[Soviet occupation zone]] (relaunched in 1949 as [[East Germany|the German Democratic Republic / \"East Germany\")]], the kidnapping and sentencing of their killer never made it to the national schools curriculum.   Sattler served his sentence and on 15 October 1972 died in prison, aged 74, under circumstances that were never entirely clear.   His youngest daughter, who had been born in 1942, and with her family had escaped to [[West Germany]] after a final cuddle from her father in 1945, grew up convinced that her father was a good man tradduced by Soviet propaganda.  After [[German reunification| reunification]] she was keen to press for his rehabilitation.   She was able to undertake extensive research in the scrupulously maintained files that the [[Stasi|East German security services]] had compiled and maintained during the intervening decades, and she was forced to accept not just that her father was the man who had murdered \"John Schehr\" and his comrades, but that this had been just the first in a succession of escalating atrocities for which Bruno Sattler had been responsible during the [[Nazi Germany|twelve Nazi years]].   In its own terms it had all amounted to a highly successful career as a senior [[Gestapo]] officer.<ref name=BSlautUG>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304112709/http://www.mdr.de/mdr-figaro/hoerspiel/feature/johnschehr100.html|date=1 March 2013|title=John Schehr und Genossen - Ein Mord, ein Mythos und die Folgen|author=Udo Grashoff|work=mdr Figaro: Kulturradio| publisher=[[Mitteldeutscher Rundfunk]], Leipzig|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BSlautSpiegelLon>{{cite web| title=Beate Niemann: My father was an evil Nazi killer|work=When Beate Niemann was a little girl, her mother always told her the father who vanished when she was a toddler was a man to be proud of.|date=9 March 2011|url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/beate-niemann-my-father-was-an-evil-nazi-115062|publisher=[[Daily Mirror]], London|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== John Schehr und Genossen ==\nIt is not known precisely when [[Erich Weinert]] wrote his [[ballad|ballad-style]] poem \"John Schehr und Genossen\" (''\"John Schehr and comrades\"''), but it appears to have been written very soon after the killings became public knowledge, probably during 1934.   Weinert was a committed antifascist who escaped via the [[Saarland]] and [[Paris]] to [[Moscow]] which is where he spent most of the [[Nazi Germany|twelve Nazi years]].   According to [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia|\"The Great Soviet Encyclopedia\"]] he published an anthology of poems in Moscow as early as 1934: this may have included his tribute to Schehr, but it would not have been widely available in Germany under the [[Hitler cabinet|Hitler dictatorship]], nor anywhere else in western Europe.<ref name=EWlautGro\u00dfeSowjetischeEnzyklop\u00e4die>{{cite web|url=https://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Erich+Weinert\n|work= [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]] ([[:ru:\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f|\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f]]) |date=1979 |title= Weinert, Erich:  Born Aug. 4, 1890, in Magdeburg; died Apr. 20, 1953, in Berlin. German poet. Son of an engineer. |publisher=Farlex ([[The Free Dictionary]])|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[End of World War II in Europe|After 1945]] the western two thirds of Germany was divided into four [[Allied occupation of Germany|military occupation zones]].   In the central region, [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|administered]] as the [[Soviet occupation zone]], \"John Schehr und Genossen\" quickly became widely known, and the late John Schehr was quickly elevated to the status of a national icon.   There was a pressing need to rename all the sreets which since 1933 had been named after [[Nazi party|National Socialist]] leaders and characters from their pantheon of German nationalist heroes.   Across the region (which in October 1949 was relaunched as the [[Group of Soviet Forces in Germany|Soviet sponsored]] [[German Democratic Republic |the German Democratic Republic (East Germany)]], the authorities in towns and cities renamed streets, public buildings and other public structires after John Schehr.   (Some of the streets and building in question have been renamed again during the subsequent 75 years).<ref name=BSlautUG/><ref name=JSuGlautTM>{{cite web|url=https://taz.de/!676676/|date=9 November 2004|author=Thomas Martin|title=John Schehr und Genossen |work=Leerstelle ... Um die Danziger Stra\u00dfe l\u00e4sst sich ein kommunistisches Widerstandsquartier besichtigen \u2013 schon mal den Stra\u00dfennamen nach|volume=Ausgabe 7509|publisher=taz Verlags u. Vertriebs GmbH , Berlin |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1967 a [[cargo ship]] was launched at [[:de:Schiffbau in der DDR |the government shipyards]] in [[Rostock]] for the East German [[:de:Deutsche Seereederei |Deutsche Seereederei fleet]] and given the name \"John Schehr\".<ref name=SeeleuteHRlautHJM>{{cite web|title=John Schehr IMO 6710528  123 DEVM / Y5MM  15.07.1966 26.11.1985 Sparta Shipping, Malta|work=Die Schiffe der Serie   ....   Typ XC|author=Hans-J\u00fcrgen Mathy (compiler)|publisher=Seeleute Rostock e. V., Schwerin|url=http://www.seeleute-rostock.de/content/moreships/3-Freighter-20/3b-Type-X/vesselgen2.htm|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>{{efn| The \"MS John Schehr\" was subsequently broken up in [[Malta]] in 1985.<ref name=SeeleuteHRlautHJM/>}}\n\nAlready, in 1954, Schehr's physical remains had been disinterred from their resting place in [[Marzahn|Berlin-Marzahn]] to the [[Zentralfriedhof Friedrichsfelde|Friedrichsfelde Main Cemetery]] where they were placed in the [[:de:Gedenkst\u00e4tte der Sozialisten|\"Gedenkst\u00e4tte der Sozialisten\"]], the special section reserved for heroes of socialism.<ref name=Gedenktafeln>{{cite web|url=https://www.gedenktafeln-in-berlin.de/nc/gedenktafeln/gedenktafel-anzeige/tid/opfer-des-nationalso-32/|title=Opfer des Nationalsozialismus|publisher=Gedenkst\u00e4tte Deutscher Widerstand , Berlin|work=Gedenktafeln an historischen Orten in Berlin|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!---\nwiki-de\n\n\n    Und schleppen sie in den dunklen Wald.\n    Und zw\u00f6lfmal knallt es und widerhallt.\n    Da liegen sie mit erloschenem Blick,\n    jeder drei Nahsch\u00fcsse im Genick,\n    John Schehr und Genossen.[5]\n\nSeit 1992 erinnert in Berlin in der N\u00e4he des Reichstags eine der 96 Gedenktafeln f\u00fcr von den Nationalsozialisten ermordete Reichstagsabgeordnete an Schehr. In Berlin-Prenzlauer Berg, Halle (Saale)-Radewell, Neubrandenburg, Pasewalk, Teltow, Rostock, Wei\u00dfenfels, Riesa, Wurzen und Lauchhammer sind Stra\u00dfen nach John Schehr benannt.\n\nAm Kilometerberg befindet sich ein Gedenkstein f\u00fcr John Schehr und die anderen Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer, die hier 1934 \u201eauf der Flucht erschossen\u201c wurden. Seit 1954 finden dort Gedenkveranstaltungen f\u00fcr die vier Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer statt.[6]\n\nIn der ehemaligen Steigerkaserne am Drosselberg in Erfurt kann man noch heute einen John-Schehr-Gedenkstein sehen, eingefasst in einem kleinen Ehrenhain, gleich rechts hinter dem Eingangsgeb\u00e4ude. Allerdings wurden die Gedenkworte herausgemei\u00dfelt, so dass diese heute nur noch in Ans\u00e4tzen lesbar sind. In der Kaserne trug das hier stationierte MotSch\u00fctzenRegiment 24 den Ehrennamen \u201eJohn Schehr\u201c. \n\nHDK\n\n--->\n{{clear}}\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |35em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schehr, John}}\n\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hamburg]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Germany politicians]]<!---activist member but probably too young to count as \"a politician\".   Activist obsessives in the wiki community nevertheless regularly delete categories for SPD / USPD \"party members\", so \"politician\" is applied here as a default for those readers who think John Schehr's early party affiliations are worth flagging--->\n[[Category:Independent Social Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Germany members]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Prussia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Reichstag of the Weimar Republic]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Germany]]\n[[Category:Communists in the German Resistance]]\n[[Category:Resistance members killed by Nazi Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Schehr\n| image         = \n| caption       =\n| imagesize     =  \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 9 February 1896\n| birth_place   = [[Ottensen]], [[Altona|Altona, Hamburg]], [[German empire|Germany]]\n| death_date    = 1/2 February 1934 (overnight)\n| death_place   = [[:de:Sch\u00e4ferberg|Sch\u00e4ferberg / Kilometerberg (hill)]], [[Wannsee|Berlin-Wannsee]], [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n| occupation    = Skilled metal worker<br>Dock worker<br>Political activist<br>Party officer<br>Politician<br>[[Communist Party of Germany|Party]] leader<br>Gestapo murder victim\n| party         =  [[Social Democratic Party of Germany |SPD]]<br>[[Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany|USPD]]<br>[[Communist Party of Germany|KPD]]\n|spouse         =  Anna\n|parents        = \n|children       = \n|alma_mater     = \n| nationality   = \n}}\n\n'''John Schehr''' (9 February 1896 - 1 February 1934) was a [[Germany|German]] political activist who became a [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]] politician and ultimately, following the arrest on 3 March 1933 of [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], Chairman (leader) of [[Communist Party of Germany|the party]].   By this time [[Nazi Germany|the country]] was very rapidly [[Gleichschaltung| being transformed]] into a [[one-party state|one-]][[Nazi Party|party]] [[Enabling Act of 1933 |dictatorship]], meaning that the party John Schehr led was outlawed, with those members of the leadership team who had not escaped abroad now living \"underground\" (unregistered) and in hiding.   Schehr was nevertheless arrested on 13 November 1933 and taken to [[Columbia concentration camp|a Berlin concentration camp]]. He died when he was one of four men shot by [[Gestapo]] officials, reportedly \"while escaping\" during an overnight transport, following arrest.<ref name=JSlauHDK>{{cite web |title= Schehr, John  * 9.2.1896  \u2020 1.2.1934|work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/john-schehr?ID=5063 |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=JSlautGDW>{{cite web|url=https://www.gdw-berlin.de/en/recess/biographies/index_of_persons/biographie/view-bio/john-schehr/?no_cache=1|title=John Schehr:  February 09, 1896 - February 01, 1934 |publisher= Gedenkst\u00e4tte Deutscher Widerstand (German Resistance Memorial Center), Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name= JSlautFreundeskreisET>{{cite web|url=http://www.etg-ziegenhals.de/John_Schehr.html|title=John Schehr (1896 \u2013 1934) |publisher= Freundeskreis \u201eErnst Th\u00e4lmann\u201c e.V., Ziegenhals-Berlin|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Aftermath of World War II|National Socialist nightmare ended]] Schehr and his three murdered comrades became celebrated, for the benefit of a new generation, in the [[German Democratic Republic|German Democratic Republic (East Germany: 1949-1989)]] by means of a poem written, probably, shortly after the killing, by [[Erich Weinert]].<ref name=JohnSchehruGenossen>{{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130304112709/http://www.mdr.de/mdr-figaro/hoerspiel/feature/johnschehr100.html|date=2 March 2013| title=John Schehr und Genossen|work=Ein Mord, ein Mythos und die Folgen|publisher=[[MDR Fernsehen |MDR]] (\"Figaro\"), [[Leipzig]]|accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n=== Provenance and early years ===\nJohn \"Jonny\" Schehr was born into a working-class family in the [[Ottensen]] quarter of [[Altona|Altona, Hamburg]], at that time a robustly independent municipality, but [[Greater Hamburg Act|subsequently - in 1937 -  subsumed]] into [[Hamburg]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   His father worked as a [[hairdresser]].<ref name=JSlautFS/>   As a boy he was particularly close to his mother, born Martha Fischer.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   John Schehr's younger brother, Franz, later recalled that the family always read [[:de:Hamburger Echo|the Hamburger Echo]] and [[:de:Der wahre Jacob|Wahre Jacob]], both staunchly [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] newspapers.<ref name=JSlautFS>:{{cite web|page=4|work=Franz Schehr: Erinnerung an den Bruder|url= https://www.thaelmann-gedenkstaette.de/GSETHP/Rundbriefe/RB40.pdf|publisher=Kuratorium Gedenkst\u00e4tte Ernst Th\u00e4lmann e.V.:  article reproduced in \"Rundbrief aus dem Th\u00e4lmann-Haus\" from \"John Schehr 1896-1934. Biographische Skizze: DKP Kreis Altona und Kuratorium \u201eGedenkst\u00e4tteErnst  Th\u00e4lmann\u201c  e.V.,  Hamburg  1984|date=February 2004|author=Franz Schehr|title=John Schehr und Genossen |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   Schehr attended school locally in [[Ottensen]] and then completed an apprenticeship as a [[:de:Schlosserei|skilled metal worker]] with \"Firma Meier\" (Gerberstra\u00dfe), an Altona manufacturing company.<ref name=JSlautFS/>    Towards the end of 1912, still aged only 16, joined the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany |Social Democratic Party (''\"Sozialdemokratische Partei Deutschlands\"''/ SPD)]].<ref name=JSlautGDW/>   The next year he also joined the Transport Workers' Union<!--- Transportarbeitergewerkschaft ---><ref name=JSlautDieLinke>{{cite web|title=John Schehr und Genossen|page=2|publisher=Kreisvorstand DIE LINKE, Potsdam |work=Potsdams andere Seiten|url=https://www.dielinke-potsdam.de/fileadmin/potsdam/PAS/2017/PaS_Maerz_2017.pdf|date=March 2017 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   He was working during this period [[Port of Hamburg|on the Hamburg docks]], which is how he came to know [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]].\n\n=== War years and the beginnings of the Communist Party ===\nIn 1916 or 1917 Schehr was conscripted into an artillery regiment and sent to serve at [[Neuf-Brisach|Neu Breisach]], an important [[Fortification|redoubt]] which at that time was part of [[German empire|Germany]].     Without intending it, he found himself promoted to the rank of a [[Unteroffizier|\"sub-officer\" (''\"Unteroffizier\"'')]].   It is recorded that during one retreat he skilfully led his troops so that they avoided capture.   His brother Walter Schehr was killed in action in 1916.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   The 1914 decision of the party leadership to [[Burgfriedenspolitik|vote in favour]] of [[War bond|war funding]] and forego criticism of the government for the duration of hostilities during the [[First World War|war]] had been contentious among party activists from the outset, and the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] finally split over the issue of support for the war in 1917.   John Schehr, like his mentor [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], was one of a large number of mainly left-wing party members who moved across to the breakaway [[Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany|Independent Social Democratic Party (''\" Unabh\u00e4ngige Sozialdemokratische Partei Deutschlands\"'' / USPD)]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=JSlautFS/>   After the war there was no immediate return to his skilled work, but [[Port of Hamburg|the docks]] continued to function and he joined his brother Franz in work as a [[stevedore]] till 1924.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   In 1919 when, in its turn, the [[Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany|USPD)]], [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann |Th\u00e4lmann]] and Schehr, were among the early recruits to the newly launched [[Communist Party of Germany |Communist Party]] in the wake of the so-called [[German Revolution of 1918\u20131919 |November revolutions]].<ref name=JSlautGDW/>    Almost all the USPD activists in the Hamburg district made the same move, which can be seen in large measure as a tribute to Ernst Th\u00e4lmann's oratorical and political powers of persuasion.   Schehr quickly became an energetic party activist:  his brother recalled later that during the early 1920s he was out almost every evening, undertaking party work.<ref name=JSlautFS/>   \n\n=== From party activist to party officer ===\n1923 was a year of [[Hyperinflation in the Weimar Republic|intensified destitution]] across [[Weimar Germany|Germany]], and a number of [[Cuno strikes|major disturbances]].  In Hamburg Schehr took part in the storming the [[Ottensen]] police station, which was one of police stations in and around Hamburg attacked on 23 October in the context of that year's  [[Hamburg Uprising|October uprising]], carefully planned and choreographed by Ernst Th\u00e4lmann on behalf of [[Communist Party of Germany |the party]].<ref name=JSlautFS/>   In 1924 Schehr became a party \"Polleiter\" (''loosely, \"policy head\"'') for [[Altona, Hamburg| Altona]] where he was already, by this time, a municipal councillor.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   He also regained his skilled work [[Port of Hamburg|on the docks]].   The next year he accepted a fulltime job working within [[Communist Party of Germany |the party]] apparatus, however.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   It is clear that John Schehr's advancement in the national party over the next few years owed much to the friendship and political patronage of [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], but he evidently had many friends and admirers among local party activists.   A particular friend and political ally was [[:de:Etkar Andr\u00e9 |Etkar Andr\u00e9]].<ref name=JSlautFS/> \n\n=== Party advancement ===\nIt was nevertheless more likely to have been as a result, primarily, of [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann|Th\u00e4lmann's]] backing that in 1925, at the tenth party congress, John Schehr was elected to membership of the party appeal's commission (''\"Beschwerdekommissio\"'').   The same congress also voted Schehr onto the list of candidates for [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD|the Party Central Committee]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   The dire economic situation during the early 1920s made this a period of expansion for the [[Communist Party of Germany |communists]] in the industrial regions, and during 1925 John Schehr was appointed to lead the party organisation in the recently established [[Harburg-Wilhelmsburg]] sub-district (''\"Unterbezirksleiter\"'') in succession to [[:de:Johann Skjellerup |Johann Skjellerup]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=UBLinHWlautCG/>   The appointment was of short duration, however, since in March 1926 the fulltime paid position was abolished, possibly to save money and possibly in response to a decline in party membership locally.<ref name=UBLinHWlautCG>{{cite web|url=http://www.harbuch.de/frische-themen-artikel/radli3.html|title=Die radikale Linke in Harburg-Wilhelmsburg|work=Nachtrag 2: Organisatorische St\u00e4rken und Schw\u00e4chen, interne Fraktionsk\u00e4mpfe 1924-1931|publisher=Dr. Christian Gotthardt, Hamburg|author=Christian Gotthardt|date=April 2018|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>   In 1927 he was appointed \"Orgleiter\" (''loosely \"Head of Administration\"'') for the party's important Hamburg-Wasserkante district (to the west and north of Hamburg),<ref name=JSlautGDW/><ref name=\"EvansGeary2015\">{{cite book|author1=Anthony McElligott (author) |author2=Dick Geary (compiler-editor)|title=Mobilising the unemployed:  the KPD and the Unemployed Workers' Movement in Hamburg-Altona during the Weimar Republic|work=The German Unemployed (Routledge Revivals): Experiences and Consequences of Mass Unemployment from the Weimar Republic to the Third Reich|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SUfLCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT289 |date=5 June 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-54203-2|pages=288\u2013294}}</ref> thereby becoming a key member of the regional party executive under the leadership of regional party secretary [[:de:John Wittorf |John Wittorf]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>\n\n=== Wittorf affair ===\nAlso in 1927 Schehr was again a delegate at the party's eleventh party congress, held that year in [[Essen]].   Again he was voted onto the list of candidates for [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD |the Party Central Committee]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   As a member of the Control Commission for the Hamburg-Wasserkante party organisation, Schehr was implicated in concealing the embezzlement of party funds by [[:de:John Wittorf |John Wittorf]] during the course of a scandal that blew up in 1928.  [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]] was, by some criteria, more heavily and directly implicated, and he was indeed briefly ousted from the [[Central Committee|party Central Committee]], but [[Joseph Stalin]], whose influence over the [[Communist Party of Germany|German party leadership]] was immense, intervened to have Th\u00e4lmann reinstated.   From now on Th\u00e4lmann was seen by party comrades as [[Stalinism|\"Stalin's man\"]]:  it did his career no harm.<ref name=ETlauHDK>{{cite web|title= Th\u00e4lmann, Ernst  * 16.4.1886  \u2020  18.8.1944|work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/ernst-thaelmann |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   There was no intervention with such immediate impact on behalf of John Schehr who was stripped of all his party functions in October 1928.   There were even demands for Schehr to be excluded from the party, but that did not happen.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>\n\n=== Political recovery and advancement ===\nFollowing [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]]'s rehabilitation Schehr, as Th\u00e4lmann's respected prot\u00e9g\u00e9, quickly recovered his position in the party.  He was reinstated as [[Communist Party of Germany|party]] \"Orgleiter\" for the  Hamburg-Wasserkante district, retaining the post till March 1930.   In 1929, at the eleventh party congress (held in [[Wedding (Berlin)|Berlin-Wedding]]) Schehr was again present as a delegate, and he was yet again included on the candidates list for [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD |Central Committee membership]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref>Protokoll XII. Parteitag der KPD 1929</ref>   An [[East Germany|East German]] newspaper tribute which appeared in 1967 states that on this occasion he was elected to full membership of the [[Central Committee|party Central Committee]],<ref name=JSlautND>{{cite web|title=John Schehr  1896-1934|work=Der aus Altona geb\u00fcrtige Arbeitersohn, selbst gelernter Schlosser, kam schon vor den ersten Weltkrieg zur Arbeiterbewegung....|publisher=[[Neues Deutschland]], Berlin |url=https://www.nd-archiv.de/ausgabe/1967-03-01 |date=1 March 1967|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> but other more plausible sources [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder der Zentralkomitees der KPD|refute this]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   It is nevertheless clear that by this stage John Schehr was widely respected and liked by party comrades<ref name=JSlautFS/> whereas his more formidable mentor, [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]], who had been party leader since 1925, is more usually seen as having been widely feared within the party by this point.<ref name=ETlauHDK/>   \n\n=== Crisis years ===\nIn 1930 John Schehr took over the job of regional party secretary (''\"Polleiter\"'') with the [[Hanover]]-based regional leadership team (''\"Bezirksleitung\"'') for the Lower Saxony region in succession to [[:de:Willi Bohn |Willi Bohn]], whom the national party leadership had decided (at very short notice) should be sent to the [[International Lenin School]] in [[Moscow]] for two years of party training.<ref name=WBlauHDK>{{cite web|title=Bohn, Willi Karl   * 6.8.1900 \u2020 23.1.1985 |work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/willi-karl-bohn|publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>   His slow but steady progression through the party ranks meant that he was beginning to emerge from behind [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann|Th\u00e4lmann's]] shadow.   Meanwhile a return to widespread economic austerity, as [[Weimar Germany|Germany]] worked through the savage backwash from the [[Great depression]], was creating a surge across Germany in support for the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]].   This was accompanied by increasing political polarisation leading, after [[July 1932 German federal election|1932]], to deadlock in the [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag (''national parliament'')]] whereby coalition with on or other of the two populist parties, the [[Nazi Party|National Socialists]] and the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communists]] was mathematically necessary for the more moderate parties to coalesce to form a majority coalition, but both extremist parties were unacceptable coaliation parties either for the moderate parties or form each other.   It was in the resulting context of intensifying crisis that in April 1932 John Schehr was elected to [[:de:Liste der Mitglieder des Landtages (Freistaat Preu\u00dfen) (4. Wahlperiode)|membership]] of the [[Landtag of Prussia|Prussian Landtag (''regional parliament'')]] in [[Berlin]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   Three months later, in [[July 1932 German federal election|July 1932]], he was elected to the  [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]].<ref name=JSlautDieLinke/>   (His [[Landtag of Prussia|Landtag]] seat was taken over by his party comrade [[:de:August T\u00fcnnermann|August T\u00fcnnermann]].<ref name=ATlauHDK>{{cite web|title=T\u00fcnnermann, August   * 18.8.1896   \u2020 23.12.1982 |work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1= [[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/ernst-thaelmann |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\nWithin the party Schehr's career continued to advance.   During the middle of 1932 he finally became a member of the [[Communist Party of Germany|party]] [[Central Committee]].   This came about not through any vote of delegates at a party congress, but as a result of being co-opted into membership by the existing members.   He relocated to [[Berlin]], becoming both secretary to the Central Committee and a member of its inner caucus, the Politburo.   Schehr was now, in all but name, deputy to the party leader, [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]].   His position in the party aparatus was further strengthened after [[Heinz Neumann]] was stripped of his party funcations and then officially condemned by the leadership in November 1932 and sent as a comintern emissary to [[Spain]].   (Neumann had clashed with Th\u00e4lmann whom he believed, along with [[Joseph Stalin]], was dangerously underestimating the strength of the threat presented by [[Adolf Hitler]].<ref name=HNlauHDK>{{cite web| title=Neumann, Heinz  * 6.7.1902   \u2020 26.11.1937  |work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1= [[Hermann Weber]]|author2= [[Andreas Herbst]] |url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/de/recherche/kataloge-datenbanken/biographische-datenbanken/heinz-neumann |publisher= Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>)\n\nIt was probably in October or November 1932 that the police arrested John Schehr  and discovered \"important material\" concerning the [[Communist Party of Germany|party's]] illegal structures (which included a semi-secret quasi-military operation across the nation and a large \"political\" espionage network on a scale normally associated with foreign governments rather than with domestic political parties).<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   The arrest was apparently made \"because of an instruction from the Ministry of Defence\".<ref name=spiegel12993>{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-13682818.html|volume=12/1993|title=Einsamer Wolf unter W\u00f6lfen|work=Eine Moskauer Personalakte der Kommunistischen Internationale erhellt das Bild Herbert Wehners, der nach dem Krieg zum SPD-Vizevorsitzenden und Minister aufstieg. In den Terrorjahren 1937 bis 1941 lebte er - zusammen mit dem sp\u00e4teren DDR-Gr\u00fcnder Walter Ulbricht - in Moskau. Dort belastete er Genossen, die der sowjetischen Geheimpolizei zum Opfer fielen. Rettete er die eigene Haut? Oder suchte er S\u00fchne f\u00fcr Verr\u00e4ter?|author=Fritjof Meyer|date=22 March 1993|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>   Although sources differ wildly over the month of Schehr's 1932 arrest, it is apparent that he was released after eight days in detention.   Regardless of the legal basis for the arrest (which remains vague and unclear), as a member of the  [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag (''national parliament'')]] till some months after the [[Machtergreifung |r\u00e9gime change]] in 1933, John Schehr enjoyed certain privileges, and it would appear to have been on account of these that on this occasion his release came so swiftly.<ref name=JSlauHDK/> \n\n=== R\u00e9gime change ===\nThe [[Hitler cabinet|Hitler government]] exploited the continuing parliamentary and political deadlock to [[Machtergreifung |take power]] in January 1933.   They lost no time in [[Gleichschaltung|transforming Germany]] into a [[one-party state|one-]][[Nazi Party |party]] [[Enabling Act of 1933|dictatorship]].  Over the next few weeks the [[Communist Party of Germany |Communist party]] was outlawed and those of its leaders who had not already gone into hiding or emigrated were rounded up by the [[Gestapo|security services]].  On 7 February 1933 Schehr was one of the participants at the [[:de:Sporthaus Ziegenhals|\"illegal\" Sporthaus Ziegenhals meeting]] held just outside Berlin, and celebrated subsequently (especially during the \"East German\" years) as the last meeting held by the German Communist Party leadership before the participants were arrested and killed, or in some cases managed to escape abroad.<ref name= JSlautFreundeskreisET/><ref name= ZiegenhalsTeilnehmer>{{cite web |  url=http://www.etg-ziegenhals.de/Teilnehmer.html | title= Teilnehmer an der Tagung des ZK der KPD am 07. Februar 1933 | publisher=Freundeskreis \u201eErnst-Th\u00e4lmann-Gedenkst\u00e4tte\u201c e.V., Ziegenhals, K\u00f6nigs-Wusterhausen   | accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March 1933 [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]] was arrested as part of the wave of (apparently preplanned) political arrests that followed the [[Reichstag fire]].   It was the [[Comintern]], presumably under instructions from [[Joseph Stalin |Moscow]], that transferred the party chairmanship to John Schehr, as Th\u00e4lmann's de facto deputy.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   The chairmanship appointment meant that he became the official leader of the from now on \"underground\" Communist Party.   His leadership position came under challenge both from [[Walter Ulbricht]] and from [[Hermann Schubert]], suggesting that even if he had not been killed early the next year, the term of his leadership might still have been brief.<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=\"SchmitthennerGraml1970\">{{cite book|author1=Walter Schmitthenner|author2=Hermann Graml|title=Resistance in the labour movement: The German Communist Party (KPD)|work=The German Resistance to Hitler|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bFwcCy2MfvEC&pg=PA167|year=1970|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-01662-0|pages=164\u2013180}}</ref>\n\n=== Arrest, detention, torture and killing/murder ===\nBy the second part of 1933 many more party comrades had found their way to Paris or Moscow, and John Schehr was the only member of a [[Communist Party of Germany|the party]] leadership team still hiding out in Germany.<ref name=\"Frank2009\">{{cite book|author=Mario Frank|title=Walter Ulbricht: Eine deutsche Biografie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QfNvCR_-L8cC&pg=PT112|date=26 January 2009|publisher=Siedler Verlag|isbn=978-3-641-01040-9|pages=112\u2013}}</ref>    The [[Gestapo|security services]] arrested him in [[Berlin]] on 13 November 1933.   This time there would be no question of their letting him go again a week later.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   He was taken to the [[Columbia concentration camp]], a former military police station on the edge of Berlin that had stood empy since 1929, till its conversion into a prison during 1933.<ref name= \"GeserickWirth2011\">{{cite book|author1=Gunther Geserick|author2=Ingo Wirth|author3=Klaus Vendura|title=Die Nacht der Langen Messer|work=Zeitzeuge Tod: Spektakul\u00e4re F\u00e4lle der Gerichtsmedizin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dBJ3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT203|date=25 July 2011|publisher=Militzke Verlag|isbn=978-3-86189-798-9|page=203}}</ref>    The [[Gestapo]] knew that Schehr was a senior party functionary and they did their best to extract statements from him, employing some of the worst forms of torture.   He suffered sever burns and there are also reports that one of his eyes was knocked out of its socket.   However, the Gestapo failed to extract from him the information that they sought.<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=JSlautHRS>{{cite web|author=[[:de:Hans-Rainer Sandvo\u00df|Hans-Rainer Sandvo\u00df]]|publisher=Gedenkst\u00e4tte Deutscher Widerstand, Berlin |issn= 0175-3592|date=October 1985|pages=168-169|title=Mord am Kilometerberg|work=Widerstand 1933 - 1945 in Steglitz und Zahlendorf |url= https://www.gdw-berlin.de/fileadmin/bilder/publikationen/Widerstand_in_Berlin/Widerstand%20in%20Steglitz%20und%20Zehlendorf_1986.pdf |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt had become known that the [[Gestapo|Security services]] had been employing a spy in the secret Berlin headquarters of the [[Communist Party of Germany|Communist Party]].   This was [[:de:Alfred Kattner|Alfred Kattner]], a one-time confidant of  [[Ernst Th\u00e4lmann]] who had been arrested in March 1933, tortured, persuaded to gather information for the [[Gestapo|security services]] and then, in August 1933, released.   It was believed that information gathered and passed on to his handlers by Kattner had enabled the Gestapo to arrest John Schehr, among others.  Kattner's role became known to comrades through the underground press during January 1934 and, after attempts to have him kidnapped and spirited away to Moscow had failed, on 1 February 1934 [[:de:Alfred Kattner|Alfred Kattner]] was shot dead by a party official called [[:de:Hans Schwarz (Parteifunktion\u00e4r)|Hans Schwarz]] in his [[:de:Nowawes|Nowawes]] apartment just outside Berlin.   The [[Nazi Party|National Socialist government]] was enraged by this turn of events.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>   \n\nAt the time of Schehr's arrest other leading party activists were also captured, including [[Eugen Sch\u00f6nhaar]] and [[:de:Rudolf Schwarz (Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer) |Rudolf Schwarz]].   One response to Kattner's killing was an order for the immediate transfer of the men from the [[Columbia concentration camp]] to a facility at the [[Gro\u00dfer Wannsee|Wannsee]].   An overnight transport was arranged.   During the night of 1/2 February 1934 these three, together with [[:de:Erich Steinfurth|Erich Steinfurth]] (who had been arrested back in March 1933) were shot dead at the [[:de:Sch\u00e4ferberg|Sch\u00e4ferberg / Kilometerberg (hill)]] on the edge of [[Berlin]] by [[Gestapo]] personnel, allegedly \"while attempting to escape\".   In reality commentators agree that the murder was an act of quick retribution following the shooting the previous day of the government spy [[:de:Alfred Kattner|Alfred Kattner]].<ref name=JSlauHDK/><ref name=ESlauHDK>{{cite web|title=Sch\u00f6nhaar, Eugen   * 29.10.1898, \u2020 1.2.1934|work=Handbuch der Deutschen Kommunisten| author1=[[Hermann Weber]]|author2=[[Andreas Herbst]]|url= https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363;-1424.html?ID=5120 |publisher=Karl Dietz Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin| accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>    The killings became widely known:  even at the time, the authorities made no attempt to refute the view that the authorities' motives for the \"act of reckoning\" were all too obvious.<ref name=JSlauHDK/>\n\n==The killer==\n{{Quote box|bgcolor=#FFDEAD|align=right|width=32%|\n\n'''John Schehr und Genossen'''<ref name=JSundGenossen>{{cite web|title=In Gedenken an John Schehr und Genossen|work=\"Leben ist das, was passiert, w\u00e4hrend du flei\u00dfig dabei bist, andere Pl\u00e4ne zu schmieden.\" John Lennon|publisher=Thomas Tr\u00fcten, Esslingen am Neckar|author=[[Erich Weinert]]|date= 21 March 2016|url=https://www.trueten.de/permalink/John-Schehr-und-Genossen.html|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEs geht durch die Nacht. Die Nacht ist kalt.<br>\nDer Fahrer bremst. Sie halten im Wald.<br>\nZehn Mann Geheime Staatspolizei.<br>\nVier Kommunisten sitzen dabei,<br>\nJohn Schehr und Genossen.\n\nDer Transportf\u00fchrer sagt: \"Kein Mensch zu sehn.\"<br>\nJohn Schehr fragt: \"Warum bleiben wir stehn?\"<br>\nDer F\u00fchrer fl\u00fcstert: \"Die Sache geht glatt!\"<br>\nNun wissen sie, was es geschlagen hat,<br>\nJohn Schehr und Genossen.\n\nSie sehn, wie die ihre Pistolen ziehn.<br>\nJohn Schehr fragt: \"Nicht wahr, jetzt m\u00fcssen wir fliehn?\"<br>\nDie Kerle lachen. \"Na, wird es bald?<br>\nRunter vom Wagen und rein in den Wald,<br>\nJohn Schehr und Genossen!\"\n{{right |''[[Erich Weinert]]''}}<br><br>\n\n''Going through the night.   The cold night.''<br>\n''The driver brakes.   They stop in the forest.''<br>\n''Ten men of the secret police.''<br>\n''Four communists sit alongside,''<br>\n''John Schehr and comrades!''\n\n''The leader of the transport says:  \"No one to be seen.\"<br>\n''John Schehr asks: \"why aren't we moving?\"<br>\n''The leader whispers: \"It's going smoothly!\"<br>\n''Now you [will] know, what it's about,<br>\n''John Schehr and comrades!''\n\n''They see how [their guards] draw their pistols.<br>\n''John Schehr asks:  \"Is it now that we must escape?\"<br>\n''The lads laugh.  \"well, will it be soon?<br>\n''Out of the transport and srtraight into the wood,<br>\n''John Schehr and comrades!\"''\n}}\nMuch later it was determined that the killer had been a police officer called [[:de:Bruno Sattler|Bruno Sattler]].   After the [[Second World War|war]] and the [[Nazi Germany|Nazi nightmare]] were over, on 11 August 1947, with Berlin divided into military zones of occupation, a clandestine operation was undertaken from the [[Soviet occupation zone]].   This involved the kidnapping from what was becoming known as \"West Berlin\" of Sattler, who was smuggled across to the east and secretly sentenced to life imprisonment.   He was officially (but incorrectly) declared dead in 1949.   Although John Schehr and his three fellow victims became heroic figures in the [[Soviet occupation zone]] (relaunched in 1949 as [[East Germany|the German Democratic Republic / \"East Germany\")]], the kidnapping and sentencing of their killer never made it to the national schools curriculum.   Sattler served his sentence and on 15 October 1972 died in prison, aged 74, under circumstances that were never entirely clear.   His youngest daughter, who had been born in 1942, and with her family had escaped to [[West Germany]] after a final cuddle from her father in 1945, grew up convinced that her father was a good man tradduced by Soviet propaganda.  After [[German reunification| reunification]] she was keen to press for his rehabilitation.   She was able to undertake extensive research in the scrupulously maintained files that the [[Stasi|East German security services]] had compiled and maintained during the intervening decades, and she was forced to accept not just that her father was the man who had murdered \"John Schehr\" and his comrades, but that this had been just the first in a succession of escalating atrocities for which Bruno Sattler had been responsible during the [[Nazi Germany|twelve Nazi years]].   In its own terms it had all amounted to a highly successful career as a senior [[Gestapo]] officer.<ref name=BSlautUG>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304112709/http://www.mdr.de/mdr-figaro/hoerspiel/feature/johnschehr100.html|date=1 March 2013|title=John Schehr und Genossen - Ein Mord, ein Mythos und die Folgen|author=Udo Grashoff|work=mdr Figaro: Kulturradio| publisher=[[Mitteldeutscher Rundfunk]], Leipzig|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BSlautSpiegelLon>{{cite web| title=Beate Niemann: My father was an evil Nazi killer|work=When Beate Niemann was a little girl, her mother always told her the father who vanished when she was a toddler was a man to be proud of.|date=9 March 2011|url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/beate-niemann-my-father-was-an-evil-nazi-115062|publisher=[[Daily Mirror]], London|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== John Schehr und Genossen ==\nIt is not known precisely when [[Erich Weinert]] wrote his [[ballad|ballad-style]] poem \"John Schehr und Genossen\" (''\"John Schehr and comrades\"''), but it appears to have been written very soon after the killings became public knowledge, probably during 1934.   Weinert was a a committed antifascist who escaped via the [[Saarland]] and [[Paris]] to [[Moscow]] which is where he spent most of the [[Nazi Germany|twelve Nazi years]].   According to [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia|\"The Great Soviet Encyclopedia\"]] he published an anthology of poems in Moscow as early as 1934: this may have included his tribute to Schehr, but it would not have been widely available in Germany under the [[Hitler cabinet|Hitler dictatorship]], nor anywhere else in western Europe.<ref name=EWlautGro\u00dfeSowjetischeEnzyklop\u00e4die>{{cite web|url=https://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Erich+Weinert\n|work= [[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]] ([[:ru:\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f|\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f]]) |date=1979 |title= Weinert, Erich:  Born Aug. 4, 1890, in Magdeburg; died Apr. 20, 1953, in Berlin. German poet. Son of an engineer. |publisher=Farlex ([[The Free Dictionary]])|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[End of World War II in Europe|After 1945]] the western two thirds of Germany was divided into four [[Allied occupation of Germany|military occupation zones]].   In the central region, [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|administered]] as the [[Soviet occupation zone]], \"John Schehr und Genossen\" quickly became widely known, and the late John Schehr was quickly elevated to the status of a national icon.   There was a pressing need to rename all the sreets which since 1933 had been named after [[Nazi party|National Socialist]] leaders and characters from their pantheon of German nationalist heroes.   Across the region (which in October 1949 was relaunched as the [[Group of Soviet Forces in Germany|Soviet sponsored]] [[German Democratic Republic |the German Democratic Republic (East Germany)]], the authorities in towns and cities renamed streets, public buildings and other public structires after John Schehr.   (Some of the streets and building in question have been renamed again during the subsequent 75 years).<ref name=BSlautUG/><ref name=JSuGlautTM>{{cite web|url=https://taz.de/!676676/|date=9 November 2004|author=Thomas Martin|title=John Schehr und Genossen |work=Leerstelle ... Um die Danziger Stra\u00dfe l\u00e4sst sich ein kommunistisches Widerstandsquartier besichtigen \u2013 schon mal den Stra\u00dfennamen nach|volume=Ausgabe 7509|publisher=taz Verlags u. Vertriebs GmbH , Berlin |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1967 a [[cargo ship]] was launched at [[:de:Schiffbau in der DDR |the government shipyards]] in [[Rostock]] for the East German [[:de:Deutsche Seereederei |Deutsche Seereederei fleet]] and given the name \"John Schehr\".<ref name=SeeleuteHRlautHJM>{{cite web|title=John Schehr IMO 6710528  123 DEVM / Y5MM  15.07.1966 26.11.1985 Sparta Shipping, Malta|work=Die Schiffe der Serie   ....   Typ XC|author=Hans-J\u00fcrgen Mathy (compiler)|publisher=Seeleute Rostock e. V., Schwerin|url=http://www.seeleute-rostock.de/content/moreships/3-Freighter-20/3b-Type-X/vesselgen2.htm|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>{{efn| The \"MS John Schehr\" was subsequently broken up in [[Malta]] in 1985.<ref name=SeeleuteHRlautHJM/>}}\n\nAlready, in 1954, Schehr's physical remains had been disinterred from their resting place in [[Marzahn|Berlin-Marzahn]] to the [[Zentralfriedhof Friedrichsfelde|Friedrichsfelde Main Cemetery]] where they were placed in the [[:de:Gedenkst\u00e4tte der Sozialisten|\"Gedenkst\u00e4tte der Sozialisten\"]], the special section reserved for heroes of socialism.<ref name=Gedenktafeln>{{cite web|url=https://www.gedenktafeln-in-berlin.de/nc/gedenktafeln/gedenktafel-anzeige/tid/opfer-des-nationalso-32/|title=Opfer des Nationalsozialismus|publisher=Gedenkst\u00e4tte Deutscher Widerstand , Berlin|work=Gedenktafeln an historischen Orten in Berlin|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!---\nwiki-de\n\n\n    Und schleppen sie in den dunklen Wald.\n    Und zw\u00f6lfmal knallt es und widerhallt.\n    Da liegen sie mit erloschenem Blick,\n    jeder drei Nahsch\u00fcsse im Genick,\n    John Schehr und Genossen.[5]\n\nSeit 1992 erinnert in Berlin in der N\u00e4he des Reichstags eine der 96 Gedenktafeln f\u00fcr von den Nationalsozialisten ermordete Reichstagsabgeordnete an Schehr. In Berlin-Prenzlauer Berg, Halle (Saale)-Radewell, Neubrandenburg, Pasewalk, Teltow, Rostock, Wei\u00dfenfels, Riesa, Wurzen und Lauchhammer sind Stra\u00dfen nach John Schehr benannt.\n\nAm Kilometerberg befindet sich ein Gedenkstein f\u00fcr John Schehr und die anderen Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer, die hier 1934 \u201eauf der Flucht erschossen\u201c wurden. Seit 1954 finden dort Gedenkveranstaltungen f\u00fcr die vier Widerstandsk\u00e4mpfer statt.[6]\n\nIn der ehemaligen Steigerkaserne am Drosselberg in Erfurt kann man noch heute einen John-Schehr-Gedenkstein sehen, eingefasst in einem kleinen Ehrenhain, gleich rechts hinter dem Eingangsgeb\u00e4ude. Allerdings wurden die Gedenkworte herausgemei\u00dfelt, so dass diese heute nur noch in Ans\u00e4tzen lesbar sind. In der Kaserne trug das hier stationierte MotSch\u00fctzenRegiment 24 den Ehrennamen \u201eJohn Schehr\u201c. \n\nHDK\n\n--->\n{{clear}}\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |35em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schehr, John}}\n\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hamburg]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Germany politicians]]<!---activist member but probably too young to count as \"a politician\".   Activist obsessives in the wiki community nevertheless regularly delete categories for SPD / USPD \"party members\", so \"politician\" is applied here as a default for those readers who think John Schehr's early party affiliations are worth flagging--->\n[[Category:Independent Social Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Germany members]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Prussia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Reichstag of the Weimar Republic]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Germany]]\n[[Category:Communists in the German Resistance]]\n[[Category:Resistance members killed by Nazi Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Schehr"}
